readme: # MEA: a Methylomic and Epigenomic Allele-specific analysis pipelineþþ![MEA Pipeline](doc/MEA-diagram.png)þþþBuilding on our previous work on the ALEA software package, a computational toolbox for allele-specific epigenomics analysis incorporating allelic variation data, we detail here ALEA’s successor - MEA. This package dramatically increases the functionality and usability of ALEA, incorporating allelic variation with existing resources, allowing for the identification of significant associations of epigenetic modifications and specific allelic variants in human and mouse cells. Similar to ALEA, MEA provides a customizable pipeline for allele-specific analysis of next-generation sequencing data which takes raw sequencing data for ChIP-seq, RNA-seq and DNA Methylation analysis, producing a UCSC track hub. MEA takes advantage of the available genomic resources for human (The 1000 Genomes Project Consortium) and mouse (The Mouse Genome Project) to reconstruct diploid in silico genomes for human samples or hybrid mouse samples. Then, for each accompanying ChIP-seq, RNA-seq or DNA Methylation dataset, MEA generates two wig files from short reads aligned differentially to each haplotype. This pipeline has been validated using human and hybrid mouse ChIPseq, RNAseq and DNA Methylation data (See [Test Data](#test-data)). þþ## Please refer to the MEA user guide (PDF) for installation and run instructionsþ  þ* [Docker installation](https://github.com/julienrichardalbert/MEA/raw/master/docker)  þ* [distribution package](https://github.com/julienrichardalbert/MEA/raw/master/dist/mea.1.0.tar.gz)þ* [documentation (PDF)](https://github.com/julienrichardalbert/MEA/raw/master/doc/MEA_UserGuide_v1.0.pdf)þ* test data: ftp://ftp.bcgsc.ca/supplementary/ALEA/files/test-data/þþþþ## CreditsþHamid Younesy, Torsten Möller, Alireza Heravi-Moussavi, Jeffrey B. Cheng, Joseph F. Costello, Matthew C. Lorincz, Mohammad M. Karimi and Steven J. M. Jones, "ALEA: a toolbox for allele-specific epigenomics analysis." Bioinformatics 30.8 (2014): 1172-1174. [[link to paper](http://bioinformatics.oxfordjournals.org/content/30/8/1172.long)]þþJulien Richard Albert, Tasuku Koike, Hamid Younesy, Richard Thompson, Aaron B. Bogutz, Mohammad M. Karimi and Matthew C. Lorincz, "Development and application of an integrated allele-specific pipeline for methylomic and epigenomic analysis (MEA)." BMC Genomics201819:463 (https://doi.org/10.1186/s12864-018-4835-2)

readme: # [![**Brooklyn**](https://brooklyn.apache.org/style/img/apache-brooklyn-logo-244px-wide.png)](http://brooklyn.apache.org/)þþ### Apache Brooklyn Server Sub-ProjectþþThis repo contains the core elements to run a Brooklyn server,þfrom the API and utils through to the core implementation and the REST server.þþ### Building the projectþþ2 methods are available to build this project: within a docker container or directly with maven.þþ#### Using dockerþþThe project comes with a `Dockerfile` that contains everything you need to build this project.þFirst, build the docker image:þþ```bashþdocker build -t brooklyn:server .þ```þþThen run the build:þþ```bashþdocker run -i --rm --name brooklyn-server -v ${HOME}/.m2:/root/.m2 -v ${PWD}:/usr/build -w /usr/build brooklyn:server mvn clean installþ```þþ#### Using mavenþþSimply run:þþ```bashþmvn clean installþ```

description: Hibernate Search: full-text search for domain model
readme: # Hibernate Searchþþ[![Maven Central](https://img.shields.io/maven-central/v/org.hibernate.search/hibernate-search-mapper-orm.svg?label=Maven%20Central&style=for-the-badge)](https://search.maven.org/search?q=g:%22org.hibernate.search%22)þ[![Build Status](https://img.shields.io/jenkins/build?jobUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fci.hibernate.org%2Fjob%2Fhibernate-search%2Fjob%2Fmaster%2F&style=for-the-badge)](https://ci.hibernate.org/job/hibernate-search/job/master)þ[![Coverage Status](https://img.shields.io/coveralls/github/hibernate/hibernate-search/master?logo=coveralls&style=for-the-badge)](https://coveralls.io/github/hibernate/hibernate-search?branch=master)þ[![Quality gate](https://img.shields.io/sonar/alert_status/org.hibernate.search:hibernate-search-parent?logo=sonarcloud&server=https%3A%2F%2Fsonarcloud.io&style=for-the-badge)](https://sonarcloud.io/dashboard?id=org.hibernate.search%3Ahibernate-search-parent)þ[![Language Grade: Java](https://img.shields.io/lgtm/grade/java/g/hibernate/hibernate-search.svg?logo=lgtm&logoWidth=18&style=for-the-badge)](https://lgtm.com/projects/g/hibernate/hibernate-search/context:java)þþ## DescriptionþþHibernate Search automatically extracts data from Hibernate ORM entities to push it toþlocal [Apache Lucene](http://lucene.apache.org/) indexesþor remote [Elasticsearch](https://www.elastic.co/products/elasticsearch) indexes.þþIt features:þþ* [**Declarative mapping**](https://docs.jboss.org/hibernate/search/6.0/reference/en-US/html_single/#mapper-orm-mapping)þof entity properties to index fields,þeither through annotations or a programmatic API.þ* [**On-demand mass indexing**](https://docs.jboss.org/hibernate/search/6.0/reference/en-US/html_single/#mapper-orm-indexing-massindexer)þof all entities in the database,þto initialize the indexes with pre-existing data.þ* [**On-the-fly automatic indexing**](https://docs.jboss.org/hibernate/search/6.0/reference/en-US/html_single/#mapper-orm-indexing-automatic)þof entities modified through a Hibernate ORM session,þto always keep the indexes up-to-date.þ* [**A Search DSL**](https://docs.jboss.org/hibernate/search/6.0/reference/en-US/html_single/#search-dsl)þto easily build full-text search queriesþand retrieve the hits as Hibernate ORM entities.þ* And more: [configuration of analyzers](https://docs.jboss.org/hibernate/search/6.0/reference/en-US/html_single/#concepts-analysis),þmany different [predicates](https://docs.jboss.org/hibernate/search/6.0/reference/en-US/html_single/#search-dsl-predicate)þand [sorts](https://docs.jboss.org/hibernate/search/6.0/reference/en-US/html_single/#search-dsl-sort)þin the Search DSL,þ[spatial support](https://docs.jboss.org/hibernate/search/6.0/reference/en-US/html_single/#mapper-orm-geopoint).þsearch queries returning [projections](https://docs.jboss.org/hibernate/search/6.0/reference/en-US/html_single/#search-dsl-projection)þinstead of entities,þ[aggregations](https://docs.jboss.org/hibernate/search/6.0/reference/en-US/html_single/#search-dsl-aggregation),þadvanced customization of the mapping using [bridges](https://docs.jboss.org/hibernate/search/6.0/reference/en-US/html_single/#mapper-orm-bridge),þ...þþFor example, map your entities like this:þþ```javaþ@Entityþ// This entity is mapped to an indexþ@Indexedþpublic class Book {þþ    // The entity ID is the document IDþ    @Idþ    @GeneratedValueþ    private Integer id;þþ    // This property is mapped to a document fieldþ    @FullTextField(analyzer = "english")þ    private String title;þþ    @ManyToManyþ    // Authors will be embedded in Book documentsþ    @IndexedEmbeddedþ    private Set<Author> authors = new HashSet<>();þþ    // Getters and settersþ    // ...þ}þþ@Entityþpublic class Author {þþ    @Idþ    @GeneratedValueþ    private Integer id;þþ    // This property is mapped to a document fieldþ    @FullTextField(analyzer = "name")þ    private String name;þþ    @ManyToMany(mappedBy = "authors")þ    private Set<Book> books = new HashSet<>();þþ    public Author() {þ    }þþ    // Getters and settersþ    // ...þ}þ```þþIndex existing data like this:þþ```javaþSearchSession searchSession = Search.session( entityManager );þMassIndexer indexer = searchSession.massIndexer( Book.class );þindexer.startAndWait();þ```þþAutomatic indexing does not require any change to code based on JPA or Hibernate ORM:þþ```javaþAuthor author = new Author();þauthor.setName( "Isaac Asimov" );þþBook book = new Book();þbook.setTitle( "The Caves Of Steel" );þbook.getAuthors().add( author );þauthor.getBooks().add( book );þþentityManager.persist( author );þentityManager.persist( book );þ```þþAnd search like this:þþ```javaþSearchResult<Book> result = Search.session( entityManager )þ        .search( Book.class )þ        .where( f -> f.match()þ                .fields( "title", "authors.name" )þ                .matching( "Isaac" )þ        )þ        .fetch( 20 );þþlong totalHitCount = result.getTotalHitCount();þList<Book> hits = result.getHits();þ```þþ## LicenseþþThis software and its documentation are distributed under the terms of the FSF Lesser GNU PublicþLicense (see lgpl.txt).þþ## Getting startedþþA getting started guide is availableþ[in the reference documentation](https://docs.jboss.org/hibernate/search/6.0/reference/en-US/html_single/#getting-started).þþFore more information, refer to the Hibernate Search website:þþ* [Available versions and compatibility matrix](http://hibernate.org/search/releases/)þ* [Reference documentation for all versions (current and past)](http://hibernate.org/search/documentation/)þþFor offline use, distribution bundles downloaded from [SourceForge](https://sourceforge.net/projects/hibernate/files/hibernate-search/)þalso include the reference documentation for the downloaded version in PDF and HTML format. þþ## Contactþþ### Latest DocumentationþþSee <http://hibernate.org/search/documentation/>.þþ### Bug ReportsþþSee the HSEARCH project on the Hibernate JIRA instance: <https://hibernate.atlassian.net/browse/HSEARCH>.þþ### Community SupportþþSee <http://hibernate.org/community/>.þþ## ContributingþþNew contributors are always welcome.þþSee [CONTRIBUTING.md](CONTRIBUTING.md) to get started.þþThe contribution guide also includes build instructions.

description: Programovací Jazyky 1
readme: # PJ1 - Programovací Jazyky 1þþ## Cíle předmětu vyjádřené dosaženými dovednostmi a kompetencemiþSeznámit studenty s možností tvorby objektově orientovaných aplikací v rámci platformy Java. Po absolvování předmětuþbude student schopen: þposoudit vhodnost platformy Java pro zamýšlenou aplikaci, þanalyzovat, navrhnout a implementovat aplikaci na platformě Java, þvyvíjet aplikace za použití rozhraní a znovupoužitelných komponent, þvyužít základních API platformy Java.þþ## Vyučovací metodyþþPřednáškyþIndividuální konzultaceþCvičení (v učebně)þExperimentální práce v laboratořiþProjektþOstatní aktivityþþ## AnotaceþJava technologie je důležitým hráčem při vývoji korporátních aplikací a aplikací pro Internet. Cílem kurzu je seznámitþstudenty se základními principy jazyka Java a objektově orientovaného programování stejně jako jim demonstrovatþmožnosti této technologie z hlediska vývoje aplikací za pomocí znovupoužitelných komponent.þþ## Povinná literatura:þBarnes, David J., and Michael Kolling. 2008.Objects First With Java: A Practical Introduction Using BlueJ. 4thþed. Prentice Hall.þPecinovský, Rudolf. 2005. JAVA 5.0 – Novinky jazyka a upgrade aplikací. Brno: Computer Press. http://knihy.pecinovsky.cz/java5novinky.þPecinovský, Rudolf. 2009. Myslíme objektově v jazyku JAVA. 2nd ed. GRADA Publishing.þþ## Doporučená literatura:þKOŽUSZNIK, Jan. Programming language 1. Opory k předmětu vzniklé v rámci projektu InterDV.þBruce Eckel: Thinking in Java, ISBN: 978-0131872486 þþJoshua Bloch: Effective Java, ISBN: 978-0321356680 þþDavid Flanagan: Programování v jazyce JAVA, ISBN: 80-85896-78-8 þMartin Fowler a kolektiv: Refaktoring - Zlepšení existujícího kódu, ISBN: 0-247-0299-1 þGrady Booch: Object-Oriented Analysis and Design with Applications. ISBN: 978-0201895513 þþHerout Pavel:Textbook of Java, ISBN: 978-80-7232-323-4 þþ## Způsob průběžné kontroly znalostí během semestruþOvěření znalostí na cvičeních prostřednictvím bodovaných úloh.þ## E-learningþ## Další požadavky na studentaþDalší požadavky na studenta nejsou kladeny.þ## Minimální znalostní požadavkyþ## PrerekvizityþþPředmět nemá žádné prerekvizity.þþ## KorekvizityþþPředmět nemá žádné korekvizity.þþ## Osnova předmětuþNáplň přednášek þþ* Úvod do jazyka Java. þ* Objektové rysy jazyka. þ* Vývoj samostatných aplikací. þ* Model událostí. þ* Grafické uživatelské rozhraní v Javě. þ* Kontejnery. þ* Generické typy a použití u kontejnerů. þ* Zpracování výjímek þ* Základní práce se soubory – vstup/výstup þ* Princip datových proudů. þ* Paralelismus a souběžná vlákna provádění programu. þ* Další pokročilejší aspekty technologie JAVA – java.lang.reflection, anotace. þ* Lambda výrazy, streamy, práce s časem a datem.þþNáplň počítačových cvičení:þ* Seznámení s vývojovým prostředím a spouštění JAVA aplikací. þ* Vytvoření a spuštění jednoduché konzolové JAVA aplikace - "Ahoj světe". þ* Realizace základních algoritmických a objektově orientovaných konstrukcí v JAVĚ. þ* Tvorba jednoduchých aplikací s grafickým uživatelským rozhraním. þ* Využití kontejnerů. þ* Implementace s generickými datovými typy. þ* Zpracování výjímek þ* Základní práce se soubory – vstup/výstup. þ* Využití datových proudů. þ* Programování pomocí vláken a jejich synchronizace. þ* Práce s java.lang.reflection a s anotacemi u tříd.þ* Základy GUI.

readme: # WorkbenchþCircleCI Test Status [![CircleCI Build Status](https://circleci.com/gh/all-of-us/workbench.svg)](https://circleci.com/gh/all-of-us/workflows/workbench)þþ## IntroductionþThe [All of Us Research Program](https://allofus.nih.gov/) Researcher Workbench is an application that runs on the [Terra platform](https://terra.bio) for researchers to work with *All of Us* program data in a secure and convenient way. It provides users with an environment for running Jupyter notebooksþin R or Python that can access data in the program's Curated Data Repository. For information on researchþopportunities see the [official website](https://allofus.nih.gov/get-involved/opportunities-researchers).þþWhile the code in this repository is available according to the terms of our [license](LICENSE.txt), not all featuresþare available for external use. In particular, it's not currently possible for third parties to build andþdeploy their own instance of the Researcher Workbench solely from the code here.þþ## Development Guidesþ[Documentation on API Structure](api/docs/code-structure.md)þþ[UI Style Guide](ui/docs/style-guide.md)þþ### Best Practices GuidesþMapStruct [Best Practices](api/docs/mapstruct.md) and [Tutorial](api/docs/tutorials/mapstruct-tutorial.md)þþ## Setup for Developmentþ* [Software Requirements](api/docs/developer-system-requirements.md)þ* [System Initialization](api/docs/developer-system-initialization.md)þ* [Intellij Setup](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1DtESBapEzvuti7xODTFPHorwmLM7LybF-6D5lhbIkLU/edit?usp=sharing)þ for UI, API, and tooling work.þþ## Development Processþ### Using GitþTo make changes, do:þþ```shellþgit checkout masterþgit pullþgit checkout -b <USERNAME>/<BRANCH_NAME>þ# (make changes and git add / commit them)þgit push -u origin <USERNAME>/<BRANCH_NAME>þ```þþAnd make a pull request in your browser atþhttps://github.com/all-of-us/workbench based on your upload.þþAfter responding to changes, merge in GitHub.þþ### APIþþ* Autoformat Java code via google-java-format: `./gradlew spotlessApply` (git pre-push / Circle will complain if you forget)þþ### UIþþ* Direct your editor to write swap files outside the source tree, so Webpackþdoes not reload when they're updated.þ[Example for vim](https://github.com/angular/angular-cli/issues/4593).þþ## Running the Dev Serversþþ### API: dev AppEngine appserverþþFrom the `api/` directory:þ```Shellþ./project.rb dev-upþ```þþWhen the console displays "Listening for transport dt_socket at address: 8001", yourþlocal API server endpoints are available under http://localhost:8081/.  You can test this byþnavigating to the [status endpoint](http://localhost:8081/v1/status) in your browser orþexecuting `curl http://localhost:8081/v1/status`þþ**Note:** If you haven't loaded any data locally for the app, please run the goal below. Also, this will not run while dev-up is running, so please kill dev-up first.þ```Shellþ./project.rb run-local-data-migrationsþ```þþOr you can run all migrations with:þ```Shellþ./project.rb run-local-all-migrationsþ```þYou can run the server (skipping config and db setup) by running:þþ```Shellþ./project.rb run-apiþ```þþOther available operations may be discovered by running:þ```Shellþ./project.rbþ```þþ#### API: Faster API startup for MacOSþThe above steps for starting the API server can take upwards of 8-10 minutes on MacOS, most likely due to performance issues with Docker for Mac. Follow these steps to set up your developer environment to start the API server outside of docker. A full restart should take ~30 seconds with this method.þþAll commands should be run from `workbench/api`þþ##### Setupþ* Install Java 8þ* Add following to `~/.bash_profile`. Note:þ    * Your Java8 library directory may be different.  þ      YOUR_WORKBENCH_DIRECTORY_PATH is the pathname to your workbench git repo.þ      ```Shellþ      export JAVA_HOME=/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/jdk1.8.0_201.jdk/Contents/Homeþ      export WORKBENCH_DIR=[YOUR_WORKBENCH_DIRECTORY_PATH]þ      source $WORKBENCH_DIR/api/db/load_vars.shþ      ```þ        * If you are using zsh, add the lines above to `~/.zshrc`.þ    * Source your bash profile or open a new terminalþ      ```Shellþ      source `~/.bash_profile`þ      ```þ* Install Java App Engine componentsþ    * ```Shellþ      gcloud components install app-engine-javaþ      ```þ* Generate Google Cloud access tokenþ    * ```Shellþ      ./project.rb get-test-service-credsþ      ```þþ##### Usageþ* If you have schema migrations or pending configuration updates, run through the [normal docker developer startup process](#api-dev-appengine-appserver) at least once successfully. This is typically only necessary when switching between branches.þ* Start services required for API serverþ    * ```Shellþ      ./project.rb start-api-reqsþ      # the counterpart command is ./project.rb stop-api-reqsþ      ```þ* Start API server through gradleþ    * ```Shellþ      ./gradlew appengineRunþ      ```þþ#### Hot Code SwappingþþWhile the API is running locally, saving a .java file should cause a recompile and reload of that class. Status is logged to the console. Not all changes reload correctly (e.g., model classes do not appear to reload more than once).þþ#### CaveatsþþThe first time a server is started after a database clear (`./project.rb docker-clean`), it may take some time for a billing project to become available for workspace creation. Generally, this takes about 5 minutes, but has been known to take upwards of 40 in some cases. The billing project buffer size is set to 2 for local environments (`config_local.json`). A cron job runs every minute while the API server is running to check if there are empty slots.þþTo check whether you have available billing projects:þ```Shellþ./project.rb connect-to-dbþselect * from billing_project_buffer_entry where status=2;þ```þþThe `status` column enum values can be found in `org.pmiops.workbench.db.model.StorageEnums`.þþ### UIþþBefore launching or testing the UI, yarn must first install the neccessary packages. From the `ui/` directory:þ```Shellþyarn installþ```þþTo launch the local UI:þ```Shellþyarn dev-upþ```þþYou can view your local UI server at http://localhost:4200/.  þþBy default, this connects to our test API server. Use `--configuration=$ENV` toþuse an alternate `src/environments/environment.$ENV.ts` file and connect to aþdifferent API server. To connect to your own API server running atþ`localhost:8081`, pass `--configuration=local`.þþTo run react UI tests:þ```Shellþyarn test-reactþ```þþOther useful yarn commands:þ```Shellþ# To upgrade yarn packages:þyarnþþ# To lint the UI and automatically fix issues:þyarn lint --fixþ```þþþ#### Legacy startupþYou can also run the UI through project.rb. NOTE: this is slower and not recommended.  þFrom the `ui/` directory,þ```Shellþ./project.rb dev-upþ```þþ[legacy] UI tests in Angular can be run and viewed at http://localhost:9876/index.html.þþOther available operations may be discovered by running:þ```Shellþ./project.rbþ```þþ#### You can regenerate classes from swagger withþþ```Shellþ./project.rb swagger-regenþ```þþ## DeployingþþTo deploy your local workbench API code to a given AppEngine project, in the apiþdirectory run:þþ```þ./project.rb deploy --project PROJECT --version VERSION --[no-]promoteþ```þþThis also migrates the SQL databases, so avoid using this when you have localþSQL schema changes.þþExample:þþ```þ./project.rb deploy --project all-of-us-workbench-test --version dantest --no-promoteþ```þþWhen the api is deployed, you'll be able to access it at https://VERSION-dot-api-dot-PROJECT.appspot.com. If you specify --promote, it will be the main API codeþserved out of https://api-dot-PROJECT.appspot.com.þAside from releases, this command can be used to test a topic branch in theþshared test project before submitting. If possible, push to a version with yourþown username and --no-promote.þþþTo deploy your local UI code to a given AppEngine project, in the uiþdirectory run:þþ```þ./project.rb deploy-ui --project PROJECT --version VERSION --[no-]promoteþ```þþExample:þþ```þ./project.rb deploy-ui --project all-of-us-workbench-test --version dantest --no-promoteþ```þþWhen the UI is deployed, you'll be able to access it at https://VERSION-dot-PROJECT.appspot.com. If you specify --promote, you can access it at https://PROJECT.appspot.com. Note that either way, it will be pointing at the live test APIþservice (https://api-dot-PROJECT.appspot.com). (This can be overridden locallyþin the Chrome console).þþ__NOTE:__ In order to test out a custom UI version in the browser, you must whitelist the base URL with the OAuth 2.0 client ID for the test Workbech environment. A common pattern is to use your GitHub username as the App Engine version name, so this setup only needs to be done once. See [this doc](https://docs.google.com/document/d/15-ktzL3Hdt5rpdFAS3z-v5vSNfk_LtjtPHCvbshjeZo/edit) for instructions.þþþ## API Server ConfigurationþþSpring application configs, in `application.properties` files, specify behaviorþlike logging. They are static files bundled with the built Java binary.þþDatabase connection information is read from `application-web.xml`. Theseþsecrets vary per-environment; Ruby setup scripts pull the values from GoogleþCloud Storage and generate the XML, which is then deployed with the Java binary.þþServer behavior configuration is stored in the database. It may be changedþwithout restarting the server, but is usually set only at deployment time. It'sþbased on config\_$ENV.json files (which are converted into `WorkbenchConfig`þobjects) and loaded into the database by `workbench.tools.ConfigLoader`.þþ`CacheSpringConfiguration`, a Spring `@Configuration`, providesþthe `@RequestScoped` `WorkbenchConfig`. It caches the values fetched from theþdatabase with a 10 minute expiration.þþ## API Server Database UpdatesþþLoading of local tables/data for both schemas (workbench/cdr) happens in a manual goal(creates tables in both schemas and insert any app data needed for local development):þþ```þ./project.rb run-local-all-migrationsþ```þþLocal tables loaded with data are:þ  * **workbench** - cdr_versionþ  * **cdr** - criteria, achilles_analysis, concept, concept_relationship, vocabulary, domain, achilles_results, achilles_results_concept and db_domainþþWhen editing database models, you must write a new changelog XML file. Seeþ[Liquibase change docs](http://www.liquibase.org/documentation/changes/index.html),þsuch as [createTable](http://www.liquibase.org/documentation/changes/create_table.html).þþYou can get Hibernate to update the schema for inspection (and then backportþthat to liquibase's XML files) by editing `api/db/vars.env` to make Hibernateþrun as the liquibase user and adding `spring.jpa.hibernate.ddl-auto=update`þto `api/src/main/resources/application.properties`.þþThen use `api/project.rb connect-to-db` and `SHOW CREATE TABLE my_new_table`.þRevert your changes or drop the db when you're done to verify the changelogþworks.þþFinally, write a new changelog file in `api/db/changelog/` and include it inþ`db.changelog-master.xml`.þþ`liquibase` does not roll back partially failed changes.þþWorkbench schema lives in `api/db` --> all workbench related activities access/persist data hereþþCDR schema lives in `api/db-cdr` --> all cdr/cohort builder related activities access/persist data hereþþ## Building a new CDR Databaseþ[Documented here](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1St6pG_EUFB9oRQUQaOSO7a9UPxPkQ5n4qAVyKF9j9tk/edit#)þþ## Special case cloud sql buildsþ#### Import sql dump locallyþ* DO NOT do this with production data. It is not allowed.þ* Make a sql dump from GCP and put in a specified bucketþ* Run `./project.rb local-mysql-import --sql-dump-file <FILE.sql> --bucket <BUCKET>`þþ#### Alternatively if you want to make a local database from csvs in gcs  þ * Run `./project.rb generate-local-count-dbs --cdr-version synth_r_2019q3_1 --bucket all-of-us-workbench-private-cloudsql/synth_r_2019q3_1/imported_to_cloudsql`þþ#### Put mysqldump of local mysql database in bucket for importing into cloudsql.þ`./project.rb mysqldump-local-db --db-name synth_r_2019q3_1 --bucket all-of-us-workbench-private-cloudsql`þþThen import a dump to cloudsql instance by specifying dump file in the --file option.þþ`./project.rb cloudsql-import --project all-of-us-workbench-test --instance workbenchmaindb --bucket all-of-us-workbench-private-cloudsql --database synth_r_2019q3_1 --file synth_r_2019q3_1.sql `þþ#### Import a dump to local mysql db.þ`./project.rb local-mysql-import --sql-dump-file synth_r_2019q3_1.sql --bucket all-of-us-workbench-private-cloudsql`þþ##### Resultþ* mysql db is in your local mysql for development. You need to alter your env per above to use it.þþþ## ElasticsearchþþElasticsearch is being integrated as an auxilliary backed on top of the BigQueryþCDR for cohort building. Currently it can only be run via docker-compose on aþlocal instance. See the full design:þhttps://docs.google.com/document/d/1N_TDTOi-moTH6wrXn1Ix4dwUlw4j8GT9OsL9yXYXYmY/editþþ### Indexingþþ```þ./project.rb load-es-indexþ```þþ### DevelopmentþþAs of 3/4/19, you'll need to enable Elasticsearch locally to utilize it in theþCohort Builder.þþ```þsed -i 's/\("enableElasticsearchBackend": \)false/\1true/' config/config_local.jsonþ```þþ#### Example criteriaþþCurrently the default setting for the indexer is to only index ~1000þto keep the local data size small. Some example criteria that will match thisþdefault dataset:þþ- Conditions ICD9: Group 250 Diabetes mellitusþ- Drugs: Acetaminophenþ- PPI: Anything (support for individual answers coming soon)þ- Procedures CPT: 99213þþ#### Elasticsearch Direct QueriesþþRequires that Elastic is running (via run-api or dev-up).þþShow the top 5 standard condition concept IDs:þþ```þcurl -H "Content-Type: application/json" "localhost:9200/cdr_person/_doc/_search?pretty" -d '{"size": 0, "aggs": {"aggs": {"terms": {"field": "condition_concept_ids", "size": 5 }}}}'þ```þþThe above IDs can be cross-referenced against the Criteria table in SQL orþBigQuery to determine cohort builder search targets.þþDump all participants matching a condition source concept ID (disclaimer: large):þþ```þcurl -H "Content-Type: application/json" "localhost:9200/cdr_person/_doc/_search?pretty" -d '{"query": {"term": {"condition_source_concept_ids": "44833466"}}}' > dump.jsonþ```þþ###þ## Cohort BuilderþþDuring ```./project dev-up``` the schema activity is the only activity run, which only creates tables for the cdr schema.þþLoading of cloud data for the criteria trees and cdr version happens in a manual goal(deletes and inserts tree data into the criteria table):þþ```./project.rb run-cloud-data-migrations```þþCDR Schema - We now have 2 activities in `api/db-cdr/build.gradle` file:þ```þliquibase {þ    activities {þ        schema {þ            changeLogFile "changelog/db.changelog-master.xml"þ            url "jdbc:mysql://${db_host}:${db_port}/cdr"þ            username "liquibase"þ            password "${liquibase_password}"þ        }þ        data {þ            changeLogFile "changelog-local/db.changelog-master.xml"þ            url "jdbc:mysql://${db_host}:${db_port}/cdr"þ            username "liquibase"þ            password "${liquibase_password}"þ        }þ        runList = project.ext.runListþ    }þ}þ```þþCDR Schema - In the `api/db-cdr/run-migrations.sh` for **local deployments** we call the liquibase update task with the specific activity name like so:þ```þecho "Upgrading database..."þ../gradlew update -PrunList=schemaþ```þþCDR Schema - In the `api/libproject/devstart.rb` for **test deployment** we call the liquibase update task with the specific activity name like so:þ```þctx.common.run_inline("#{ctx.gradlew_path} --info update -PrunList=schema")þ```þþ## Running test casesþþTo run both api and common api unit tests, in the api dir run:þþ```þ./project.rb testþ```þþTo run just api unit tests, run:þþ```þ./project.rb test-apiþ```þþTo run bigquery tests (which run slowly and actuallyþcreate and delete BigQuery datasets), run:þþ```þ./project.rb bigquerytestþ```þþBy default, all tests will return just test pass / fail output and stack traces for exceptions. To get full logging, pass on the command line --project-prop verboseTestLogging=yes when running tests.þþTo filter tests, use the [--tests flag](https://docs.gradle.org/current/userguide/java_testing.html#simple_name_pattern) on any test command:þþ```þ./project.rb bigquerytest --tests "org.pmiops.workbench.api.CohortBuilderControllerBQTest.countSubjectsNotValidMessageException"þ```þ### Running tests in IntelliJþþTo run tests in IntelliJ, go to your preferences, click plugins, and make sure you have the `JUnit` plugin installed.þþOnce you have JUnit installed, go to the test file you want to run, right click on the test file, and select `Run` or `Debug` to run or debug the tests. To run or debug on a specific test class or method, open the file, and test running options should appear as green triangles pointing right on the side bar. Clicking that will open a dialog allowing you to run that specific class or method.þþ### Debugging a Running API in IntelliJþþChoose `Edit Configurations...` from the dropdown at the left side of the top the menu barþand choose `Templates` -> `Remote`.  Click `Create configuration` in the top right.  Thisþwill create a Remote Configuration which you can name how you like.  Ensure that thisþconfiguration uses the port the API is listening on, *8001*.þþWhen this configuration is selected, clicking the debug icon (looks like a green bug) willþcause the running API process to stop at breakpoints you have set for inspection.þþ## DevOpsþThe `devops` toolkit is described [here](ops/ruby/devops-framework/README.md). Otherþdocumentation (including the playbook) is available for oncall engineers. This toolkitþis independent of the build and release system, and may be used by any GCP applicationþfor which they are useful.þþ## Manual Testingþþ### Backend Swagger PortalsþþThese are easiest if you need to authenticate as one of your researcher accounts.þþ- Firecloudþ  - dev: https://firecloud-orchestration.dsde-dev.broadinstitute.org/þ  - prod: https://api.firecloud.orgþ- Leo (notebook clusters)þ  - dev: https://leonardo.dsde-dev.broadinstitute.orgþ  - prod: https://notebooks.firecloud.orgþþ### Authenticated Backend Requests (CLI)þþThis approach is required if you want to issue a request to a backend as a service account. This may be necessary in some cases as the Workbench service is an owner on all AoU billing projects.þþThis approach requires [oauth2l](https://github.com/google/oauth2l) to be installed (and `brew install go` on MacOS):þþ```Shellþgo get github.com/google/oauth2lþgo install github.com/google/oauth2lþ```þþTo obtain the service account credentials, runþ```Shellþcd apiþgcloud auth login <user>@pmi-ops.org # for test environmentþgcloud config set account <user>@pmi-ops.org # also works if logged in.þgcloud auth list # confirm it's what you expectþ./project.rb get-test-service-creds # the dev-up command should also include this step.þ```þYou should see a file `sa-key.json` in the current directoryþThe following shows how to make an authenticated backend request as the sharedþworkbench test service account against Firecloud dev. It retrieves required authorizaitonþscopes of `email`, `profile`, and `cloud-billing`.þþ```Shellþ# From the "api" directory, use `oauth2l` to retrieve an authorization header:þ`~/go/bin/oauth2l header --json ./sa-key.json email profile cloud-billing`þ```þþNow we'll demonstrate calling Firecloud's [profile/billing API](https://api.firecloud.org/#!/Profile/billing)þwith the service account credentials.þ```Shellþ# call Firecloud Billing API, format the JSON output and view in lessþþcurl -X GET -H "`~/go/bin/oauth2l header --json ./sa-key.json email profile cloud-billing`" \þ    -H "Content-Type: application/json" \þ    "https://firecloud-orchestration.dsde-dev.broadinstitute.org/api/profile/billing" \þ    | jq | lessþþ# If you get 401 errors, you may need to clear your token cache.þoauth2l resetþ```þþ### Action Audit SystemþWe have a Stackdriver- and BigQuery-powered framework for user action auditing that supportsþflexible [queries](api/docs/action-audit-queries.md). Read more about its design, structure, andþimplementation in this [document](api/docs/action-audit.md).

readme: # titan.EclipsePlug-insþþThe Titan Eclipse plug-ins offer a TTCN-3 IDE for the Titan Execution environment.þTTCN-3 is a standardized, modular language specifically designed for testing. þEclipse Titan offers a free and open source (FOSS) compiler both for TTCN-3 and for þASN.1 (Abstract Syntax Notation One).þþ# Standards page (also including downloadable code):þþ* http://www.ttcn-3.org/þþ# Main project page:þþ* https://projects.eclipse.org/projects/tools.titanþþ## Introductory video of a presentation about Titan held at EclipseCon 2014: þ* https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2knzZuwzn-Y.þþ## Titan Datasheet on polarsys.org:þhttp://polarsys.org/sites/default/files/custom_uploads/TITAN%20Datasheet%20A4%202.1.pdfþþþ# Related products:þþ## Titan TTCN-3 Compiler and Executor þþ* https://github.com/eclipse/titan.coreþ þ## Titan test ports and protocol modulesþþlisted on the titan.core page þþ#Compressed update site and SHA512 checksum for the Eclipse plug-ins:þþ* https://projects.eclipse.org/projects/tools.titan/downloads

description: 华为 framework 源码
readme: # HwFrameWorkSourceþ## 本项目为华为 framework 源码合集：þ    þ    Mate10 EMUI 5.1 8.1.0þ    P9 EMUI 5.0 8.0.0þ    Mate20 EMUI 9.0.0 9.0.0þþ## framework 提取步骤：þþ### 1. 拷贝 framework 到本地目录：þþ```bashþ    adb pull /system/framework .þ```þþ### 2. 利用 [vdexExtractor](https://github.com/anestisb/vdexExtractor)工具将 *.vdex 转化为 dex 文件þþ```bashþ    vdexExtractor -i input_file -o . output_fileþ```þþ### 3. 利用 [jadx](https://github.com/skylot/jadx)将转化后的 dex 文件转化为 java 源码;þþ### 4. 编写脚本 convert.sh，请见 [convert.sh](https://github.com/SivanLiu/HwFrameWorkSource/blob/master/convert.sh)þþ### 5. 注意：þ- Android 9.0 dex2oat 生成的衍生文件（odex、vdex 和 cdex）, 其中 cdex 需要用到 [compact_dex_converter](https://github.com/anestisb/vdexExtractor/blob/master/tools/deodex/run.sh) þ- compact_dex_converter 工具可以将 cdex 转化为标准的 dex，再用最新的 jadx 转化成 java 源码，旧版本的 jadx 转化可能有问题，建议自己编译最新的源码使用； þ- run.sh 会去 one.drive下载 compact_dex_converter，速度太慢，自己可以先根据 [constants.sh](https://github.com/anestisb/vdexExtractor/blob/master/tools/deodex/constants.sh) 中的网址下载解压后放到对应的目录：þ[linux](https://onedrive.live.com/download?cid=D1FAC8CC6BE2C2B0&resid=D1FAC8CC6BE2C2B0%21581&authkey=AE_kzPqzG_-R4T0)、[mac](https://onedrive.live.com/download?cid=D1FAC8CC6BE2C2B0&resid=D1FAC8CC6BE2C2B0%21580&authkey=ADMmFqIo6bj7X5Y)þ    þ    其中 linux 路径:þ ```groovyþ vdexExtractor/tools/deodex/hostTools/Linux/api-API_28þ```þþ- 将 run.sh 中 deps_prepare_env "$apiLevel" 一行注释掉就会使用本地已经下载好的依赖þþ### 6. 将脚本放到 framework 目录下修改权限，执行即可þþ参考链接：<https://github.com/dstmath/HWFramework>

description: Apache Cassandra, supplying tools for Scylla
readme: Apache Cassandraþ-----------------þþApache Cassandra is a highly-scalable partitioned row store. Rows are organized into tables with a required primary key.þþhttp://wiki.apache.org/cassandra/Partitioners[Partitioning] means that Cassandra can distribute your data across multiple machines in an application-transparent matter. Cassandra will automatically repartition as machines are added and removed from the cluster.þþhttp://wiki.apache.org/cassandra/DataModel[Row store] means that like relational databases, Cassandra organizes data by rows and columns. The Cassandra Query Language (CQL) is a close relative of SQL.þþFor more information, see http://cassandra.apache.org/[the Apache Cassandra web site].þþRequirementsþ------------þ. Java >= 1.8 (OpenJDK and Oracle JVMS have been tested)þ. Python 2.7 (for cqlsh)þþGetting startedþ---------------þþThis short guide will walk you through getting a basic one node cluster upþand running, and demonstrate some simple reads and writes. For a more-complete guide, please see the Apache Cassandra website's http://cassandra.apache.org/doc/latest/getting_started/[Getting Started Guide].þþFirst, we'll unpack our archive:þþ  $ tar -zxvf apache-cassandra-$VERSION.tar.gzþ  $ cd apache-cassandra-$VERSIONþþAfter that we start the server. Running the startup script with the -f argument will causeþCassandra to remain in the foreground and log to standard out; it can be stopped with ctrl-C.þþ  $ bin/cassandra -fþþ****þNote for Windows users: to install Cassandra as a service, downloadþhttp://commons.apache.org/daemon/procrun.html[Procrun], set theþPRUNSRV environment variable to the full path of prunsrv (e.g.,þC:\procrun\prunsrv.exe), and run "bin\cassandra.bat install".þSimilarly, "uninstall" will remove the service.þ****þþNow let's try to read and write some data using the Cassandra Query Language:þþ  $ bin/cqlshþþThe command line client is interactive so if everything worked you shouldþbe sitting in front of a prompt:þþ----þConnected to Test Cluster at localhost:9160.þ[cqlsh 2.2.0 | Cassandra 1.2.0 | CQL spec 3.0.0 | Thrift protocol 19.35.0]þUse HELP for help.þcqlsh> þ----þþAs the banner says, you can use 'help;' or '?' to see what CQL has toþoffer, and 'quit;' or 'exit;' when you've had enough fun. But lets tryþsomething slightly more interesting:þþ----þcqlsh> CREATE SCHEMA schema1 þ       WITH replication = { 'class' : 'SimpleStrategy', 'replication_factor' : 1 };þcqlsh> USE schema1;þcqlsh:Schema1> CREATE TABLE users (þ                 user_id varchar PRIMARY KEY,þ                 first varchar,þ                 last varchar,þ                 age intþ               );þcqlsh:Schema1> INSERT INTO users (user_id, first, last, age) þ               VALUES ('jsmith', 'John', 'Smith', 42);þcqlsh:Schema1> SELECT * FROM users;þ user_id | age | first | lastþ---------+-----+-------+-------þ  jsmith |  42 |  john | smithþ cqlsh:Schema1> þ----þþIf your session looks similar to what's above, congrats, your single nodeþcluster is operational! þþFor more on what commands are supported by CQL, seeþhttp://cassandra.apache.org/doc/latest/cql/[the CQL reference]. Aþreasonable way to think of it is as, "SQL minus joins and subqueries, plus collections."þþWondering where to go from here?þþ  * Join us in #cassandra on irc.freenode.net and ask questionsþ  * Subscribe to the Users mailing list by sending a mail toþ    user-subscribe@cassandra.apache.orgþ  * Visit the http://cassandra.apache.org/community/[community section] of the Cassandra website for more information on getting involved.

MASON Multiagent Simulation Toolkit
readme: # Build MASON Toolkitþþ## Build Core MASON OnlyþþInside the folder mason/mason:þþ```bashþmvn clean installþ```þþThe output should say:þþ```[INFO] BUILD SUCCESS```þþþ## Import in Eclipseþþ1. Clone the project on your local machine, and import the Maven project.þþ```þFile-> Import -> Existing Maven Projects -> Root Directoryþ```þþ2. Build and Install on the mason-build project.þþ```þRun as -> Maven installþ```þþþ## Build MASON with 3dþþTo use MASON in 3D, you must install Java3D. Unfortunately, installing Java3D is not as easy as it once was. You can try [Oracle's older distribution](http://www.oracle.com/technetwork/java/javase/tech/index-jsp-138252.html), but you may have more luck, particularly recent OS X version users, in installing Java3D and JOGL directly from the [jogamp website](http://jogamp.org/). To do this, you'll need to install three [Java3D libraries](http://jogamp.org/deployment/java3d/) (j3dcore.jar, j3dutils.jar, and vecmath.jar), and a few [JOGL libraries](http://jogamp.org/deployment/) (gluegen-rt.jar gluegen-rt-natives-your-platform.jar, joal.jar, joal-all-natives-your-platform.jar, jogl-all.jar, and jogl-natives-your-platform.jar — look in a recent version directory like v2.1.4/jar; the jogamp-current/jar directory often has broken files).þþOften the Java3D libraries are buggy and in flux for OS X users, so I've made a collection [here](https://cs.gmu.edu/~eclab/projects/mason/j3dlibs.zip) for OS X which seems to work okay. Install these in your system-wide Java library location (on the Mac, it's /Library/Java/Extensions/). For more instructions, see [this posting](http://gouessej.wordpress.com/2012/08/01/java-3d-est-de-retour-java-3d-is-back/).

description: Visualization and analysis software for Hi-C data -
readme: --------------þAbout Juiceboxþ--------------þJuicebox is visualization software for Hi-C data. This distribution includes the source code for Juicebox, Juicer Tools, and Assembly Tools. Download Juicebox here, or use Juicebox on the web. Detailed documentation is available on the wiki. Instructions below pertain primarily to usage of command line tools and the Juicebox jar files.þþJuicebox can now be used to visualize and interactively (re)assemble genomes. þCheck out the Juicebox Assembly Tools Module website https://aidenlab.org/assembly for þmore details on how to use Juicebox for assembly.þþþJuicebox was created by Jim Robinson,þNeva C. Durand, and Erez Lieberman Aiden. Past contributors include Ido Machol, Zulkifl Gire, Marie Hoeger, Fanny Huang, Nam Hee Kim, Vi Nguyen, Jay Ryu, Nathaniel T. Musial, and Ragib Mostofa.þþOngoing development work is carried out by Muhammad Saad Shamim, Neva C. Durand, and Olga Dudchenko.þþ--------------þQuestions?þ--------------þþFor FAQs, or for asking new questions, please see our forum: aidenlab.org/forum.html.þþ--------------þIntelliJ Setupþ--------------þþUse IntelliJ IDEA (Community edition - free)þþTo set up in IDEA, have the Java SDK installedþthen you'll point to it (IntelliJ has lots of documentation on this sort of thing).þþ* Then go to `VCS` -> `checkout from version control`.þ* You'll need to do is be sure `*.sizes` is included as a file to be copied over to the class files.þSet this up via IntelliJ `Preferences` -> `Compiler`. Add `?*.sizes` to the list of `Resource Patterns`.þ* While there, also go to `Java Compiler` and put this into additional command line options: `-Xlint:all -target 1.7`þThe former turns on all warnings, the latter gives some flexibility since some people haven't updated Java to 1.8 yet.þ* Then go to `Run` -> `Edit Configurations`.þ* With the `+` sign, add `Application`.þ* You'll create two of these, one for the GUI (call it Juicebox GUI or whatever you want, really) and one for the CLT.þ* Set the main class by clicking the little `...` button next to the text box for main classþþ MainWindow.java is the main method class for the visualization/GUI portion of the software.þ HiCTools.java is the main method class for the analysis/CLT portion.þþ* For the GUI under VM Options:þþ -Xmx2000mþ -Djnlp.loadMenu="https://hicfiles.tc4ga.com/juicebox.properties"þþ* For the CLT useþþ -Xmx2000mþþ* Note that the `Xmx2000m` flag sets the maximum memory heap size to 2GB.þDepending on your computer you might want more or less.þSome tools will break if there's not enough memory and the file is too large,þbut don't worry about that for development; 2GB should be fine.þ* One last note: be sure to `Commit and Push` when you commit files, it's hidden in the dropdown menu button in theþcommit window.þþ----------------------------------þHardware and Software Requirementsþ----------------------------------þThe minimum software requirement to run Juicebox is a working Java installationþ(version > 1.6) on Windows, Linux, and Mac OSX. We recommend using the latestþJava version available, but please do not use the Java Beta Version. Minimumþsystem requirements for running Java can be found atþhttps://java.com/en/download/help/sysreq.xml. To download and install the latestþJava Runtime Environment (JRE), please go to https://www.java.com/download.þþWe recommend having at least 2GB free RAM for the best user experience withþJuicebox.þþTo launch the Juicebox application from command line, typeþ java -Xms512m -Xmx2048m -jar Juicebox.jarþþNote: the -Xms512m flag sets the minimum memory heap size at 512 megabytes, andþthe -Xmx2048m flag sets the maximum size at 2048 megabytes (2 gigabytes). Theseþvalues may be adjusted as appropriate for your machine.þþ-------------þDocumentationþ-------------þWe have extensive documentation for how to use Juicebox atþhttps://github.com/theaidenlab/juicebox/wiki including a video, a Quick Start Guide, and aþdetailed tutorial.þþFor using Juicebox to assemble genomes see https://www.aidenlab.org/assembly/.þþ------------------------þCommand Line Tools Usageþ------------------------þþSee the documentation at https://github.com/theaidenlab/juicer/wiki for informationþon how to use the Juicer tools.þþ--------------------------------þCompiling Jars from Source Filesþ--------------------------------þ1. You should have Java 1.8 JDK and Apache Ant installed on your system. Seeþ below for more information.þ2. Go to the folder containing the Juicebox source files and edit theþ juicebox.properties file with the proper Java JDK Address.þ3. Open the command line, navigate to the folder containing the build.xml fileþ and typeþ antþ The process should take no more than a minute to build on most machines.þ4. The jars are written to the directory out/. You can change this by editingþ the build.xml file.þþ* Installing Java 1.8 JDKþþFor Windows/Mac/Linux, the Java 1.8 JDK can be installed from here:þhttps://www.oracle.com/technetwork/java/javase/downloads/jdk8-downloads-2133151.htmlþ(Alternative) For Ubuntu/LinuxMintþhttps://tecadmin.net/install-oracle-java-8-jdk-8-ubuntu-via-ppa/þþ* Installing Apache AntþMacþ Ant should be installed on most Macs. To verify installation via the commandþ prompt, typeþ ant -versionþ If Ant is not on your Mac, install it via homebrew. At the command prompt, typeþ brew updateþ brew install antþ You may need to install Homebrew (https://brew.sh/) on your machineþ See the following Stackoverflow post for more details:þ https://stackoverflow.com/questions/3222804/how-can-i-install-apache-ant-on-mac-os-xþþWindowsþ Installing Ant requires some minor changes to your system environment. Followþ the instructions in this article:þ https://www.nczonline.net/blog/2012/04/12/how-to-install-apache-ant-on-windows/þþLinuxþ In the command prompt, typeþ sudo apt-get install antþ orþ sudo yum install antþ depending on your package installer

description: Android DroneKit implementation
readme: # DroneKit-Androidþþ![dronekit_python_logo](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/5368500/10805537/90dd4b14-7e22-11e5-9592-5925348a7df9.png)þþ[![Build Status](https://travis-ci.org/dronekit/dronekit-android.svg?branch=develop)](https://travis-ci.org/dronekit/dronekit-android)þ[![Issue Stats](http://issuestats.com/github/dronekit/DroneKit-Android/badge/pr)](http://issuestats.com/github/dronekit/DroneKit-Android)þ[![Issue Stats](http://issuestats.com/github/dronekit/DroneKit-Android/badge/issue)](http://issuestats.com/github/dronekit/DroneKit-Android) þþþDroneKit-Android helps you create powerful Android apps for UAVs.þþþ## Overviewþþ[DroneKit-Android](http://android.dronekit.io/) is the implementation of [DroneKit](http://dronekit.io/) on Android.þþThe API provides interfaces that apps can use to control copters, planes, and ground vehicles. It is compatible with vehicles that communicate using the MAVLink protocol (including most vehicles made by 3DR and other members of the DroneCode foundation), and is validated against the open-source [ArduPilot flight control platform](http://ardupilot.com).þþThis project implements the [DroneKit-Android Client library](http://android.dronekit.io) which allows developers to leverage the DroneKit API.þþ## Getting StartedþþThe [Getting Started](http://android.dronekit.io/getting_started.html) guide explains how to set up a DroneKit project in Android Studio, and start the autopilot simulator (SITL) for testing during development.þþOnce you've got DroneKit set up, the [First App: Hello Drone](http://android.dronekit.io/first_app.html) tutorial provides a step-by-step guide to creating a basic DroneKit-Android app and connecting it to a vehicle. þþ### ExamplesþþSource code and documentation for some of the apps built with DroneKit is linked below:þ* [Tower](https://github.com/DroidPlanner/Tower)þ* [Tower-Wear](https://github.com/DroidPlanner/tower-wear)þ* [Tower-Pebble](https://github.com/DroidPlanner/dp-pebble) ([documentation here](http://android.dronekit.io/pebble_app.html))þþþ## ResourcesþþProject documentation is provided at http://android.dronekit.io/. This includes getting stated and tutorial material, and has links to [examples](#examples) and the full [Javadoc](http://android.dronekit.io/javadoc/) API Reference.þþThe [DroneKit Forums](http://discuss.dronekit.io) are the best place to ask for technical support on how to use the library. You can also check out our [Gitter channel](https://gitter.im/dronekit/dronekit-android) though we prefer posts on the forums where possible.þþ* **Documentation:** http://android.dronekit.io/þ * **API Reference:** http://android.dronekit.io/javadoc/þ * **Examples:** http://android.dronekit.io/resources.html#example-appsþ* **Forums:** [http://discuss.dronekit.io/](http://discuss.dronekit.io)þ* **Gitter:** https://gitter.im/dronekit/dronekit-android (we prefer posts on the forums!)þþþ## Users and contributors wanted!þþWe'd love your [feedback and suggestions](https://github.com/dronekit/dronekit-android/issues) about this API and are eager to evolve it to meet your needs, please feel free to create an issue to report bugs or feature requests.þþWe welcome all types of contributions but mostly contributions that would help us shrink our þ[issues list](https://github.com/dronekit/dronekit-android/issues).þþþ## Licenceþþ[DroneKit-Android Client library](http://android.dronekit.io) is made available under the permissive open source [Apache 2.0 License](https://github.com/dronekit/dronekit-android/blob/develop/ClientLib/LICENSE).þþ***þþCopyright 2015 3D Robotics, Inc.

description: Simple Matlab/Octave based framework for building Brain Computer/Machine Interfaces (BCI/BMI)s
readme: # Buffer BCIþþBuffer BCI is a platform independent and language agnostic frameworkþfor building Brain Computer Interface experiements.  It is based on aþ*client-server architecture* with multiple clients getting and puttingþdata to a centeral data and events server.  The server is based on theþ[fieldtrip buffer](http://fieldtrip.fcdonders.nl/development/realtime)þspecificitation for data access and storage. þþThe server is available for Mac, Linux and Windows and languageþbindings are provided the following programming languages Matlab,þOctave, Java, Python, C\# and c.  For Matlab and Octave additionalþsignal-analysis, classification and example demonstration BCIs areþprovided.  A summary of the language feature support is:þ* C#, java, Python, c : support for accessing data and eventsþ* Octave : with Octave_java, support for accessing data and events. Support of processing of data.  Graphics supportd depends on the graphics toolkit available, viz. Qthandles=full support, fltk=data visualization, gnuplot=no graphics.þ* Matlab : R>7.4, full support for accessing data and events, signal analysis, data visualization and GUI control.þþ## Important Note:þþThis is a *client-server architecture*.  Thus to use any of the demos or run time you need at least:þ1. a server running (the 'buffer') and two clients: þ2. a data-acquisation client which interfaces with the hardware to send data to the server, þ3. an application client which does something with the received data, like showing it on the screen.þþFurther different clients may be written in different programming languages and hence have different dependences.  As a minimum many of the clients interfacing with signal measurement hardware are written in java (specificially: the MUSE and openBCI clients) hence you will need a working java run-time to use these devices.  Further, most of the demonstration systems are written in Matlab/Octave, so you will need to install these systems to run these demos – though check the java, python and csharp directories for demonstrations written in those languages.þþ## Installation: GeneralþþCopy these directories somewhere on your local drive.þþNote: If using MATLAB/Octave and the .bat/.sh files do not work because the MATLAB/Octave executable is not found automatically then modify the path in the file [`utilities\findMatlab.bat`](utilities/findMatlab.bat) (windows) or [`utilities/findMatlab.sh`](utilities/findMatlab.sh) (Linux/MacOSX) to point to the executable location.þþ### Installation: Octave+WindowsþWhen using Matlab/Octave this code relies on java for network communication between processes.  Matlab includes a JRE internally, for octave you must download and install the *correct* JRE first.  These are specific instructions for that case:þþ1) First install java *32bit*.  Note: with the current version of octave is *must* be the 32bit java version, e.g. from <https://www.java.com/en/download/manual.jsp>, which is not what you get by default if you just 'download java'.þþ2) Then install / setup octave.  You can find a binary installer here <https://ftp.gnu.org/gnu/octave/windows/>.  This should then auto-detect the java install and setup the java environment.þþ3) Check your octave-java install with: usejava('jvm') at the octave command line, which should return 1.þþ### Installation : MacOSþþ*MacOS* to run the *.sh files from the finder you need to set them to open with the *Terminal* application (which is in the utilities sub-directory of applications).  Set this by Control-clicking any .sh file and choosing 'Open With' then browse to the *Terminal* application and choose open all .sh files this way.þþ### Installation : Linuxþþ*Linux* to run the *.sh files from Nautilus, the Gnome file manager, you need to set it to run 'executable text files' directly.  To do this goto: Files->Preferences, open the Behaviour tab and in the 'Executable Text Files' set it to either 'Run them' (potential security risk) or 'Ask what to do' (safer).þþ## QuickStartþþRead the `README` file in either of the [`games`](matlab/games), [`EEGBCITutorial`](tutorial/EEGBCITutorial), [`imaginedMovement`](matlab/imaginedMovement), [`matrixSpeller`](matlab/matrixSpeller) directories for instructions on how to startup and runþthose demos.  (Note: all demos require Matlab/Octave_java+QtHandles toþrun correctly!)þþTo run the [games](matlab/games) demo:þþ1. Start the data Acquisation system.þþ If you have *no* EEG hardware, but just want to test:þþ  1. start a buffer by running: [`dataAcq/startJavaBuffer.bat`](dataAcq/startJavaBuffer.bat) or [`dataAcq/startJavaBuffer.sh`](dataAcq/startJavaBuffer.sh)  þ  2. start a *simulated* data source by running: [`dataAcq/startJavaSignalProxy.bat`](dataAcq\startJavaSignalProxy.bat) or [.sh](dataAcq/startJavaSignalProxy.sh)þþORþ  Start a complete simulated EEG system in one step using [`debug_quickstart.bat`](debug_quickstart.bat) or [`debug_quickstart.sh`](debug_quickstart.sh)þþ If you have EEG hardware connected then depending on the hardware:þþ  1. start a buffer by running: [`dataAcq/startJavaBuffer.bat`](dataAcq/startJavaBuffer.bat) or [`dataAcq/startJavaBuffer.sh`](dataAcq/startJavaBuffer.bat)  þ  2. start appropriate acquisition driver for your device:þ    * TMSi Mobita:       [`dataAcq/startMobita.bat`](dataAcq\startMobita.bat)  or  `dataAcq/startMobita.sh`  þ    * Emotiv Epoc:        `dataAcq/startEmotiv.bat`  or  `dataAcq/startEmotiv.sh`  þ    * Biosemi Active 2:   `dataAcq/startBiosemi.bat` or  `dataAcq/startBiosemi.sh`þ    * Interaxon Muse:     `dataAcq/startMuse.bat`    or  `dataAcq/startMuse.sh`  þþNote: By default raw data is saved to:  þ*  *MacOS/Linux*: `~/output/test/_YYMMDD_/_HHMM_/raw_buffer/0001`  þ*  *Windows*: `C:\output\test\_YYMMDD_\_HHMM_\raw_buffer\0001`  þ   where `_YYMMDD_` is the date in year/month/day format, `_HHMM_` is start time hour and minutesþþ2. Start the Matlab/Octave based signal processing process by running: [`matlab/games/startSigProcBuffer.bat`](matlab/games/startSigProcBuffer.bat) or [`.sh`](matlab/games/startSigProcBuffer.sh)þþ3. Start the Matlab/Octave based experiment control & stimulus presentation system by running : [`matlab/games/runGame.bat`](matlab/games/runGame.bat) or [`runGame.sh`](matlab/games/runGame.sh)þþ4. Type in the subject name to the experiment control window, and then run through each of the experiment phases: þþ  * Practice -- practice the task to be used in the BCI.  Green arrows indicate target locations you should attend to by counting the white and red arrow 'flashes'þþ  * Calibration -- get calibration data by attending as instructed for ~90secondsþþ  * Classifier Training -- train a classifier using the calibration data.  3 windows will pop-up showing: Per-class ERPs, per-class AUCs, and cross-validated classification performance.þþ5. Select the game you would like to play!þþ## Folder StructureþþAn overview of the included directories is:þ*  [`dataAcq`](dataAcq) -- code for data acquisition, i.e. interfacing to recording hardware, based on the [field-trip buffer specification](http://fieldtrip.fcdonders.nl/development/realtime).þ     Also scripts (.bat for windows, .sh for Linux/Mac) for starting the executablesþ*  [`matlab`](matlab)  -- example BCIs written in the [MATLAB](http://www.mathworks.com) language also compatiable with the free+open-source [OCTAVE](http://www.gnu.org/software/octave) system.þ*  [`c`](c) -- example BCIs written the raw cþ*  [`python`](python) -- example BCIs written in the [Python](http://www.python.org) programming languageþ*  [`java`](java) -- example BCI writen in the [java](http://www.oracle.com/java) programming languageþ*  [`csharp`](csharp) -- example BCIs written in the [C#](https://msdn.microsoft.com/en-us/library/67ef8sbd.aspx) programming languageþ*  [`unity`](unity) -- example BCIs writtin in the [unity](http://unity3d.com) game development environmentþ*  [`tutorial`](tutorial) -- Tutorial on BCI and how to use buffer_bci arranged in lectures 1 through 5 about how BCIs work, the structure and components of a BCI and how to build a standard BCI with the buffer_bci frameworkþþ## Main example BCI systemsþþ* [`tutorial/EEGBCITutorial`](tutorial/EEGBCITutorial) -- Tutorial on how to use an EEG BCI, including general experience on EEG signals, and two simple BCIs; imagined-movements, and a visual-p300 speller.þ     þ*  [`matlab/imaginedMovement`](matlab/imaginedMovement) -- Example BCI system for controlling a cursor using an imagined movement (ERSP) type BCIþþ*  [`matlab/matrixSpeller`](matlab/matrixSpeller) -- Example BCI system for spelling characters using a visual matrix-speller (p300) type BCIþþ*  [`matlab/matrixSpellerPTB`](matlab/matrixSpellerPTB) -- Example BCI system for spelling characters using a visual matrix-speller (p300) type BCI.  This version uses PsychToolBox to improve the timing of the visual stimulus rendering.  þ    N.B. to use this you will need to set the PTB path correctly in `utilities/initPTBPaths.m`þþ*  [`matlab/cursorControl`](matlab/cursorControl) -- Example BCI system for controlling a cursor in 2-d using visual evoked response (ERP) type BCI

readme: ![Psylla logo](src/logo/psylla-64.png)þþ# Psyllaþþ**Psylla** is a scriptable interpretive concatenative homoiconic PostScript-like programming language.þþPsylla is implemented as a library written in Java.þþ[![License](https://img.shields.io/badge/license-zlib%2Fpng-blue.svg)](http://opensource.org/licenses/Zlib)þ[![Build Status](https://secure.travis-ci.org/urbic/psylla.png)](http://travis-ci.org/urbic/psylla)þþ## Featuresþþ* Dynamic arrays, strings, dictionaries and setsþ* Complex numbersþ* Multicontext execution (multithreading), synchronization primitives, blocking queuesþ* Regular expressions _— under construction_þ* REPLþ* Support for Java scripting APIþþ## Dependenciesþþ### Jar:þþJava 8 (OpenJDK or Oracle JDK), JavaCC, Apache Ant, JUnit, JLineþþ### Documentation:þþApache Ant, Docbook 5 XSL, Saxon 6, XSLTHL, SASS, Graphviz, Perl

readme: # þþ[![Codacy Badge](https://api.codacy.com/project/badge/Grade/30ecd0d9ba8a4561a60335644b592418)](https://www.codacy.com/gh/metasfresh/metasfresh?utm_source=github.com&utm_medium=referral&utm_content=metasfresh/metasfresh&utm_campaign=Badge_Grade)þ[![release](https://img.shields.io/badge/release-5.144-blue.svg)](https://github.com/metasfresh/metasfresh/releases/tag/5.144)þ[![Gitter](https://img.shields.io/gitter/room/nwjs/nw.js.svg)](https://gitter.im/metasfresh)þ[![license](https://img.shields.io/badge/license-GPL-blue.svg)](https://github.com/metasfresh/metasfresh/blob/master/LICENSE.md)þþ![Twitter Follow](https://img.shields.io/twitter/follow/metasfresh?style=social)þþþmetasfresh is a responsive, Free and Open Source ERP System. Our aim is to create fast and easy-to-use enterprise software with an outstanding user experience.þþ> **__We do Open Source ERP__**þþEquipped with wide and detailed functionality, metasfresh fits for companies from industry and trade that are searching business software that provides high scalability and flexibility.þþIt has a 3-tier architecture with Rest-API and a Web User Frontend developed in HTML5/ ReactJS/ Redux.þþ![metasfresh-sales-order](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/13365687/36896187-f5ed2e48-1e11-11e8-9c41-a7878c148f81.gif)þþ þþ## InstallationþWe publish a stable Release of metasfresh each Friday - ok, we skip 1 week at the end of the year ;) . It can be downloaded [here](http://metasfresh.com/en/download/).þþmetasfresh can be installed via **Docker** or **Ubuntu Installer**þþ**Docker** [How do I setup the metasfresh stack using Docker?](http://docs.metasfresh.org/howto_collection/EN/How_do_I_setup_the_metasfresh_stack_using_Docker.html)þþ**Ubuntu** [How do I install metasfresh using the Installation package?](http://docs.metasfresh.org/installation_collection/EN/installer_how_do_install_metasfresh_package.html)þþ>**First steps:**þ>- [How do I log on?](http://docs.metasfresh.org/webui_collection/EN/Logon.html)þ>- [How do I change the Interface Language?](http://docs.metasfresh.org/webui_collection/EN/SwitchLanguage)þ>- [How do I Setup my Company?](http://docs.metasfresh.org/webui_collection/EN/InitialSetupWizard)þ>- [How do I create my first Sales Order?](http://docs.metasfresh.org/webui_collection/EN/SalesOrder_recording)þ>- [How do I create my first Shipment?](http://docs.metasfresh.org/webui_collection/EN/Ship_SalesOrder)þ>- [How do I create my first Invoice?](http://docs.metasfresh.org/webui_collection/EN/Invoice_SalesOrder)þþ## DocumentationþIf you are new to metasfresh and would like to learn more, then you can find our documentation here:þþ- [Admins](http://docs.metasfresh.org/pages/installation/index_en)þ- [Users](http://docs.metasfresh.org/pages/webui/index_en)þ- [Developers](http://docs.metasfresh.org/index.html)þ- [Tester](http://docs.metasfresh.org/pages/tests/index_en)þþ## DiscussionþJoin one of the gitter rooms [metasfresh](https://gitter.im/metasfresh/metasfresh), [metasfresh-webui-frontend](https://gitter.im/metasfresh/metasfresh-webui-frontend), [metasfresh-documentation](https://gitter.im/metasfresh/metasfresh-documentation) or visit us in our [forum](https://forum.metasfresh.org/).þþ## ContributingþDo you want to help improving documentation, contribute some code or participate in functional requirements. That's great, you're welcome! Please read our [Code of Coduct](https://github.com/metasfresh/metasfresh/blob/master/CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md) and [Contibutor Guidelines](https://github.com/metasfresh/metasfresh/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md) first.þþ### "Monorepo"þTo check out only certain parts of this repository, we recomment to get git version 2.25.0 or later and use the [git-sparse-checkout](https://www.git-scm.com/docs/git-sparse-checkout) feature.þExamples:þ* to get started, do `git sparse-checkout init --cone`þ * this will leave you with just the files in the repo's root folder, such as the file you are readingþ* to get the frontend code, do `git sparse-checkout set frontend`þ* to go back to having everything checked out, do `git sparse-checkout disable`þþ## What's new in metasfresh ERP?þIf you are interested in latest improvements or bug fixes of metasfresh ERP, then take a look in our [Release Notes](https://github.com/metasfresh/metasfresh/blob/master/ReleaseNotes.md).

readme: # conveyorþReactive Aggregating and Creational Frameworkþþ[Tutorial](https://github.com/aegisql/conveyor/wiki)þþ### Maven dependenciesþconveyor-coreþ```xmlþ<dependency>þ  <groupId>com.aegisql</groupId>þ  <artifactId>conveyor-core</artifactId>þ  <version>1.4.4</version>þ</dependency>þ```þþconveyor-parallelþ```xmlþ<dependency>þ  <groupId>com.aegisql</groupId>þ  <artifactId>conveyor-parallel</artifactId>þ  <version>1.4.4</version>þ</dependency>þ```þþconveyor-persistenceþ```xmlþ<dependency>þ<groupId>com.aegisql.persistence</groupId>þ  <artifactId>conveyor-persistence-core</artifactId>þ  <version>1.4.4</version>þ</dependency>þ```þ```xmlþ<dependency>þ  <groupId>com.aegisql.persistence</groupId>þ  <artifactId>conveyor-persistence-jdbc</artifactId>þ  <version>1.4.4</version>þ</dependency>þ```þþconveyor configuratorþ```xmlþ<dependency>þ  <groupId>com.aegisql</groupId>þ  <artifactId>conveyor-configurator</artifactId>þ  <version>1.4.4</version>þ</dependency>þ```þþ## Release Historyþþ### 1.4.4-SNAPSHOTþ* Added support for config propertiesþ* Added class Priority. Contains pre-defined suppliers for priority queue þ* Switched SimpleConveyor to [JavaPath](https://github.com/aegisql/java-path) v 0.1.2 labelsþ* Added Sample Result Consumerþ* Added Observable Result Consumerþ* Added Runnable Consumerþ* Added Observable Scrap Consumerþ* Testsþ* Bugfixesþþ### 1.4.3þ* Additional filters for Result and Scrap consumersþ* BuilderUtils helps to add conveyor compatibility to existing buildersþ* Improved performance for byName lookupþ* Derby persistence limited to version 10.14þ* Testsþ* Bugfixesþþ### 1.4.2þ* Suspend/resume running conveyorþ* Suspend command with Futureþ* derby-memory engineþ* P-Balanced conveyorþ* Bugfixesþ* Improved test coverageþþ### 1.4.1þ* Added Persistence Engine for MariaDBþ* Output ordering configuration for Conveyor restore from Persistence (No ordering, By ID, By Priority and then by ID)þ* Add additional fields to the PARTS table; can be used to create unique indexesþ* Create secondary unique indexes on existing and added fieldsþ* Bugfixesþþ### 1.4.0þ* Removed Deprecated Derby Jdbc Persistenceþ* Simplified and improved Archiversþ* Configurable JDBC engines in persistence for any database supporting JDBCþ* Pre-configured JDBC engines for derby (static and client), MySQL, Postgres and Sqlite þ* Configuration support for derby (static and client), MySQL, Postgres and Sqlite þ* Bugfixesþþ***þþ### 1.3.15þ* Improved Loader interfacesþ* Added access by conveyor name for Loadersþ* Added lazy suppliers for Loadersþþ### 1.3.14þ* KeepRunning exception for non-critical errorsþ* ConveyorRuntimeException instead of RuntimeExceptionsþ* Added priority field to cartsþ* Made carts comparable by their priority and creation timestampþ* Added priority to loadersþ* Added enablePriorityQueue parameter to the Configuratorþ* Added priority support to persistenceþ* Bugfixesþþ### 1.3.13þ* Configuration support for compaction moved to persistence levelþþ### 1.3.12þ* Added peek() and peek(Consumer) commands to AssemblingConveyor and CommandLoaderþ* Lazy Conveyor Supplierþ* Lazy Persistence Supplierþ* Added Memento object for Builder instance and its statusþ* Added commands to retrieve the Memento object and restore build from it.þ* Compact commands for Persistent Conveyor - replaces multiple þ* Automatic compaction when reach certain number of parts per build.þ* Configuration support for compactionþ* Bugfixesþþ### 1.3.11þ* Derby persistence propertiesþ* Extended support for JavaScript in Conveyor Persistence Configurationþ* Define Conveyor and Persistence properties from ENV and System propertiesþ* Added support for standard label readiness testers "readyWhenAccepted" propertiesþ* unRegister conveyor name, to hide it from JMX and runtime lookupþ* Forwarding results with foreach predicate optionþ* Bugfixes and improvementsþþ### 1.3.10þ* Started conveyor-configurator sub-projectþ* Create conveyors from .properties filesþ* Create conveyors from .YAML filesþ* Added constructor for L balanced conveyor that takes a list of enclosed conveyor namesþ* Created ForwardResult consumer factoryþ* Removed forwardTo methods from interfaceþ* Resolving persistence by its JMX name: Persistence.byName(name)þ* Bugfixesþþ### 1.3.9þ* MBeans improvementsþ* MBean for the DerbyPersistenceþ* Conveyor.byName(name) methodþ* Persistence as an Archiverþþ### 1.3.7þ* More converters for basic typesþ* File Archiverþ* CartInputStreamþ* CartOurputStreamþ* ReflectingValueConsumerþ* Simple Conveyor - uses reflection to match String labels to the Builder APIþ* @Label and @NoLabel annotations for builder settersþ* Improvements and bugfixesþþ### 1.3.6þ* Added converters for all basic Java types, collections, maps and arraysþ* Improved restoring from persistenceþ* Added interrupt method to the Conveyor interfaceþ* Added Interruptable interface.þ* Bugfixesþþ### 1.3.4þ* Persistence core moduleþ* Persistence JDBC moduleþ* Uses TimeHostIdGenerator by defaultþ* Apache Derby implementation for the Persistenceþ* Serializable functional interfacesþ* Changes in the Conveyor API to support persistenceþ* Acknowledge added to the ProductBin and ScrapBinþ* General re-factoringþ* Tests and bugfixesþþ### 1.3.3þ* Extracted Parallel conveyors into a separate moduleþ* Added the persistence project - testing deployment, not for useþ* Added runtime propertiesþþ### 1.3.2þ* No code changes. Changed project structure. All current code moved into the conveyor-core module þþ### 1.3.1þ* Added functional Interfaces ResultConsumer and ScrapConsumer with default methods extending standard Consumer interface.þ* re-factored code to use new interfacesþ* Cart interface now provides the getScrapConsumer method which can be overridden to customize the scrap consumption behavior.   þ* Tests and bugfixesþþ### 1.3.0þ* New unstable releaseþ* Changes in the Result and Scrap consumer processingþ* Removed multi-key part and command loader interfaces. Their functionality merged with part and command interfaces respectively.þ* Added new and improved old result and scrap consumersþ* More tests and bugfixes  þþ*** þþ### 1.2.5þ* Collection of result consumersþ* Collection of scrap consumersþþ### 1.2.4þ* CompletableFuture<Boolean> completeAndStop() method. When called, conveyor stops accepting new messages or commands, then waits for completion of existing tasks. When all builds complete or time out, exits the conveyor thread. This method can be useful for single time jobs, like massive batch load from parallel sources.þ* Changes in the forwardResultsTo method. Now allows to forward results to conveyor with different data structure, inluding transformation of the key.þ* Dropped ChainResults class as redundant. Functionality better covered by the forwardResultsTo methodsþþ### 1.2.3þ* static loader and valuesþ* Improved setting names for smart lablesþ* bare smart labels with no actual function attached in order to pass messages that do not need to change state of the builderþ* Improvements to Conveyor interfaceþ* testsþ* map-reduce demoþþ### 1.2.2þ* added method getConsumerFor with explicit Bulder class parameter to avoid class casting in consumers.þ* regex pattern match methods added to the LabeledValueConsumer interface.þ* more testsþ* minor bugfixes and refactoringþþ### 1.2.1þ* Utility conveyors modified to use Loadersþ* Extended use of Duration in conveyor settingsþ* Bugfixesþ* More testsþþ### 1.2.0þ* Changes in Conveyor interfaceþ* Changes in Cart interfaceþ* Loaders for parts, commands, futures and buildsþ* Bugfixes and improvements þþ*** þþ### 1.1.9þ* More interface extensionsþ* Code re-factoring and cleaningþþ### 1.1.8þ* Added default methods on basic functional interfaces: ProductSupplier, SmartLabel and LabeledValueConsumer. This allows to construct very flexible builders and data consumersþþ### 1.1.7þ* Added explicit timeout postpone for TimeoutAction (if postpone enabled) to resolve possible conflicts with cache implementations  þþ### 1.1.6þ* NOTE: This release contains a bug that affects caches with extendable TTL and builders that do not implement Expireable interface.þ* Added timeout postpone from TimeoutAction (if postpone enabled)  þ* minor bugfixesþ* refactoringþþ### 1.1.5þ* Added BuildTester - helping class to build readiness evaluator.  þ* minor bugfix - double call of the ready() methodþþþ### 1.1.4þ* New constructor for AssemblingConveyor allows to define Supplier for alternative implementation of internal Queues.  þ* Helping classes for simple scalar cachesþþ### 1.1.3þ* ImmutableReference for simple scalar cachesþ* Bugfix in createBuild returned future þþ### 1.1.2þ* MBeans support þþ### 1.1.1þ* Bugfix in balancing functions. Also exists in 1.0.x þþ### 1.1.0þ* First and unstable release of the new versionþ* CompletableFuture on carts and commandsþ* CompletableFuture for the productþ* Interface improvementsþ* ParallelConveyor becomes abstract and replaced by a pair of K and L balanced conveyors þ* Bugfixes for 1.0.xþþ*** þþ### 1.0.16þ* bugfixþ* added posponing expiration time when data accessed via caching interfaceþþ### 1.0.15þ* added posponing expiration timeþþ### 1.0.14þ* skipþþ### 1.0.13þ* Changes in the Conveyor interface. Assembling and Parallel conveyors now share most of methodsþ* Scaling by labelsþ* setExpirationCollectionIdleInterval renamed to setIdleHeartBeatþþ### 1.0.12þ* Bugfixþ* Re-scheduling.  þþ### 1.0.11þ* Chaining refactoringþ* forEachKeyAndBuilder bugfix þþ### 1.0.10þ* createBuild interfaceþ* Improvements for the CreateCart and CreateCommandþ* forEachKeyAndBuilder method provides safe way to apply safe action to all current builds þþ### 1.0.9þ* Extended the Conveyor interface. added multiple add, offer and addCommand methods to avoid explicit creation of carts. Cart though is still a holder for all input information.þ* Minor refactoring and testsþþ### 1.0.8þ* Reschedule commandþ* DelayLine utility conveyorþ* Improvement in expiration priority resolutionþþ### 1.0.7þ* Detailed failure type in the Scrap Binþþ### 1.0.6þ* add cart pre-placement user's validation algorithm to parallel conveyorþ* add key pre-eviction user's algorithm to parallel conveyorþþ### 1.0.5þ* add cart pre-placement user's validation algorithmþ* add key pre-eviction user's algorithmþ* minor timeout bugfixþþ### 1.0.4þ* SmartLabel extends standard Supplier interfaceþ* Added option to keep all accepted carts on site and make them available at testing and scrap collection timeþþ### 1.0.3þ* Added utility ResutQueue - Wrapper implementing Queue and ProductBin Consumerþ* Changes scope of slf4j library to providedþþ### 1.0.2þ* Moved excessive logging to TRACE levelþ* Delay queue now holds all Builders with the same expiration time in one Box. þþ### 1.0.1þ* Expireable is the only interface to control expiration timeþ* Updated librariesþþ### 1.0.0þ* First release
