# VocabHunterþþ[![Build Status](https://img.shields.io/travis/VocabHunter/VocabHunter/master.svg)](https://travis-ci.org/VocabHunter/VocabHunter)þ[![Code Coverage](https://img.shields.io/codecov/c/github/VocabHunter/VocabHunter.svg)](https://codecov.io/gh/VocabHunter/VocabHunter)þ[![SonarCloud](/assets/SonarCloud.svg)](https://sonarcloud.io/dashboard?id=io.github.vocabhunter%3Avocabhunter)þ[![Latest Release](https://img.shields.io/github/release/VocabHunter/VocabHunter.svg)](https://github.com/VocabHunter/VocabHunter/releases/latest)þ[![Twitter Follow](https://img.shields.io/twitter/follow/vocabhunterapp.svg?style=social&label=Follow)](https://twitter.com/vocabhunterapp)þþ[![VocabHunter](/assets/VocabHunter.png)](https://vocabhunter.github.io/)þþVocabHunter is a system to help learners of foreign languages.  The best place to go for information about VocabHunter is the project website: [vocabhunter.github.io](https://vocabhunter.github.io/).þþTo get all the latest news about VocabHunter including announcements of new releases, follow [@vocabhunterapp](https://twitter.com/vocabhunterapp) on Twitter.þþ[![VocabHunter](/assets/VocabHunter-in-use.png)](https://vocabhunter.github.io/)þþ# PrerequisitesþþYou will need Java 11 to build and run VocabHunter.  The version provided by [AdoptOpenJDK](https://adoptopenjdk.net/) is an excellent choice for this.  Everything else, including Gradle, will be downloaded by the build process.þþ# How To Run VocabHunterþþGo to the [download](https://vocabhunter.github.io/download/) page of the website to get the latest release of VocabHunter.  Alternatively, you can run the development version from the command line as follows:þ~~~þ$ ./gradlew :gui:runþ~~~þþ# How to Use VocabHunterþþDo you want to use VocabHunter to help you to learn a foreign language?  You'll find everything you need to know to get you started in the guide [How to Use VocabHunter](https://vocabhunter.github.io/help/).þþ# How To Build VocabHunterþþYou can build the entire system with the following command:þ~~~þ$ ./gradlew clean buildþ~~~þþ# How To Run The GUI TestþþBy default the GUI test runs as part of the standard Gradle build, in headless mode.  If you'd like to run the GUI test in a non-headless mode so that you can see what is happening, use the following command:þ~~~þ$ ./gradlew :gui:test --tests io.github.vocabhunter.gui.main.GuiTest --rerun-tasks -PnoHeadlessþ~~~þþ# How to Build The Installable Bundleþþ[![Using the Java Packager with JDK 11](/assets/Using-The-Java-Packager-With-JDK-11.png)][Using the Java Packager with JDK 11]þþIn the article [Using the Java Packager with JDK 11] you can read about how installable bundles for Mac, Windows and Linux are created and how you can do this in your own project.  These self-contained installers allow users to setup VocabHunter on their computer without the need to first install Java.þþYou can also find full, step-by-step instructions for creating the VocabHunter installable bundle in [PACKAGING.md](package/PACKAGING.md).þþ# Technical ArticlesþþIf you'd like to know more about how VocabHunter works and the technologies used to build it, take a look at the following articles that explore various aspects of the implementation:þþ* [Read (Almost) Any Document in Java] (VocabHunter Blog) - VocabHunter uses Apache Tika to read documents in a wide variety of formats ranging from Microsoft Word through to PDF.  This article explains how it is done.þ* [How JavaFX was used to build a desktop application] (King Tech Blog) - A detailed look at several important features of JavaFX using VocabHunter as an example.þ* [Migrating to JUnit 5] (VocabHunter Blog) - How the VocabHunter project was updated to use JUnit 5 for testing.  This article explains the changes that were made, the problems that were encountered and how they were solved.þ* [Dependency Injection in JavaFX] (VocabHunter Blog) - How to Gluon Ignite and Google Guice are used for the  Dependency Injection in VocabHunter.þ* [User Interface Testing with TestFX] (VocabHunter Blog) - A guide to automating user interface tests using TestFX.  VocabHunter includes a complete automated GUI test suite and here you can learn how it works.þ* [Building a JavaFX Search Bar] (VocabHunter Blog) - How the user interface for the VocabHunter search bar works with details of the use of ControlsFX and FontAwesomeFX in giving the bar a distinctive style.þ* [VocabHunter – A tool for learners of foreign languages] (King Tech Blog) - An introduction to some of the technologies being used in VocabHunter.þþ[![VocabHunter](/assets/VocabHunter-Technical-Articles.png)](https://vocabhunter.github.io/blog/)þþ[Dependency Injection in JavaFX]:https://vocabhunter.github.io/2016/11/13/JavaFX-Dependency-Injection.htmlþ[User Interface Testing with TestFX]:https://vocabhunter.github.io/2016/07/27/TestFX.htmlþ[Building a JavaFX Search Bar]:https://vocabhunter.github.io/2017/01/15/Search-Bar.htmlþ[Read (Almost) Any Document in Java]:https://vocabhunter.github.io/2017/04/30/Read-Any-Document-Format.htmlþ[Migrating to JUnit 5]:https://vocabhunter.github.io/2017/10/17/migrating-to-junit-5.htmlþþ[VocabHunter – A tool for learners of foreign languages]:https://medium.com/techking/vocabhunter-a-tool-for-learners-of-foreign-languages-55c467a6250cþ[How JavaFX was used to build a desktop application]:https://medium.com/techking/how-javafx-was-used-to-build-a-desktop-application-7d4c680d8dcþ[Using the Java Packager with JDK 11]:https://medium.com/@adam_carroll/java-packager-with-jdk11-31b3d620f4a8

description: Some Java scripts what might come in handy
readme: # JavaþSome Java scripts what might come in handyþþ### GenerateGPSCoordinates.javaþThis file contains a method that generates new GPS coordinates based on an initial Position, the distance between the old and new position and the bearing (heading) in degrees. þþIf this method is used for other calculations than for satellites, the `heightSatellite` variable will be set to 0, and the `distanceOrbit` variable describes the real distance on the ground. Otherwise the `distanceOrbit` describes the distance the satellite makes between each method call and the `heightSatellite` variable contains the satellite's height in meters in the sky **measured from the earth surface**.þþ### KerasImageClassifierInJava.javaþThis file is an example of how to read in a keras model in Java using deeplearning4j. To change the shape of the numpy arrays use the Nd4j package like reshaping etc.þþA model gets read in including weights (see the link of deeplearning4j for other possibilities), then the image will be read and transformed to fit the input layer of the model. Then the classifier returns the result.

XML files can be found in exmaple folder.þþ#### Helpþ```þusage: org.cern.cms.dbloader.DbLoaderþ    --channel-class <arg>           print generated channel classþ    --channel-desc <arg>            describe single channelþ    --channel-list                  list available channelsþ    --cond-class <arg>              print generated condition classþ    --cond-dataset <arg>            get XML stream dataþ    --cond-datasets <arg>           list condition datasetsþ    --cond-desc <arg>               describe single conditionþ    --cond-list                     list available conditionsþ    --cond-xml <arg>                print condition XML exampleþ    --condition-core-schema <arg>   CONDITION: core schema nameþ    --condition-ext-schema <arg>    CONDITION: extension schema nameþ    --construct-core-schema <arg>   CONSTRUCT: core schema nameþ    --construct-ext-schema <arg>    CONSTRUCT: extension schema nameþ    --help                          print usageþ    --iov-core-schema <arg>         MANAGEMNT: iov schema nameþ    --log-level <arg>               log level, possible valuesþ                                    OFF,FATAL,ERROR,WARN,INFO,DEBUG,TRACE.þ                                    Default is ERRORþ    --managemnt-core-schema <arg>   MANAGEMNT: core schema nameþ    --password <arg>                database passwordþ    --print-sql                     print SQL queries to stdoutþ    --properties <arg>              path to connection properties fileþ    --schema <arg>                  save XML schema files to pathþ    --test                          upload test - proceed with the fullþ                                    upload process but rollback theþ                                    transactionþ    --url <arg>                     database connection URLþ    --username <arg>                database usernameþ    --version                       print versionþ```

readme: StrangeBrew Java - 2.1.0þ=============þþ(c)2000-2008 Drew Avis - drew.avis@gmail.comþDoug Edey - doug.edey@gmail.comþþThank you for downloading and trying StrangeBrew Java.þþThis file contains:þ* What's New in this release?þ* What is this?þ* Running StrangeBrew Javaþ* Extra help for running on Linuxþ* Setting the look and feelþ* Files in this releaseþ* Required JREþ* Known Issues (bugs)þ* Reporting Bugsþ* Older Releasesþ* Roadmapþ* Building the projectþ* Contributorsþ* Copyrights and LicensesþþWhat's Newþ==========þþ2.1.0þ---------þ- New FEATURE! Web Server to allow you to read any recipes you have in your recipes directory on any device connected to the networkþ-- I'll be making this nicer soonþ-- You can currently enable/disable this and set the Port in the Brewer Preferences panel, you must restart StrangeBrew when changing the valuesþ- Lots of changes, I'll add any I can rememberþ- A lot of bugfixesþ- Mash Calculator was broken so it would advise you to collect less than you neededþ- Added a pantry mode so you can record how much of an ingredient you haveþ- Added more themesþ- Moved to a DB for storing ingredientsþ- Fixed the Refractometer toolþ- Add ingredients from the UI (Under the "Edit -> Add *" menus)þ- Fix styles having the high and low the wrong way roundþþþ What is this?þ===============þþThis is a "release quality" release of StrangeBrew Java, which means þit's feature-complete, and is pretty stable.  If you find bugs, pleaseþreport them via the Github Project. Or email a developer aboveþþStrangeBrew Java is a Java port of the popular Windows homebrewingþsoftware, StrangeBrew (www.strangebrew.ca).þþIngredients can now be added/edited from the application, removing theþneed to edit the data files directly.þþNOTE: We've changed the numbering of Java releases to 2.0, based on þthe idea that this is a continuation of the Windows version 1.8.þþþ þþþ Running StrangeBrew Javaþ==========================þþRunning StrangeBrew:þ1. Unzip the sb_XXX.zip file (where XXX is the latest version, eg: "sb_2.0.1").þBe sure to preserve the directory structure.þ2. Type "java -jar strangebrew.jar" at the command line.  Under Windows,þyou can right-click this file, select "Open With > " and select a Javaþinstallation. You can also just double-click the file, if ".jar" filesþare associated with javaw.exe.  Double-clicking reportedly also works onþMac OSX.  There's probably a Linux way to do this, but I don't know what it is.þþNOTE: StrangeBrew loads data (ingredients, styles, etc) from:þsrc/ca/strangebrew/data/þWhen you unzip the file, be sure to preserve directory names, soþthat StrangeBrew can find this data.þþþExtra help for running on Linuxþ===============================þþþ**I do not recommend this, just use ``` java -jar strangebrew.jar ```**þþThese are notes from Scott Alfter via rec.crafts.brewing:þþ1. Make sure CONFIG_BINFMT_MISC is enabled in the kernel (built-in orþ   module)...look in Executable file formats/Emulations -> Kernel supportþ   for MISC binaries. þ2. Add the following to /etc/fstab:þ   binfmt_misc /proc/sys/fs/binfmt_misc binfmt_misc defaults 0 0þ3. Create /usr/bin/jexec with the following contents and make it executableþ   by everybody:þ   #!/bin/shþ   java -jar $*þ4. Add the following to whatever script your distro provides for localþ   customization (in Gentoo, it's /etc/conf.d/local.start):þ   echo ':jarexec:M::PK\x03\x04::/usr/bin/jexec:' >/proc/sys/fs/binfmt_misc/registerþþWhen you reboot (or if you execute the preceding from a root prompt), youþcan chmod 755 strangeBrew_fat.jar and then run it with the following:þþ./strangeBrew_fat.jarþþNOTE: At least one person has experienced problems running StrangeBrew on Fedoraþusing their 1.4.2 JRE, which is the GNU gcj.  The problem was solved by using theþ1.5 JRE from Sun.  þþFor Ubuntu:þInstall Sun's JRE:þ $ sudo apt-get install sun-java6-jreþUpdate default system JVM:þ $ sudo update-alternatives --config javaþ  Select java-6 from the listþ $ sudo update-alternatives --config jarþ  Select java-6 from the listþþSee https://help.ubuntu.com/community/Java for more help with Ubuntu.þþ**This bug below is fixed**þþGreg LaPolla points out:þWhen you create a launcher on the desktop and start the app with the java -jar þcommand it displays the "can't find the database" error.  You can create a shellþscript to fix it by simply changing to the StrangeBrew directory first:þþ```þ#!/bin/shþcd ~/StrangeBrewþjava -jar StrangeBrew.jarþ```þþþSetting the Look and Feelþ=========================þþThe Java Swing library (which StrangeBrew uses for its user interface) supportsþa "pluggable look and feel" (LAF) -- meaning you can easily change the appearance þof Swing applications to suit your own tastes.  þþThe default is the System Look and Feel, this means that the application should þfairly closely match your Operating Systems Look & Feel (there are some exceptions,þsuch as KDE based environments)þþ(Some betas of StrangeBrew used the JGoodies Looks LAF, but I removedþit as the default to give users more control over how the application looks).þþVery nice look and feels are available on-line from several sources.  Here are þa few of my favourites for StrangeBrew:þ* JGoodies Looks: http://javootoo.l2fprod.com/plaf/jgoodies/index.phpþ* Liquid L&F: https://liquidlnf.dev.java.net/þ* Synthetica L&F: http://www.javasoft.de/jsf/public/products/syntheticaþ* Tonic L&F: http://www.digitprop.com/p.php?page=toniclfþþDownload the .jar file you'd like to try, and put it in your Java home directory underþ/lib/ext.þþYou can set the Look and Feel in a couple of ways:þþ1) From the Command-line:þUse the -Dswing.defaultlaf= option when starting the application.þHere's an example of starting StrangeBrew using the Synthetica LAF:þþ```java -Dswing.defaultlaf=de.javasoft.plaf.synthetica.SyntheticaStandardLookAndFeel -jar strangebrew.jar```þþThe "de.javasoft.plaf.synthetica.SyntheticaStandardLookAndFeel" bit is the full class þname of the Look And Feel -- you'll have to read the documentation for each LAF to find þout the proper text to put hereþþ2) Using swing.properties:þYou can set the default LAF for all Java Swing applications by editing the swing.propertiesþfile in your $JAVA_HOME/lib directory.  You need to add two lines for your new LAF, andþchange the default line.  Here's an example of the new & changed lines using the TonicþLAF:þ```þswing.installedlaf.tonic.name = Tonicþswing.installedlaf.tonic.class = com.digitprop.tonic.TonicLookAndFeelþswing.defaultlaf=com.digitprop.tonic.TonicLookAndFeelþ```þþ3) Using the preferences options. Under the "Brewer" pane you can select from any of the L&Fs installed þon your system. This gets saved.þþNow start StrangeBrew as you would normally, and it should use the new LAF.þþþFiles þ==========þþThe file you downloaded should contain these files (at least):þ  * strangebrew.jar: a Fat Jar file which you can run (see above).  Thisþ    file also contains the complete Java source for the application.  Toþ    view the source, decompress this file with an archive utility.þ  * gpl.txt: the GPL license this software is distributed underþ  * readme.txt: this fileþ  * src/ca/strangebrew/data: data files and the xslt files required þ    for exporting HTML and printing.  You can modify the xslt files if þ    you want to customize the look of the HTML.þ  * help/: help files.  These files are under development.þ  * recipes/: example recipe files in various formats.    þ  * src/*: all the Java files you need to build and run StrangeBrew yourself.  þ    You will need to either download or extract a couple of other .jar files þ    that StrangeBrew requires.þþþRequired JREþ============þþYou require a Java Runtime Environment (JRE) on your system to runþStrangeBrew.  It requires versions 1.5 and up (See þhttp://java.sun.com/j2se/1.5.0/index.jsp). As of version 2.0.1, þStrangeBrew no longer runs under version 1.4.   StrangeBrew hasþbeen tested and runs on Linux, MacOS-X, and Windows.  þþþKnown Issuesþ============þþ* When importing recipes from StrangeBrew for Windows (1.8 or earlier),þfermentables that are sugars are incorrectly considered "grains".  Theirþgravity contribution is calculated using the recipe efficiency, rather thanþ100%.  You should uncheck the "M" (for mashed) column, which indicates thatþthe ingredient is a sugar.  This applies to all sugar-type fermentables, suchþas honey, DME, LME, maple syrup, and sugars.þþþRunning from Eclipseþ============þþStrangeBrew.launch in the repository contains the Run configurations listed here.þþþAdd a new Run or debug configuration with þ``` ca.strangebrew.ui.swing.dialogs.Splash ```þþAs the Main class, then you need to add the build directory to the Configuration, you may need to run a build first and refresh the eclipse directoryþþClass Path -> Advanced -> Add Folder -> find the "Build" directoryþþþReporting Bugsþ==============þþLook to the top right, there's a button for "Issues" click that, and report anything.þþOr use http://reddit.com/r/StrangeBrewþþþOlder Release þ==============þþ2.0.2þ--------þNew Features:þ- You can now specify the BJCP style year you want to use (2004 or 2008).þ- Random Name Generator for recipes!þ- Table column sizes are now remembered when you close and restart the applicationþ  (Request 1493295).þ- Diluted recipe feature works a lot better.  Diluted specs show up on the main recipeþ  details tab.  þ- If StrangeBrew can't find the ingredient databases, it will ask you where they are insteadþ  of silently starting anyway.  þ- StrangeBrew now looks more like a native MacOS/X application on Macs.  þ- Windows Installerþ- Ingredients can be added/edited from the GUI, under the Edit menu.þþBugs Fixed:þ- Pre/Post boil volumes don't match the Unitþ- Mac is now detected correctlyþ- BeerXML now opens files correctlyþ- Hops sorted correctly for timings, not nameþ- Switching temperature units no longer corrupts the valueþ- Adding fermentables now orders them correctly and they do not switch order when selecting the nameþ- Strangebrew now looks in the correct location for data filesþ- Misc water loss is now set correctly on the Water tab.þ- Rager formula bug fixed.þ- New Recipe Defaults: Temp Units now displays properly.þþ2.0.1þ--------þNew Features:þ- New Gravity Teperature Tool Dialog (Request 1222300)þ- New selectable user locale, which affects date format (Bug 1480514)þ- New Fermentation Schedule tabþ- New Carbonation tabþ- New Water Treatment tabþþBugs Fixed:þ- Default hop type (Leaf, Pellet, Plug) is now configurable (Request 1489276) þ- Text field auto selection (Bug 1489252)þ- You can now select-by-typing in malt and hop lists (Bug 1493279)þ- Mash Steps now insert at end of list (Request 1497970)þ- Changed default bottle unit and size to imperal (Bug 1493267) þ- UI improvments to the saved "default" mash schedulesþþþ2.0.0þ--------þBugs Fixed:þ- Mash ratio and ratio units are now properly displayed.þ- After storing ingredients from an imported recipe, the database is no longer corrupted.þ- Malt and hop drop-downs behave better (Bugs 1580524 and 1511954).þ- Selecting a date now permanently changes it (Bug 1581203).þ- The comments scrollbar now behaves correctly.þ- File extensions don't keep multiplying every time you open the Save/SaveAs/Export dialogs.þ- The Min column in the hops table is now handled correctly.þ- The style dropdown now displays from the top of the list, rather than the bottom, for an empty style (Bug 1493269).þþþ2.0.rc1þ--------þNew Features:þ- StrangeBrew no longer uses the JGoodies Look And Feel by default, as this wasþ  causing some refresh issues on older versions of Mac OSX.  Instead, you can setþ  the LAF yourself. (See the "Setting the Look And Feel" section above).þ- You can now set the bottom of temp ranges used to determine mashout and spargeþ  steps.  The defaults are 161F for mashout, and 170F for sparge.  This means thatþ  when you add a mashout step, it uses the middle of the range (161 + 170 / 2, orþ  165.5F) when you add a mashout step, and if you change the start temp to <161, itþ  becomes a different step type.  You can adjust these numbers to suit your mashingþ  preferences.þ- More and better StrangeBrew Java-specific help.  þ- New Print toolbar button.þþBugs Fixed:þ- FWH, mash hop, and dry hop IBU values are now correctly calculated.þ- The strangebrew.ini file is now saved and read from the correct location on þ  non-Windows machines.þ- HTML export now works again on non-Windows machines.  þþ2.0.b7þ--------þNew Features:þ- You can now apply default mash schedules on the Mash tab to quickly loadþ  a popular schedule.  You can also save the current schedule to the list ofþ  defaults.  You can edit the /data/mashdefaults.csv file by hand to add or þ  remove a default schedule.þ- The Resize Recipe dialog now allows you to also convert hops and fermentablesþ  (Bug 1489903).þ- New potential extract calculator.  þ- You can now add sparge steps to a mash schedule.  Add a step, and change the þ  type to "sparge".  If you add more than one sparge step, it's automaticallyþ  considered a batch sparge, and correct additions are calculated.  þ- You can now set the parameters for a thick and thin decoction on the þ  settings tab.þ- You can now add cereal mash steps to a mash schedule.  Add a step, and change theþ  method to "cereal mash".  Enter the weight of the grain used in the cereal mash.þ  Other values will update accordingly.  Note: the temperature of the step is adjustedþ  if the cereal mash addition brings the step above the targe temp.  Tryþ  decreasing the weight and adjusting the temperature until you get the values youþ  want.  þ- New Refractometer Utility lets you peform various calculations with readingsþ  from a refractometer.  þþBugs Fixed:þ- You can now specify a default boil time on the Preferences Dialog (Bug 1493270)þ- Style tab now displays correct SRM value when you're using EBC colour (Bug 1497989)þ- You can now set various mash defaults on the Preferences dialog (Bug 1489256)þ- You can now set boil units (C or F) as well as boil temp on the Preferencesþ  dialog (Bug 1489250)þ- Cost tab now re-calculates correctly when values change (Bug 1493994)þ- Final beer volume shown on cost tab now matches volume shown on water tab (Bug 1493294)þ- BU:GU ratio is now displayed correctly on the Style panel (Bug 1493283).þ- Dilution panel is now updated when you first open a recipe (Bug 1492475).þ- Setting pre-boil amount now correctly updates post-boil amount.þ- Changing mash temp units to C now correctly converts tun loss (Bug 1492220).þ- Yeast now imports in BeerXML recipes. (Note: if there's more than one yeastþ  listed, only the last is imported w/ the recipe).þ- Find toolbar button now works (Bug 1489274).  þ- Water panel numbers now aligned (Bug 1493293).þ- On the preferences dialog, when you select a constant evaporation rate, theþ  units are correctly displayed as the current default recipe volume units þ  (Bug 1493263).þ- Removed the extra note area on the notes tab (Bug 1493286).þ- Malts with a weight of 0 are correctly displayed as being 0% (Bug 1493276).  þ- Malt and hop amounts are rounded to 2 decimal places instead of 1 (Bug 1493281).þ- Preferences are saved in the right place on non-Windows machines.þ- Misc ingredient table column widths are now nicer (Bug 1493284).þ- %alc, ibu, colour method combos are wider so text isn't cut off (Bug 1489271).þ- Switching between % and constant evaporation doesn't redraw the Preferencesþ  tab. (Bug 1493266)þ- Mash tab now shows step volume and temp. (Bug 1489258)  þþ  þþ Roadmapþ=========þþFeatures on the "TODO List" for StrangeBrew:þ- mash tun thermal massþ- hop scalingþ- real application help (not the SB Win version)þ- save / load mash profilesþ- specify mash temp rangesþ- cereal mashþ- allow user-specified precision of valuesþþPlanned StrangeBrew  Pro Features:þ- advanced water profilingþ- inventory trackingþ- brewday timeline generationþ- brew sessions (vs recipes)þ- saved mash schedulesþ- alternate malt/hop selection dialogþ- ingredient database editingþ- equipment databasesþ- iPod Note exportþþ(StrangeBrew Java will be released under a "dual-license": a free þOpen Source version and a commercial "Pro" version that will þinclude some additional functionality.)þþComments or questions should be directed to drew.avis@gmail.com.þþþBuilding the projectþ====================þþComplete StrangeBrew Java source is included in the strangebrew.jar file.þStrangeBrew Java source is also available via githubþþ(http://github.com/DougEdey/StrangeBrew)[Github Repo] for more information.þþI'm building the project in Eclipse, which is freely available at eclipse.org.  þOnce you've un-archived the source from the jar file (or obtained it from cvs), youþcan import it as a new project into Eclipse.  You'll need to:þ- add the 3rd party .jar files in /lib (in the strangebrew.jar archive) to the þ  project librariesþ- add an appropriate Sun JRE (1.5+) to the project libraries, if one is not alreadyþ  selectedþþThat should be all you need to build and run the program.þþIf you wish to build the application from Ant, Greg LaPolla has kindly contributedþa build file (build.xml in the top level of the source tree).  This file has threeþtargets:þ* ant build - build the applicationþ* ant clean - clean the workspaceþ* ant zip - build a zip file for distribution.  You have to editþ  the version.num property at the top of the build.xml file.  This build targetþ  also unpacks the other jars and incorporates them into the distributableþ  jar and it also creates the manifest file. þþContributorsþ============þþThe following people have contributed to the development of this þprogram:þ* Mike Charlton - SWT gui development / Java consultingþ* Jim Clark - bug fixing and new feature developmentþ* Chris Cook - xslt developmentþ* Andy Davison - testingþ* Mike Gibson - testing and the splash screen / logoþ* Kris Henderson (Zymurgist) - preferences codingþ* Don Kelly - Promash recipe format decodingþ* Colin Kilburn - testing / bug fixesþ* Jason Landry - database updatesþ* Jeroen Wouters - bug fixesþ* Greg LaPolla - bug fixes / ant build / windows installerþ* Sean Cotterill - for his research into Refractometer accuracyþþþCopyrightsþ==========þþParts of this program are copyright by:þ        Copyright (C) 2002-2004 Roedy Green þ        (CSVReader and CSVWriter classes)þ        Copyright (C) Copyright (c) 2003-2004 Werner Randelshoferþ        (Splash and SplashWindow classes)þ        Copyright (c) 2001-2006 JGoodies Karsten Lentzsch. All rights reserved.þ        (JGoodies Look and Feel)þ        Copyright (c) 2005-2006, Michael Baranovþ        (Microba library)þþþLicenseþ=======þþ        Copyright (C) 2006-2008  Drew Avisþþ    This program is free software; you can redistribute it and/or modifyþ    it under the terms of the GNU General Public License as published byþ    the Free Software Foundation; either version 2 of the License, orþ    (at your option) any later version.þþ    This program is distributed in the hope that it will be useful,þ    but WITHOUT ANY WARRANTY; without even the implied warranty ofþ    MERCHANTABILITY or FITNESS FOR A PARTICULAR PURPOSE.  See theþ    GNU General Public License for more details.þþ    You should have received a copy of the GNU General Public Licenseþ    along with this program; if not, write to the Free Softwareþ    Foundation, Inc., 51 Franklin St, Fifth Floor, Boston, MA  02110-1301  USAþ    þ    See the gpl.txt file for more information.þ

# NgdroidAppþWe teach game programming here in Gamelab Istanbul (http://gamelab.istanbul) and in 2 universities. This simple Java framework is created to use in the classes. Thus, instead of spending time with configuring Android, the students can start to write their game codes asap.þþThe framework is an Android Studio project. You can fork it, and then, you can clone your fork into your computer via the Android Studio.þþThe framework has got;þþ- GameActivity (the entry point),þ- AppManager (SurfaceView),þ- Main loop (main thread),þ- NgApp (the root class),þ- CanvasManager andþ- GameCanvas.þþAll you have to do is opening GameCanvas and start coding your game.þþThe framework is designed in the MVC pattern. If you need to create new classes for your menus and other views, you can simply extend BaseCanvas and set this new child canvas as the current canvas.þþWhen you want to generate your own APK;þþ- Change the app name in the res/values/strings.xml,þ- Change package com.mycompany.myngdroidapp to your own package name,þ- Put your game icon into res/mipmap folders,þ- Modify the app/build.graddle andþ- Modify AndroidManifest.xml.þþThere are still a lot of rooms to develop. Contributions are really appreciated.þþThis framework is licenced with MIT licence.þþInstallation Noticeþ--------þþThe NgdroidApp is designed as an Android Studio project. Thus you can clone and open it via your Android Studio. Some users reported that Android Studio could not sometimes open the NgdroidApp project. In this case, close the project via "File->Close Project", select "Open an existing Android Studio project", then find and open the project via project explorer window.

description: Libraries that help with some common computing tasks in Java
readme: [![Travis build status](https://img.shields.io/travis/mike10004/common-helper.svg)](https://travis-ci.org/mike10004/common-helper)þ[![AppVeyor status](https://ci.appveyor.com/api/projects/status/sklwcp67bi3lpp05?svg=true)](https://ci.appveyor.com/project/mike10004/common-helper)þ[![Maven Central](https://img.shields.io/maven-central/v/com.github.mike10004/common-helper.svg)](https://repo1.maven.org/maven2/com/github/mike10004/common-helper/)þþCommon Helper Librariesþ=======================þþLibraries that help with some common computing tasks in Java. They are:þþ* imnetio-helper: imaging, networking, and I/Oþ* ormlite-helper and ormlite-helper-testtools: help with ORMLite and þ  database unit/integration testingþ* native-helper: help with platform-dependent tasks like subprocesses þ  and platform-specific filesystem conventionsþþ## Imaging, Networking, and I/Oþþ### ImagingþþWant to get an image's dimensions without buffering all the pixels?þþ    Dimension dim = ImageInfos.readImageSize(imageBytes);þ    System.out.format("%d x %d", dim.width, dim.height);þþ### Networking þþWant to download something but handle various error conditions (unknown host, 404) þthe same way? Don't try þ[java.net.URLConnection](http://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/net/URLConnection.html), þwhere you'll get the unknown host exception on `URL.openConnection()`, or if þyou make it past that, have to catch an I/O exception on 4xx and 5xx errors and þread from the error stream. Just do this instead:þþ    HttpRequester requester = HttpRequests.newRequester();þ    ResponseData responseData = requester.retrieve("http://example.com");þ    System.out.println("HTTP response " + responseData.code);þ    System.out.println(new String(responseData.data));þþ### I/OþþWant to read from the first good input stream out of multiple potentially þbroken streams?þþ    ByteSource first = ByteSources.broken();þ    byte[] bytes = { (byte) 1, (byte) 2, (byte) 3, (byte) 4};þ    ByteSource other = ByteSource.wrap(bytes);þ    ByteSource result = ByteSources.or(first, other);þ    System.out.println(Arrays.toString(result.toByteArray())); // [1, 2, 3, 4]þþ## ORMLite helperþþDoing some quick database work? This might help you:þþ    DatabaseContext db = new DefaultDatabaseContext(new H2MemoryConnectionSource());þ    try {þ        db.getTableUtils().createTable(Customer.class);þ        Customer customer = new Customer("Jane Doe", 123);þ        db.getDao(Customer.class).create(customer);þ    } finally {þ        db.closeConnections(false); // 'true' to swallow exception on closeþ    }þþ## NativeþþWant the pathname of the directory where system configuration files are?þþ    File dir = Platforms.getPlatform().getSystemConfigDir();þ    System.out.println(dir); þþ...prints `/etc` on Linux and value of `%ProgramData%` environment variable on þWindows.þþWant to launch a subprocess and capture the output as strings?þþ    // <String, String> parameters refer to type of captured stdout and stderr dataþ    ProcessResult<String, String> result;þ    try (ScopedProcessTracker processTracker = new ScopedProcessTracker()) {þ        result = Subprocess.running("echo")þ                .arg("hello, world")þ                .build()þ                .launcher(processTracker)þ                .outputStrings(Charset.defaultCharset())þ                .launch()þ                .await();þ    }þ    System.out.println(result.content().stdout()); // prints "hello, world"þþ# How do I build it?þþ## PrerequisitesþþThe build system must have Maven 3.0+ installed. On Windows, you must have Perlþinstalled and `perl.exe` on the system path. Visit þ[strawberryperl.com](http://strawberryperl.com) for free Perl.þþOn Linux, make sure the **libaio1** (Linux kernel asynchronous I/O access þlibrary) package is installed, or else the MySQL integration tests will fail.þþThe MySQL distribution dependency is platform-dependent and Maven central may þnot host an artifact corresponding to your platform. If that is the case, youþcan download a [MySQL](http://www.mysql.com) tarball release, re-package it þinto a zip file, and install it to your local repository. For example:þþ    $ mvn install:install-file -DartifactId=mysql-dist -DgroupId=com.jcabi \þ        -Dversion=5.5.41 -Dclassifier=myoperatingsystem-amd64 -Dpackaging=zip \þ        -Dfile=/path/to/downloaded/mysql-dist-5.5.41-myoperatingsystem-amd64.zipþþAdd a profile to your `$HOME/.m2/settings.xml` that only gets activated when yourþplatform is detected.þþ## BuildþþExecuteþþ    $ mvn installþþin the parent project directory.

description: Open source Java tool which searches for similar genes across species using the NCBI database.
readme: # Cross-Species Gene FinderþOpen source Java tool which searches for similar genes across species using the NCBI database.þþUsed in [this research project](https://github.com/parrotgeek1/CrossSpeciesGeneFinder/raw/master/TvedteGradRetreatPosterSp16.pdf) by Eric Tvedte at the University of Iowa.þþThe resulting research paper is here: https://academic.oup.com/jhered/article/108/7/791/3978731þþ# Verified to NOT be working with NCBI's API as of 2019-09-10. I am attempting to fix it, but major changes are required.þþ# [Download (.jar)](https://github.com/parrotgeek1/CrossSpeciesGeneFinder/raw/master/CSGF.jar)þDouble-click CSGF.jar to start. You will be given instructions. Java is required.þ# [Source Code](https://github.com/parrotgeek1/CrossSpeciesGeneFinder)þþCSGF Batch File Formatþ---þþThe file extension is always ".txt".þþThe first line of the file starts with:þþ```þ!CSGFBatchV1þ```þþThis identifier can also be followed by a colon and several extra fields to predefine search parameters. The current possibilities are as follows:þþ* A species name, a colon, and a maximum e value: þþ        !CSGFBatchV1:Nasonia giraulti:1e-30þ        þ* A species name, a colon, a maximum e value, and a custom buffer size on both sides of the gene: þþ        !CSGFBatchV1:Nasonia giraulti:1e-30:2000þþ* A species name, a colon, a maximum e value, and 2 custom buffer sizes on either side of the gene: þþ        !CSGFBatchV1:Nasonia giraulti:1e-30:2000,3000þþAny input parameters not given will be prompted for at the start of the program, except for the default buffer size, which is 1000 bases on both sides if unspecified.þþExtraneous spaces between colons and commas, or at the END of the line, will be ignored. The file must start with EXACTLY !CSGFBatchV1 in that capitalization, with no extra spaces.þþThe rest of the file is composed of NCBI gene IDs, one per line. Extraneous spaces at the beginning or end of the line will be ignored.þþA comment (any text after a #) will cause the rest of the line it is in to be ignored, and can be anywhere in the file except on the first line. Comments can either be at the beginning of a line, or after a valid gene ID, at the end. There can be any number of spaces before or after the #.þþBlank lines, or lines consisting only of spaces, are silently ignored.þþTo Doþ---þþ* add NOT specifying max e value or species on batch fileþ* can pause and resume?þ* show expiration date for resultsþ* more code cleanup

readme:
## Welcome!þThis GitHub repository contains the source code that is used to build an Android app to control a *FIRST* Tech Challenge competition robot. To use this SDK, download/clone the entire project to your local computer.þþIf you are new to the *FIRST* Tech Challenge software and control system, you should visit the online wiki to learn how to install, configure, and use the software and control system:þþ      https://github.com/ftctechnh/ftc_app/wikiþþNote that the wiki is an "evergreen" document that is constantly being updated and edited. It contains the most current information about the *FIRST* Tech Challenge software and control system.þþ## Downloading the ProjectþIt is important to note that this repository is large and can take a long time and use a lot of space to download. If you would like to save time and space, there are some options that you can choose to download only the most current version of the Android project folder:þþ* If you are a git user, *FIRST* recommends that you use the --depth command line argument to only clone the most current version of the repository:þþ

            git clone --depth=1 https://github.com/ftctechnh/ftc_app.git

þþ* Or, if you prefer, you can use the "Download Zip" button available through the main repository page. Downloading the project as a .ZIP file will keep the size of the download manageable.þþ* You can also download the project folder (as a .zip or .tar.gz archive file) from the Downloads subsection of the Releases page for this repository.þþOnce you have downloaded and uncompressed (if needed) your folder, you can use Android Studio to import the folder ("Import project (Eclipse ADT, Gradle, etc.)").þþ## Getting Helpþ### User Documentation and Tutorialsþ*FIRST* maintains an online wiki with information and tutorials on how to use the *FIRST* Tech Challenge software and robot control system. You can access the wiki at the following address:þþ      https://github.com/ftctechnh/ftc_app/wikiþþ### Javadoc Reference MaterialþThe Javadoc reference documentation for the FTC SDK is now available online. Visit the following URL to view the FTC SDK documentation as a live website:þþ      http://ftctechnh.github.io/ftc_app/doc/javadoc/index.html þþDocumentation for the FTC SDK is also included with this repository. There is a subfolder called "doc" which contains several subfolders:þþ * The folder "apk" contains the .apk files for the FTC Driver Station and FTC Robot Controller apps.þ * The folder "javadoc" contains the JavaDoc user documentation for the FTC SDK.þþ### Online User ForumþFor technical questions regarding the SDK, please visit the FTC Technology forum:þþ      http://ftcforum.usfirst.org/forumdisplay.php?156-FTC-Technologyþþþþ**************************************************************************************þ# Release Informationþ**************************************************************************************þþVersion 3.6 (built on 17.12.18)þþChanges include:þ * Blocks Changesþ - Uses updated Google Blockly software to allow users to edit their op modes on Apple iOS devices (including iPad and iPhone).þ - Improvement in Blocks tool to handle corrupt op mode files.þ - Autonomous op modes should no longer get switched back to tele-op after re-opening them to be edited.þ - The system can now detect type mismatches during runtime and alert the user with a message on the Driver Station.þ * Updated javadoc documentation for setPower() method to reflect correct range of values (-1 to +1).þ * Modified VuforiaLocalizerImpl to allow for user rendering of framesþ - Added a user-overrideable onRenderFrame() method which gets called by the class's renderFrame() method.þþ**************************************************************************************þ# Release Informationþ**************************************************************************************þþVersion 3.5 (built on 17.10.30)þþChanges with version 3.5 include:þ * Introduced a fix to prevent random op mode stops, which can occur after the Robot Controller app has been paused and then resumed (for example, when a user temporarily turns off the display of the Robot Controller phone, and then turns the screen back on).þ * Introduced a fix to prevent random op mode stops, which were previously caused by random peer disconnect events on the Driver Station.þ * Fixes issue where log files would be closed on pause of the RC or DS, but not re-opened upon resume.þ * Fixes issue with battery handler (voltage) start/stop race.þ * Fixes issue where Android Studio generated op modes would disappear from available list in certain situations.þ * Fixes problem where OnBot Java would not build on REV Robotics Control Hub.þ * Fixes problem where OnBot Java would not build if the date and time on the Robot Controller device was "rewound" (set to an earlier date/time).þ * Improved error message on OnBot Java that occurs when renaming a file fails.þ * Removed unneeded resources from android.jar binaries used by OnBot Java to reduce final size of Robot Controller app.þ * Added MR_ANALOG_TOUCH_SENSOR block to Blocks Programming Tool.þþ**************************************************************************************þ# Release Informationþ**************************************************************************************þþVersion 3.4 (built on 17.09.06)þþChanges with version 3.4 include:þ * Added telemetry.update() statement for BlankLinearOpMode template.þ * Renamed sample Block op modes to be more consistent with Java samples.þ * Added some additional sample Block op modes.þ * Reworded OnBot Java readme slightly.þþ**************************************************************************************þþVersion 3.3 (built on 17.09.04)þþThis version of the software includes improves for the FTC Blocks Programming Tool and the OnBot Java Programming Tool.þþChanges with verion 3.3 include:þ * Android Studio ftc_app project has been updated to use Gradle Plugin 2.3.3.þ * Android Studio ftc_app project is already using gradle 3.5 distribution.þ * Robot Controller log has been renamed to /sdcard/RobotControllerLog.txt (note that this change was actually introduced w/ v3.2).þ * Improvements in I2C reliability.þ * Optimized I2C read for REV Expansion Hub, with v1.7 firmware or greater.þ * Updated all external/samples (available through OnBot and in Android project folder).þ * Vuforiaþ - Added support for VuMarks that will be used for the 2017-2018 season game.þ * Blocksþ - Update to latest Google Blockly release.þ - Sample op modes can be selected as a template when creating new op mode.þ - Fixed bug where the blocks would disappear temporarily when mouse button is held down.þ - Added blocks for Range.clip and Range.scale.þ - User can now disable/enable Block op modes.þ - Fix to prevent occasional Blocks deadlock.þ * OnBot Javaþ - Significant improvements with autocomplete function for OnBot Java editor.þ - Sample op modes can be selected as a template when creating new op mode.þ - Fixes and changes to complete hardware setup feature.þ - Updated (and more useful) onBot welcome message.þ þKnown issues:þ * Android Studioþ - After updating to the new v3.3 Android Studio project folder, if you get error messages indicating "InvalidVirtualFileAccessException" then you might need to do a File->Invalidate Caches / Restart to clear the error.þ * OnBot Javaþ - Sometimes when you push the build button to build all op modes, the RC returns an error message that the build failed. If you press the build button a second time, the build typically suceeds.þ þ**************************************************************************************þþVersion 3.2 (built on 17.08.02)þþThis version of the software introduces the "OnBot Java" Development Tool. Similar to the FTC Blocks Development Tool, the FTC OnBot Java Development Tool allows a user to create, edit and build op modes dynamically using only a Javascript-enabled web browser.þþThe OnBot Java Development Tool is an integrated development environment (IDE) that is served up by the Robot Controller. Op modes are created and edited using a Javascript-enabled browser (Google Chromse is recommended). Op modes are saved on the Robot Controller Android device directly. þþThe OnBot Java Development Tool provides a Java programming environment that does NOT need Android Studio.þþþþChanges with version 3.2 include:þ * Enhanced web-based development toolsþ - Introduction of OnBot Java Development Tool.þ - Web-based programming and management features are "always on" (user no longer needs to put Robot Controller into programming mode).þ - Web-based management interface (where user can change Robot Controller name and also easily download Robot Controller log file).þ - OnBot Java, Blocks and Management features available from web based interface.þþ* Blocks Programming Development Tool:þ - Changed "LynxI2cColorRangeSensor" block to "REV Color/range sensor" block.þ - Fixed tooltip for ColorSensor.isLightOn block.þ Added blocks for ColorSensor.getNormalizedColors and LynxI2cColorRangeSensor.getNormalizedColors.þþ* Added example op modes for digital touch sensor and REV Robotics Color Distance sensor.þ* User selectable color themes.þ* Includes many minor enhancements and fixes (too numerous to list).þþKnown issues:þ* Auto complete function is incomplete and does not support the following (for now):þ - Access via *this* keywordþ - Access via *super* keywordþ - Members of the super cloass, not overridden by the classþ - Any methods provided in the current classþ - Inner classesþ - Can't handle casted objectsþ - Any objects coming from an parenthetically enclosed expressionþþ**************************************************************************************þþVersion 3.10 (built on 17.05.09)þþThis version of the software provides support for the REV Robotics Expansion Hub. This version also includes improvements in the USB communication layer in an effort to enhance system resiliency. If you were using a 2.x version of the software previously, updating to version 3.1 requires that you also update your Driver Station software in addition to updating the Robot Controller software.þþAlso note that in version 3.10 software, the setMaxSpeed and getMaxSpeed methods are no longer available (not deprecated, they have been removed from the SDK). Also note that the the new 3.x software incorporates motor profiles that a user can select as he/she configures the robot.þþChanges include:þ * Blocks changesþ - Added VuforiaTrackableDefaultListener.getPose and Vuforia.trackPose blocks.þ - Added optimized blocks support for Vuforia extended tracking.þ - Added atan2 block to the math category.þ - Added useCompetitionFieldTargetLocations parameter to Vuforia.initialize block. If set to false, the target locations are placed at (0,0,0) with target orientation as specified in https://github.com/gearsincorg/FTCVuforiaDemo/blob/master/Robot_Navigation.java tutorial op mode.þ * Incorporates additional improvements to USB comm layer to improve system resiliency (to recover from a greater number of communication disruptions).þþ**************************************************************************************þþAdditional Notes Regarding Version 3.00 (built on 17.04.13)þþIn addition to the release changes listed below (see section labeled "Version 3.00 (built on 17.04.013)"), version 3.00 has the following important changes:þþ1. Version 3.00 software uses a new version of the FTC Robocol (robot protocol). If you upgrade to v3.0 on the Robot Controller and/or Android Studio side, you must also upgrade the Driver Station software to match the new Robocol.þ2. Version 3.00 software removes the setMaxSpeed and getMaxSpeed methods from the DcMotor class. If you have an op mode that formerly used these methods, you will need to remove the references/calls to these methods. Instead, v3.0 provides the max speed information through the use of motor profiles that are selected by the user during robot configuration.þ3. Version 3.00 software currently does not have a mechanism to disable extra i2c sensors. We hope to re-introduce this function with a release in the near future.þþ**************************************************************************************þþVersion 3.00 (built on 17.04.13)þþ*** Use this version of the software at YOUR OWN RISK!!! ***þþThis software is being released as an "alpha" version. Use this version at your own risk!þþThis pre-release software contains SIGNIFICANT changes, including changes to the Wi-Fi Direct pairing mechanism, rewrites of the I2C sensor classes, changes to the USB/FTDI layer, and the introduction of support for the REV Robotics Expansion Hub and the REV Robotics color-range-light sensor. These changes were implemented to improve the reliability and resiliency of the FTC control system.þþPlease note, however, that version 3.00 is considered "alpha" code. This code is being released so that the FIRST community will have an opportunity to test the new REV Expansion Hub electronics module when it becomes available in May. The developers do not recommend using this code for critical applications (i.e., competition use).þþ*** Use this version of the software at YOUR OWN RISK!!! ***þþChanges include:þ * Major rework of sensor-related infrastructure. Includes rewriting sensor classes to implement synchronous I2C communication.þ * Fix to reset Autonomous timer back to 30 seconds.þ * Implementation of specific motor profiles for approved 12V motors (includes Tetrix, AndyMark, Matrix and REV models).þ * Modest improvements to enhance Wi-Fi P2P pairing.þ * Fixes telemetry log addition race.þ * Publishes all the sources (not just a select few).þ * Includes Block programming improvementsþ - Addition of optimized Vuforia blocks.þ - Auto scrollbar to projects and sounds pages.þ - Fixed blocks paste bug.þ - Blocks execute after while-opModeIsActive loop (to allow for cleanup before exiting op mode).þ - Added gyro integratedZValue block.þ - Fixes bug with projects page for Firefox browser.þ - Added IsSpeaking block to AndroidTextToSpeech. þ * Implements support for the REV Robotics Expansion Hubþ - Implements support for integral REV IMU (physically installed on I2C bus 0, uses same Bosch BNO055 9 axis absolute orientation sensor as Adafruit 9DOF abs orientation sensor). - Implements support for REV color/range/light sensor.þ - Provides support to update Expansion Hub firmware through FTC SDK.þ - Detects REV firmware version and records in log file.þ - Includes support for REV Control Hub (note that the REV Control Hub is not yet approved for FTC use).þ - Implements FTC Blocks programming support for REV Expansion Hub and sensor hardware.þ - Detects and alerts when I2C device disconnect.þþ**************************************************************************************þþVersion 2.62 (built on 17.01.07)þ * Added null pointer check before calling modeToByte() in finishModeSwitchIfNecessary method for ModernRoboticsUsbDcMotorController class.þ * Changes to enhance Modern Robotics USB protocol robustness.þþ**************************************************************************************þþVersion 2.61 (released on 16.12.19)þ * Blocks Programming mode changes:þ - Fix to correct issue when an exception was thrown because an OpticalDistanceSensor object appears twice in the hardware map (the second time as a LightSensor).þþ**************************************************************************************þþVersion 2.6 (released on 16.12.16)þ * Fixes for Gyro class:þ - Added blocks to support VuforiaTrackables, VuforiaTrackable, VuforiaLocalizer, VuforiaTrackableDefaultListener.þ - Fixed a few blocks.þ - Added type checking to new blocks.þ - Updated to latest blockly.þ - When user uploads Blocks-generated op mode (.blk file), Javascript code is auto generated.þ - Added DbgLog support.þ - Added logging when a blocks file is read/written.þ - Fixed bug to properly render blocks even if missing devices from configuration file.þ - Added support for additional characters (not just alphanumeric) for the block file names (for download and upload).þ - Added support for OpMode flavor (“Autonomous” or “TeleOp”) and group.þ * Changes to Samples to prevent tutorial issues.þ * Incorporated suggested changes from public pull 216 (“Replace .. paths”).þ * Remove Servo Glitches when robot stopped.þ * if user hits “Cancels” when editing a configuration file, clears the unsaved changes and reverts to original unmodified configuration.þ * Added log info to help diagnose why the Robot Controller app was terminated (for example, by watch dog function).þ * Added ability to transfer log from the controller.þ * Fixed inconsistency for AngularVelocityþ * Limit unbounded growth of data for telemetry. If user does not call telemetry.update() for LinearOpMode in a timely manner, data added for telemetry might get lost if size limit is exceeded.þþ**************************************************************************************þþVersion 2.35 (released on 16.10.06)þ * Blockly programming mode - Removed unnecesary idle() call from blocks for new project.þþ**************************************************************************************þþVersion 2.30 (released on 16.10.05)þ * Blockly programming mode:þ - Mechanism added to save Blockly op modes from Programming Mode Server onto local deviceþ - To avoid clutter, blocks are displayed in categorized foldersþ - Added support for DigitalChannelþ - Added support for ModernRoboticsI2cCompassSensorþ - Added support for ModernRoboticsI2cRangeSensorþ - Added support for VoltageSensorþ - Added support for AnalogInputþ - Added support for AnalogOutputþ - Fix for CompassSensor setMode blockþ * Vuforiaþ - Fix deadlock / make camera data available while Vuforia is running.þ - Update to Vuforia 6.0.117 (recommended by Vuforia and Google to close security loophole).þ * Fix for autonomous 30 second timer bug (where timer was in effect, even though it appeared to have timed out).þ * opModeIsActive changes to allow cleanup after op mode is stopped (with enforced 2 second safety timeout).þ * Fix to avoid reading i2c twice.þ * Updated sample Op Modes.þ * Improved logging and fixed intermittent freezing.þ * Added digital I/O sample.þ * Cleaned up device names in sample op modes to be consistent with Pushbot guide.þ * Fix to allow use of IrSeekerSensorV3.þþ**************************************************************************************þþVersion 2.20 (released on 16.09.08)þ * Support for Modern Robotics Compass Sensor.þ * Support for Modern Robotics Range Sensor.þ * Revise device names for Pushbot templates to match the names used in Pushbot guide.þ * Fixed bug so that IrSeekerSensorV3 device is accessible as IrSeekerSensor in hardwareMap.þ * Modified computer vision code to require an individual Vuforia license (per legal requirement from PTC).þ * Minor fixes.þ * Blockly enhancements:þ - Support for Voltage Sensor.þ - Support for Analog Input.þ - Support for Analog Output.þ - Support for Light Sensor.þ - Support for Servo Controller.þþ**************************************************************************************þþVersion 2.10 (released on 16.09.03)þ * Support for Adafruit IMU.þ * Improvements to ModernRoboticsI2cGyro classþ - Block on reset of z axis.þ - isCalibrating() returns true while gyro is calibration.þ * Updated sample gyro program.þ * Blockly enhancementsþ - support for android.graphics.Color.þ - added support for ElapsedTime.þ - improved look and legibility of blocks.þ - support for compass sensor.þ - support for ultrasonic sensor.þ - support for IrSeeker.þ - support for LED.þ - support for color sensor.þ - support for CRServoþ - prompt user to configure robot before using programming mode.þ * Provides ability to disable audio cues.þ * various bug fixes and improvements.þþ**************************************************************************************þþVersion 2.00 (released on 16.08.19)þ * This is the new release for the upcoming 2016-2017 FIRST Tech Challenge Season.þ * Channel change is enabled in the FTC Robot Controller app for Moto G 2nd and 3rd Gen phones.þ * Users can now use annotations to register/disable their Op Modes.þ * Changes in the Android SDK, JDK and build tool requirements (minsdk=19, java 1.7, build tools 23.0.3).þ * Standardized units in analog input.þ * Cleaned up code for existing analog sensor classes.þ * setChannelMode and getChannelMode were REMOVED from the DcMotorController class. This is important - we no longer set the motor modes through the motor controller.þ * setMode and getMode were added to the DcMotor class. þ * ContinuousRotationServo class has been added to the FTC SDK.þ * Range.clip() method has been overloaded so it can support this operation for int, short and byte integers.þ * Some changes have been made (new methods added) on how a user can access items from the hardware map.þ * Users can now set the zero power behavior for a DC motor so that the motor will brake or float when power is zero.þ * Prototype Blockly Programming Mode has been added to FTC Robot Controller. Users can place the Robot Controller into this mode, and then use a device (such as a laptop) that has a Javascript enabled browser to write Blockly-based Op Modes directly onto the Robot Controller.þ * Users can now configure the robot remotely through the FTC Driver Station app.þ * Android Studio project supports Android Studio 2.1.x and compile SDK Version 23 (Marshmallow).þ * Vuforia Computer Vision SDK integrated into FTC SDK. Users can use sample vision targets to get localization information on a standard FTC field.þ * Project structure has been reorganized so that there is now a TeamCode package that users can use to place their local/custom Op Modes into this package.þ * Inspection function has been integrated into the FTC Robot Controller and Driver Station Apps (Thanks Team HazMat… 9277 & 10650!).þ * Audio cues have been incorporated into FTC SDK.þ * Swap mechanism added to FTC Robot Controller configuration activity. For example, if you have two motor controllers on a robot, and you misidentified them in your configuration file, you can use the Swap button to swap the devices within the configuration file (so you do not have to manually re-enter in the configuration info for the two devices).þ * Fix mechanism added to all user to replace an electronic module easily. For example, suppose a servo controller dies on your robot. You replace the broken module with a new module, which has a different serial number from the original servo controller. You can use the Fix button to automatically reconfigure your configuration file to use the serial number of the new module.þ * Improvements made to fix resiliency and responsiveness of the system.þ * For LinearOpMode the user now must for a telemetry.update() to update the telemetry data on the driver station. This update() mechanism ensures that the driver station gets the updated data properly and at the same time.þ * The Auto Configure function of the Robot Controller is now template based. If there is a commonly used robot configuration, a template can be created so that the Auto Configure mechanism can be used to quickly configure a robot of this type.þ * The logic to detect a runaway op mode (both in the LinearOpMode and OpMode types) and to abort the run, then auto recover has been improved/implemented.þ * Fix has been incorporated so that Logitech F310 gamepad mappings will be correct for Marshmallow users.þþ**************************************************************************************þþRelease 16.07.08þþ * For the ftc_app project, the gradle files have been modified to support Android Studio 2.1.x.þþþþ**************************************************************************************þþRelease 16.03.30þþ * For the MIT App Inventor, the design blocks have new icons that better represent the function of each design component.þ * Some changes were made to the shutdown logic to ensure the robust shutdown of some of our USB services.þ * A change was made to LinearOpMode so as to allow a given instance to be executed more than once, which is required for the App Inventor.þ * Javadoc improved/updated.þþ**************************************************************************************þþRelease 16.03.09þþ * Changes made to make the FTC SDK synchronous (significant change!)þ - waitOneFullHardwareCycle() and waitForNextHardwareCycle() are no longer needed and have been deprecated.þ - runOpMode() (for a LinearOpMode) is now decoupled from the system's hardware read/write thread.þ - loop() (for an OpMode) is now decoupled from the system's hardware read/write thread.þ - Methods are synchronous.þ - For example, if you call setMode(DcMotorController.RunMode.RESET_ENCODERS) for a motor, the encoder is guaranteed to be reset when the method call is complete.þ - For legacy module (NXT compatible), user no longer has to toggle between read and write modes when reading from or writing to a legacy device.þ * Changes made to enhance reliability/robustness during ESD event.þ * Changes made to make code thread safe.þ * Debug keystore added so that user-generated robot controller APKs will all use the same signed key (to avoid conflicts if a team has multiple developer laptops for example).þ * Firmware version information for Modern Robotics modules are now logged.þ * Changes made to improve USB comm reliability and robustness.þ * Added support for voltage indicator for legacy (NXT-compatible) motor controllers.þ * Changes made to provide auto stop capabilities for op modes.þ - A LinearOpMode class will stop when the statements in runOpMode() are complete. User does not have to push the stop button on the driver station.þ - If an op mode is stopped by the driver station, but there is a run away/uninterruptible thread persisting, the app will log an error message then force itself to crash to stop the runaway thread.þ * Driver Station UI modified to display lowest measured voltage below current voltage (12V battery).þ * Driver Station UI modified to have color background for current voltage (green=good, yellow=caution, red=danger, extremely low voltage).þ * javadoc improved (edits and additional classes).þ * Added app build time to About activity for driver station and robot controller apps.þ * Display local IP addresses on Driver Station About activity.þ * Added I2cDeviceSynchImpl.þ * Added I2cDeviceSync interface.þ * Added seconds() and milliseconds() to ElapsedTime for clarity.þ * Added getCallbackCount() to I2cDevice.þ * Added missing clearI2cPortActionFlag.þ * Added code to create log messages while waiting for LinearOpMode shutdown.þ * Fix so Wifi Direct Config activity will no longer launch multiple times.þ * Added the ability to specify an alternate i2c address in software for the Modern Robotics gyro.þþ**************************************************************************************þþRelease 16.02.09þþ * Improved battery checker feature so that voltage values get refreshed regularly (every 250 msec) on Driver Station (DS) user interface.þ * Improved software so that Robot Controller (RC) is much more resilient and “self-healing” to USB disconnects:þ - If user attempts to start/restart RC with one or more module missing, it will display a warning but still start up.þ - When running an op mode, if one or more modules gets disconnected, the RC & DS will display warnings,and robot will keep on working in spite of the missing module(s).þ - If a disconnected module gets physically reconnected the RC will auto detect the module and the user will regain control of the recently connected module.þ - Warning messages are more helpful (identifies the type of module that’s missing plus its USB serial number). þ * Code changes to fix the null gamepad reference when users try to reference the gamepads in the init() portion of their op mode.þ * NXT light sensor output is now properly scaled. Note that teams might have to readjust their light threshold values in their op modes.þ * On DS user interface, gamepad icon for a driver will disappear if the matching gamepad is disconnected or if that gamepad gets designated as a different driver.þ * Robot Protocol (ROBOCOL) version number info is displayed in About screen on RC and DS apps.þ * Incorporated a display filter on pairing screen to filter out devices that don’t use the “-“ format. This filter can be turned off to show all WiFi Direct devices.þ * Updated text in License file.þ * Fixed formatting error in OpticalDistanceSensor.toString().þ * Fixed issue on with a blank (“”) device name that would disrupt WiFi Direct Pairing.þ * Made a change so that the WiFi info and battery info can be displayed more quickly on the DS upon connecting to RC.þ * Improved javadoc generation.þ * Modified code to make it easier to support language localization in the future.þþ**************************************************************************************þþRelease 16.01.04þþ * Updated compileSdkVersion for appsþ * Prevent Wifi from entering power saving modeþ * removed unused import from driver stationþ * Corrrected "Dead zone" joystick code.þ * LED.getDeviceName and .getConnectionInfo() return nullþ * apps check for ROBOCOL_VERSION mismatchþ * Fix for Telemetry also has off-by-one errors in its data string sizing / short size limitations errorþ * User telemetry output is sorted.þ * added formatting variants to DbgLog and RobotLog APIsþ * code modified to allow for a long list of op mode names.þ * changes to improve thread safety of RobocolDatagramSocketþ * Fix for "missing hardware leaves robot controller disconnected from driver station" errorþ * fix for "fast tapping of Init/Start causes problems" (toast is now only instantiated on UI thread).þ * added some log statements for thread life cycle.þ * moved gamepad reset logic inside of initActiveOpMode() for robustnessþ * changes made to mitigate risk of race conditions on public methods.þ * changes to try and flag when WiFi Direct name contains non-printable characters.þ * fix to correct race condition between .run() and .close() in ReadWriteRunnableStandard.þ * updated FTDI driverþ * made ReadWriteRunnableStanard interface public.þ * fixed off-by-one errors in Command constructorþ * moved specific hardware implmentations into their own package.þ * moved specific gamepad implemnatations to the hardware library.þ * changed LICENSE file to new BSD version.þ * fixed race condition when shutting down Modern Robotics USB devices.þ * methods in the ColorSensor classes have been synchronized.þ * corrected isBusy() status to reflect end of motion.þ * corrected "back" button keycode.þ * the notSupported() method of the GyroSensor class was changed to protected (it should not be public).þþþ**************************************************************************************þþRelease 15.11.04.001þþ * Added Support for Modern Robotics Gyro.þ - The GyroSensor class now supports the MR Gyro Sensor.þ - Users can access heading data (about Z axis)þ - Users can also access raw gyro data (X, Y, & Z axes).þ - Example MRGyroTest.java op mode included.þ * Improved error messagesþ - More descriptive error messages for exceptions in user code.þ * Updated DcMotor APIþ * Enable read mode on new address in setI2cAddressþ * Fix so that driver station app resets the gamepads when switching op modes.þ * USB-related code changes to make USB comm more responsive and to display more explicit error messages.þ - Fix so that USB will recover properly if the USB bus returns garbage data.þ - Fix USB initializtion race condition.þ - Better error reporting during FTDI open.þ - More explicit messages during USB failures.þ - Fixed bug so that USB device is closed if event loop teardown method was not called.þ * Fixed timer UI issueþ * Fixed duplicate name UI bug (Legacy Module configuration).þ * Fixed race condition in EventLoopManager.þ * Fix to keep references stable when updating gamepad.þ * For legacy Matrix motor/servo controllers removed necessity of appending "Motor" and "Servo" to controller names.þ * Updated HT color sensor driver to use constants from ModernRoboticsUsbLegacyModule class.þ * Updated MR color sensor driver to use constants from ModernRoboticsUsbDeviceInterfaceModule class.þ * Correctly handle I2C Address change in all color sensorsþ * Updated/cleaned up op modes.þ - Updated comments in LinearI2cAddressChange.java example op mode.þ - Replaced the calls to "setChannelMode" with "setMode" (to match the new of the DcMotor method).þ - Removed K9AutoTime.java op mode.þ - Added MRGyroTest.java op mode (demonstrates how to use MR Gyro Sensor).þ - Added MRRGBExample.java op mode (demonstrates how to use MR Color Sensor).þ - Added HTRGBExample.java op mode (demonstrates how to use HT legacy color sensor).þ - Added MatrixControllerDemo.java (demonstrates how to use legacy Matrix controller).þ * Updated javadoc documentation.þ * Updated release .apk files for Robot Controller and Driver Station apps.þþT. EngþNovember 5, 2015þþ**************************************************************************************þþRelease 15.10.06.002þþ * Added support for Legacy Matrix 9.6V motor/servo controller.þ * Cleaned up build.gradle file.þ * Minor UI and bug fixes for driver station and robot controller apps.þ * Throws error if Ultrasonic sensor (NXT) is not configured for legacy module port 4 or 5.þþT. EngþOctober 6, 2015þþ**************************************************************************************þþIn this latest version of the FTC SDK (20150803_001) the following changes should be noted:þþ * New user interfaces for FTC Driver Station and FTC Robot Controller apps.þ * An init() method is added to the OpMode class.þ - For this release, init() is triggered right before the start() method.þ - Eventually, the init() method will be triggered when the user presses an "INIT" button on driver station.þ - The init() and loop() methods are now required (i.e., need to be overridden in the user's op mode).þ - The start() and stop() methods are optional.þ * A new LinearOpMode class is introduced.þ - Teams can use the LinearOpMode mode to create a linear (not event driven) program model.þ - Teams can use blocking statements like Thread.sleep() within a linear op mode.þ * The API for the Legacy Module and Core Device Interface Module have been updated.þ - Support for encoders with the Legacy Module is now working.þ * The hardware loop has been updated for better performance.þþþT. EngþAugust 3, 2015

readme: GCE The Biography of I I am looking forward to learning the true value of an education giving back to the community, as well as develop as a lifelong learner. I'm an Army Brat born in Fort Hood, Texas. I am an older brother who was raised by two parents from Mayaguez, Puerto Rico. I often try to spend time with family. I grew up in Germany, Maryland, and Virginia. I have traveled from New York to Florida. I was an altar boy at Catholic Church in Odenton. I was a Boy Scout in Laurel, Maryland. I played youth sports with the Bowie Boys and Girls Club including basketball and football. I attend six different elementary schools. I went to Robert Goddard Middle School in Greenbelt. I enjoy meeting new people and traveling plane, train or automobile. I served in the Armed Services from 2006-2008. I enjoy taking courses and advancing my education. I also enjoy volunteering at Non-Profit Organizations including Education Based Latino Outreach and Northern Virginia Family Services. I enjoy embracing my Puerto Rican heritage at Latin festivals. I have always enjoyed dancing and music. I enjoy spending time with family and friends. iBiography

readme: # FlowLayoutManagerþþFlow layout manager for RecyclerView.Supports **API 10(Android 2.3)** and above.þþ![Example vertical](flow_layout_manager_vertical.gif)þþ## Featuresþþ1. Vertical/Horizontal orientation;þ2. Custom gravity;þ3. Maximum items in line;þ4. Spaces between items and/or lines;þ5. Stores position during orientation changes;þ6. Scroll/Smooth scroll.þþ## UsageþþInstead standard layout manager use FLMFlowLayoutManager:þþ    ...þ        þ    FLMFlowLayoutManager layoutManager = new FLMFlowLayoutManager(FLMFlowLayoutManager.VERTICAL);þ        þ    RecyclerView recyclerView = (RecyclerView) findViewById(R.id.recyclerView);þ    recyclerView.setLayoutManager(layoutManager);þ    recyclerView.setAdapter(new Adapter(this));þ        þ    ...þþTo change gravity of the layout manager:þ    þ    ...þ        þ    layoutManager.setGravity(Gravity.START|Gravity.CENTER_HORIZONTAL);þ        þ    ...þþTo change maximum items count in line:þþ    ...þþ    layoutManager.setMaxItemsInLine(4);þþ    ...þþTo change spaces between items and lines:þþ    ...þþ    layoutManager.setSpacingBetweenItems(10);þ    layoutManager.setSpacingBetweenLines(10);þþ    ...þþ## LicenseþþCopyright 2018 Astrocode011235813þþ   Licensed under the Apache License, Version 2.0 (the "License");  þ   you may not use this file except in compliance with the License.  þ   You may obtain a copy of the License atþþ       http://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0þþ   Unless required by applicable law or agreed to in writing, software  þ   distributed under the License is distributed on an "AS IS" BASIS,  þ   WITHOUT WARRANTIES OR CONDITIONS OF ANY KIND, either express or implied.  þ   See the License for the specific language governing permissions and  þ   limitations under the License.

readme: HTML player (E-detailing) app.þþapp basically displays a set of local HTML pages divided into categories, accompanied by PDF andþvideo.þþthis sort of apps. is used in medical marketing CLM (Closed Loop Marketing) to market / collect surveysþon a new medical product from doctors or pharmacists.þþthe app provides the below functionality natively:þþ- HTMLs are loaded and displayed in tab bar, each tab representing a category / product from json map fileþ- a javascript bridge allows for two communication between the native app and the loaded html pageþ to send and receive dataþ- in app custom video player plays video files shipped with the app accessed from HTML href linksþ- app can switch between certain slides in different categories if a nested href points to a slideþ in another category or load an external web page if not found in the local html assetsþ- bottom recycler view displays thumbnails of the loaded category set pages & can be used for quick navigationþ- app copies PDF files to external storage once the app is loaded for 1st time, files can be launched fromþ links in the html pages and opened in respective pdf file reader if found on users device or display message if no apps found
