description: Application in Java that converts wikitext documents into HTML documents.
readme:
# [WikiHTML](https://julianmendez.github.io/wikihtml/)þþ[![build](https://travis-ci.org/julianmendez/wikihtml.png?branch=master)](https://travis-ci.org/julianmendez/wikihtml)þ[![maven central](https://maven-badges.herokuapp.com/maven-central/de.tu-dresden.inf.lat.wikihtml/wikihtml/badge.svg)](https://search.maven.org/#search|ga|1|g%3A%22de.tu-dresden.inf.lat.wikihtml%22)þ[![license](https://img.shields.io/badge/license-Apache%202.0-blue.svg)](https://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0.txt)þ[![license](https://img.shields.io/badge/license-LGPL%203.0-blue.svg)](https://www.gnu.org/licenses/lgpl-3.0.txt)þþ**WikiHTML** is a Java library and executable standalone application that converts a document in wiki text format to an HTML document.þþþ## Downloadþþ* [executable JAR file](https://sourceforge.net/projects/latitude/files/wikihtml/0.1.0/wikihtml-0.1.0.jar/download)þ* [The Central Repository](https://repo1.maven.org/maven2/de/tu-dresden/inf/lat/wikihtml/)þ* as dependency:þþ```xmlþþ de.tu-dresden.inf.lat.wikihtmlþ wikihtmlþ 0.1.0þþ```þþþ## UseþþIt can be used as a Java library or from the command line. For example, use:þþ```þjava -jar wikihtml-0.1.0.jar inputfile.text outputfile.htmlþ```þþto create a new HTML file from the command line, and useþþ```þjava -jar wikihtml-0.1.0.jar inputoutputfile.htmlþ```þþto just update an HTML file with embedded wiki text.þþþ## DescriptionþþWiki markup, also wikitext or wikicode, is a markup language for wiki-based pages. It is a simplified human-friendly substitute of HTML. This library reads text written in this markup language and produces an HTML document. There are several "dialects" of wiki markup. This library implements a subset of the language used by the [MediaWiki](https://www.mediawiki.org/wiki/MediaWiki) software.þþThe application generates the HTML document with the original wiki markup source code inside. Technically, the source code will be between: ``. This allows to update an HTML file using the source in the same file.þþThis could be useful, for example, when maintaining documentation of a project. The files can be easily edited using a text editor, but after processing them with this library, they can be viewed with a browser.þþWhen using only the wiki formatting, the produced document is an [XHTML 1.1](https://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml11/) document.þþþ#### SectionsþþSections are marked at the beginning of a line. The heading should be between a sequence of equals signs (=). Using more equals signs makes the heading smaller. For example:þþ| wiki markup | HTML |þ|:------------------------------|:------------------------|þ| `= heading 1 =` |

heading 1

|þ| `== heading 2 ==` |

heading 2

|þ| `=== heading 3 ===` |

heading 3

|þ| `==== heading 4 ====` |

heading 4

|þ| `===== heading 5 =====` |
heading 5
|þ| `====== heading 6 ======` |
heading 6
|þþþ#### Line breaksþþA new line is marked with two new lines. For example,þþ```þTwo linesþtogetherþare not considered different lines.þ```þþis renderedþþ```þTwo lines together are not considered different lines.þ```þþbut:þþ```þOne line.þþAnother line.þ```þþis renderedþþ```þOne line.þAnother line.þ```þþþ#### Indented textþþText can be indented using colons (:) at the beginning of the line. For example:þþ```þ: item 1þ: item 2þ:: item 2.1þ:: item 2.2þ::: item 2.2.1þ: item 3þ```þþproduces:þþ```þ item 1þ item 2þ item 2.1þ item 2.2þ item 2.2.1þ item3þ```þþþ#### Unordered listsþþItems in a list are marked with asterisks (*) at the beginning of the line. A subitem is marked with more asterisks. For example:þþ```þ* item 1þ* item 2þ** item 2.1þ** item 2.2þ*** item 2.2.1þ* item 3þ```þþis rendered asþþ* item 1þ* item 2þ * item 2.1þ * item 2.2þ * item 2.2.1þ* item 3þþþ#### Ordered listsþþNumbered items are marked with hash signs (#) at the beginning of the line. A subitem is marked with more hash signs. For example:þþ```þþ# item 1þþ# item 2þþ## item 2.1þþ## item 2.2þþ### item 2.2.1þþ# item 3þ```þþis rendered asþþ1. item 1þ2. item 2þ 1. item 2.1þ 2. item 2.2þ 1. item 2.2.1þ3. item 3þþþ#### Text formattingþþThe text can be formatted using apostrophes (') according to the following table:þþ| wiki markup | HTML |þ|:------------------------------|:------------------------|þ| `''italics''` | *italics* |þ| `'''bold'''` | **bold** |þ| `'''''bold italics'''''` | ***bold italics*** |þþþ#### LinksþþLinks can be marked with square backets ([ ]). For example:þ`[https://www.wikipedia.org Wikipedia]` renders [Wikipedia](https://www.wikipedia.org).þIf the brackets are omitted, the URI is shown directly. For example: `https://www.wikipedia.org` renders https://www.wikipedia.org .þþThe double square brackets ([[ ]]) are rendered as local links.þþþ#### TablesþþThis wiki text:þþ```markdownþ{| border="1"þ| 4 || 9 || 2þ|-þ| 3 || 5 || 7þ|-þ| 8 || 1 || 6þ|}þ```þþproduces the following table:þþþþþþ
492
357
816
þþ(without the white and gray alternation of lines)þþThe following wiki text is not implemented in MediaWiki, but it also produces the same table:þþ* using semicolon:þþ```markdownþ{||; border="1"þ4;9;2þ3;5;7þ8;1;6þ||}þ```þþ* using comma:þþ```markdownþ{||, border="1"þ4,9,2þ3,5,7þ8,1,6þ||}þ```þþ* using tabs:þþ```markdownþ{|| border="1"þ4 9 2þ3 5 7þ8 1 6þ||}þ```þþþ#### nowikiþþThe pair of tags ``...`` is used to mark text without using the wiki formatting. For example:þ`'''non-bold'''` is not in bold.þþþ#### VariablesþþThe following MediaWiki variables are implemented:þþ| name | example | meaning |þ|:----------------------------------|:-----------------|:-----------------------------------------------------------------------|þ|{{CURRENTDAY}} | `1` | Displays the current day in numeric form. |þ|{{CURRENTDAY2}} | `01` | Same as {{CURRENTDAY}}, but with leading zero (01 .. 31). |þ|{{CURRENTDAYNAME}} | `Friday` | Name of the day in the language of the project or English. |þ|{{CURRENTDOW}} | `5` | Same as {{CURRENTDAYNAME}}, but as a number (0=Sunday, 1=Monday...). |þ|{{CURRENTMONTH}} | `01` | The number 01 .. 12 of the month. |þ|{{CURRENTMONTHABBREV}}| `Jan` | Same as {{CURRENTMONTH}}, but in abbreviated form as Jan .. Dec. |þ|{{CURRENTMONTHNAME}} |`January` | Same as {{CURRENTMONTH}}, but in named form January .. December. |þ|{{CURRENTTIME}} | `16:03` | The current time (00:00 .. 23:59). |þ|{{CURRENTHOUR}} | `16` | The current hour (00 .. 23). |þ|{{CURRENTWEEK}} | `1` | Number of the current week (1-53) according to ISO 8601 with no leading zero.|þ|{{CURRENTYEAR}} | `2016` | Returns the current year. |þ|{{CURRENTTIMESTAMP}} | `20160101160345` | ISO 8601 time stamp |þþIn addition, the {{LOCAL...}} variables are also implemented:{{LOCALDAY}}, {{LOCALDAY2}}, ... , {{LOCALTIMESTAMP}}. For example, in UTC+1 {{CURRENTTIMESTAMP}} returns `20160101160345`, while {{LOCALTIMESTAMP}} returns `20160101170345`.þþþ#### HTMLþþHTML code can also be inserted directly. For example:þ`bold` is the same as `'''bold'''`, and `λ` is rendered λ.þþþ## ExampleþþThe file [mupuzzle.text](https://github.com/julianmendez/wikihtml/blob/master/wikihtml/src/test/resources/mupuzzle.text) has the following wiki text:þþ```þ== MIU system ==þ(see [https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MU_puzzle MU puzzle])þþþ# ''x''I → ''x''IUþþ# M''x'' → M''xx''þþ# ''x''III''y'' → ''x''U''y''þþ# ''x''UU''y'' → ''xy''þ```þþand is translated to the following HTML document:þþ```htmlþþþþþþþþ þ þþþ
þþ

MIU system

þ (see MU puzzle)
þþ
    þ
  1. xI → xIU
    2. þ
  2. Mx → Mxx
    3. þ
  3. xIIIy → xUy
    4. þ
  4. xUUy → xy
    5. þ
þ
þþ
þþþ```þþThe file [example.text](https://github.com/julianmendez/wikihtml/blob/master/wikihtml/src/test/resources/example.text) has more examples.þþþ## Source codeþþTo checkout and compile the project, use:þþ```þ$ git clone https://github.com/julianmendez/wikihtml.gitþ$ cd wikihtmlþ$ mvn clean installþ```þþThe created executable library, its sources, and its Javadoc will be in `wikihtml/target`.þþTo compile the project offline, first download the dependencies:þþ```þ$ mvn dependency:go-offlineþ```þþand once offline, use:þþ```þ$ mvn --offline clean installþ```þþThe bundles uploaded to [Sonatype](https://oss.sonatype.org/) are created with:þþ```þ$ mvn clean install -DperformRelease=trueþ```þþand then:þþ```þ$ cd wikihtml/targetþ$ jar -cf bundle.jar wikihtml-*þ```þþThe version number is updated with:þþ```þ$ mvn versions:set -DnewVersion=NEW_VERSIONþ```þþwhere *NEW_VERSION* is the new version.þþþ## ArchitectureþþThe library reads a wiki text and creates a `WikiDocument`.þIt extracts the wiki text from the given input and processes it line by line.þþEach line is transformed into a `ConversionToken`. Each token is processed by a pipeline of objects where each one is a `Renderer`. Each renderer (`-Renderer`) processes each conversion token producing a list of conversion tokens. These are the input for the next renderer, if any. Some renderers are parameterized and grouped (`-GroupRenderer`). Some renderers process whole lines (in package `...line`) and some renderers process pieces of lines (in package `...part`).þþFor example, all variables are processed by `...part.DateVariableRenderer`, but the headings are processed by a group of renderers (`...line.HeadingGroupRenderer`) composed by 6 renderers (h1, h2, ..., h6), where each one is a `...line.HeadingRenderer`.þþþ## Authorþþ[Julian Mendez](https://julianmendez.github.io)þþþ## Licensesþþ[Apache License Version 2.0](https://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0.txt), [GNU Lesser General Public License version 3](https://www.gnu.org/licenses/lgpl-3.0.txt)þþþ## Release notesþþSee [release notes](https://julianmendez.github.io/wikihtml/RELEASE-NOTES.html).þþþ## ContactþþIn case you need more information, please contact @julianmendez .

# Zip-RangeþþThis program reduces a given list of 5-digit ZIP code ranges to the minimum amount of ranges that encompasses the original input.þþ## Getting StartedþþRun the following commands to produce a .jar file and execute the program.þþ```þmvn compileþmvn exec:javaþ```þþ## Accepted InputþþRanges must be provided containing 5-digit ZIP codes in the following format.þþ```þ[12345,67890] [23456,78901] etc...þ```þþ## Running the testsþþTo run unit tests, use the following command.þþ```þmvn testþ```þþ## Authorsþþ* **Jonathan Quiambao** - *Initial work* - [jcquiambao](https://github.com/jcquiambao)

# EasyCounterMasterþþMaybe this is the best app for Android.þOf course, this is a simple counter, but hell, everything ingenious is simple.þEasyCounter - reliable as AK-47 and indispensable in certain situations.þþ![screen 1](1.png)þ![screen 2](2.png)þ![screen 3](3.png)

description: Dendrite is a library for querying large datasets on a single host at near-interactive speeds.
readme: # DendriteþþDendrite is a library for querying large datasets on a single host at near-interactive speeds.þþIt attempts to be:þþ- __simple__: there is no configuration, no services to run, and reads are as simple as opening a file;þ- __fast__: there are few bottlenecks and reads will usually make good use of all available CPU cores;þ- __compact__: the file size is typically 30-40% lower than the equivalent compressed JSON;þ- __flexible__: it supports the same rich set of nested data structures as [EDN][];þ- __write once, read often__: optimizations are run at write-time to ensure fast read-time performance.þþ[EDN]: https://github.com/edn-format/ednþþþThe current implementation is in Java but only exposes a Clojure API. In the future, I would like to expose aþclean Java interface and build a C implementation for non-JVM code.þþThis code has been in used in production for over a year. It has been successfully used both as a buildingþblock in large ETL systems and for ad-hoc data-science studies. However, prior to the 1.0 release, no effortþwill be made at preserving backwards compatibility of APIs or binary compatibility of files.þþDendrite implements the record shredding and assembly ideas from Google's [Dremel paper][Dremel] [1]. Queryingþfor only small parts of the stored records can be up to several orders of magnitude faster than fullyþdeserializing each record and pulling out the desired information. Furthermore, this library also borrows many ideas from the [Parquet][] project, an implementation of theþDremel file format for Hadoop. Unlike Parquet, Dendrite is not tied to any particular ecosystem and isþdesigned to be a small library with no external dependencies.þþþ[Dremel]: http://research.google.com/pubs/pub36632.htmlþ[Parquet]: http://parquet.io/þþ__Status update__ (March 23, 2018): For personal reasons, I haven't been able to work on this project in theþpast two years. However, I have been accumulating ideas for the next iteration and hope to resume progressþlater this year.þþ[![Build Status](https://travis-ci.org/jwhitbeck/dendrite.png)](https://travis-ci.org/jwhitbeck/dendrite.png)þþ## DocumentationþþWork-in-progress documentation and benchmarks are available at [dendrite.tech](http://dendrite.tech).þþ## Roadmap to 1.0þþ- Improve writer performance.þ- Cleanly separate clojure and java code.þ- Expose a good Java APIþ- Preserve presence/absence of record keysþ- Add indexingþþ## Referencesþþ1. Sergey Melnik, Andrey Gubarev, Jing Jing Long, Geoffrey Romer, Shiva Shivakumar, Matt Tolton, Theo Vassilakis.þ[Dremel: Interactive Analysis of Web-Scale Datasets][Dremel].þIn _Proc. VLDB_, 2010þþ## LicenseþþCopyright © 2013-2017 John WhitbeckþþDistributed under the Eclipse Public License, the same as Clojure.

description: Personal project for 17-month in-depth Java training
readme: # java-trainingþþPersonal project for 17-month Java training hosted by my company.þþ## Training detailsþþThe training focused on understanding Java language specifications and good API designs. It was hosted by my company from Oct 2016 to Sep 2017 (11 sessions) and from Apr 2018 to Aug 2018 (6 sessions) and conducted in Japanese.þþ### What I did as an attendeeþ* Attending at monthly sessionsþ* Completing assignments every monthþ  * Reading specified chapters of reading materials and listing questionsþ  * Coding exercises listed in the reading materials (including unit tests)þ  * Designing and implementing a GUI app with different requirementsþ* Completing final GUI project and giving a presentation (I won the first prize!)þþ### Reading materialsþ  * "The Java Programming Language, 4th Edition" by Ken Arnold, James Gosling, and David Holmesþ  * "Java SE 8 for the Really Impatient" by Cay S. Horstmannþ  * "Java 2 Standard Edition 5.0 Tiger―拡張された言語仕様について" by Yoshiki Shibataþ  * "Effective Java (3rd Edition)" by Joshua Blochþþ## Contentsþþ* `src/jpl` : Exercises from "The Java Programming Language, 4th Edition"þ* `test/jpl` : Unit tests for the aboveþ* `src/java8` : Exercises from "Java SE 8 for the Really Impatient"þ* `test/java8` : Unit tests for the aboveþ* `src/gui` : GUI apps with AWT, Swing and JavaFXþ* `src/interpret` : A GUI app which operates Java classes and functions using `java.lang.reflection`þ* `src/clock` : The final GUI projectþ  * Pomodoro timer for pair programming using JavaFXþ    * Downloadþ      * For Windows: [pomopomo.exe](https://github.com/YukiThornton/java-training/raw/master/src/clock/pomopomo.exe)þ      * For Mac OS:  [pomopomo.app](https://github.com/YukiThornton/java-training/raw/master/src/clock/pomopomo.app)

description: This is for 2018 spring UCB 61b course
readme: # UCB_61b_18SpringþThis is my presonal study note for 2018 spring UCB 61b course.þþCourse Description:þIn CS61B, we’re concerned also with engineering. An engineer, it is said, is someone who can do for a dime what any fool can do for a dollar. Much of 61B will be concerned with the tradeoffs in time and memory for a variety of methods for structuring data. We’ll also be concerned with the engineering knowledge and skills needed to build and maintain moderately large programs.

# Web ProgrammingþþFinal Examination Exercise for the 4th semester course, Web Programming, University of Piraeus.þThe exercise asked us to develop a website for patients, and doctors. Patients had the ability to book an appointment, cancel an appointment, view their info and their appointments. Doctors had the ability to view their appointments, plan which days the accept appointments and cancel their appointments. Finally, there was an admin that could log in the system to add more doctors or new patients. People had the ability to either register or log in with their credentials.þI used PostgreSQL as the database where data was stored. Passwords were encrypted(Hash and Salt) inside the database.þþExercise was graded 9/10 due to some minor bugs which were later fixed.

The resulting jar can be run as follows:þþ```þjava -jar target/mass_transit-1.0-SNAPSHOT-jar-with-dependencies.jarþ```þþThis will start a webserver serving our application on [http://localhost:4567](http://localhost:4567).þþ## Generate Database data`þþData for the backend is stored in a PostGres SQL Database.þThe name of the database is "martadb". To setup the database from þscratch (using the official VM, from the base repository directory)þþ```þpsql martadbþ\i martadb_structure.backupþ\i martadb_schema_new_tablesþ\i create_random_table_data.sqlþ```þþRandom data is generated using a python script. # Golf Stat Tracker for the Wenatchee Golf and Country Clubþ þ Here is the official beta release for this open source application! There's still bugs and a ton of code refactoring to do, but that's what we have betas for.þ þ þ Here is the title screenþ þ þþþ## Scorecard ActivityþþThe scorecard activity is where most of the work gets done. Its where scores are tracked during a round and how the user indicates more specific stats like hitting the fairway or sand traps. This activity will also mark scores accordingly with squares or circles for bogeys and birdies respectively. Additionally in the center of the screen the user is told how far away they are from the front center and back of the green for the hole they have selected.þþþþThe checkbox icon in the action bar will prompt the user if they want to save a round, which is done on a Room database which is maintained locally on the device.þþþþþ## Main Stats ActivityþþHere is where the average overall statistics are displayed. For a golfer this will be essessentially the assessment of how good they are as a player. These averages are tracked with a file saved to internal storage using a serialized data object. This activity holds two more buttons for more detailed statistics.þþþþþ## Look at old roundsþþHere the user can go back and look at how they did on past rounds. You can see the score, fairway and green in regulation percentages, putts, and sand shots on each hole. Select a hole to get statistics for that hole specifically.þþþþ## Track statistics hole by holeþþOn this page users are able to see how they do on each individual hole over time. These stats are meant to show the user what holes they need to improve on, and which ones they can count on for low scores. More detailed statistics will be added.þþþþþþþ## Future workþþI will be adding more detailed statistical tracking to the stats pages, and making them easier to understand and view. I also want to track the best rounds for individual statistics, so the user can look at their glory rounds. The UI needs some redesign to differentiate the buttons and text boxes. There is a lot of behind the scenes stuff that can be improved, especially as this is my first real project in Java and my first time working with Android Studio. I also still need to get official pictures of the logo to use for the app icon and the main activity. I just took a picture with my phone of the logo, since I'm having trouble getting a hold of the official logo and other official images.

= Gradle Site Plugin image:https://travis-ci.org/gradle-guides/gradle-site-plugin.svg?branch=master["Build Status", link="https://travis-ci.org/gradle-guides/gradle-site-plugin"] image:https://img.shields.io/badge/build-scan-green.svg["Build Scan", link="https://gradle.com/s/thgfe3dxihijo"]þþA sample Gradle plugin demonstrating established techniques and practices for plugin development as described in the following guides:þþ- link:https://guides.gradle.org/designing-gradle-plugins/[Designing Gradle plugins]þ- link:https://guides.gradle.org/implementing-gradle-plugins/[Implementing Gradle plugins]þ- link:https://guides.gradle.org/testing-gradle-plugins/[Testing Gradle plugins]þþ== FunctionalityþþThe plugin provides a task for generating a web page that derives information about the project e.g. applied plugins and available tasks. While minimalistic in functionality it serves as a show case for demonstrating best practices for Gradle plugin development. A site generated for a sample project can be viewed link:http://gradle-guides.github.io/gradle-site-plugin/sample/index.html[here].þþTIP: The plugin is link:https://plugins.gradle.org/plugin/com.github.gradle-guides.site[available on the Gradle plugin portal] for public consumption.þþ== Usage exampleþþThe plugin can be applied with by identifier `org.gradle.site`. Default values can be configured with the help of the provided extension `org.gradle.plugins.site.SitePluginExtension`. To generate the web page run the task named `generateSite` e.g. `gradle generateSite`.þþIMPORTANT: The plugin requires a Gradle version of 4.0 or higher. All features that are based on Gradle 4.0 are explicitlyþmarked above. All other features will work with earlier versions of Gradle.þþ```þapply plugin: 'com.github.gradle-guides.site'þþsite {þ    outputDir = file("$buildDir/site")þ    websiteUrl = 'http://gradle.org'þ    vcsUrl = 'https://github.com/gradle-guides/gradle-site-plugin'þ}þ```þþ== Applied techniques and practicesþþ- Production source code written in Java, test code written in Groovy with link:http://spockframework.org/[Spock framework].þ- Reusable logic written as binary plugin.þ- Usage of the Plugin Development plugin to simplify plugin development. [link:https://github.com/gradle-guides/gradle-site-plugin/blob/master/build.gradle#L3[Code] | link:https://guides.gradle.org/implementing-gradle-plugins/#plugin-development-plugin[More Details]]þ- Implementation of tasks as custom task type. [link:https://github.com/gradle-guides/gradle-site-plugin/blob/master/src/main/java/org/gradle/plugins/site/tasks/SiteGenerate.java[Code] | link:https://guides.gradle.org/implementing-gradle-plugins/#prefer_writing_and_using_custom_task_types[More Details]]þ- Usage of input and output properties to enable incremental tasks. [link:https://github.com/gradle-guides/gradle-site-plugin/blob/master/src/main/java/org/gradle/plugins/site/tasks/SiteGenerate.java[Code] | link:https://guides.gradle.org/implementing-gradle-plugins/#benefiting_from_incremental_tasks[More Details]]þ- Usage of an extension to capture user-configurable values. [link:https://github.com/gradle-guides/gradle-site-plugin/blob/master/src/main/java/org/gradle/plugins/site/SitePlugin.java#L23[Code] | link:https://guides.gradle.org/designing-gradle-plugins/#convention_over_configuration[More Details]]þ- Mapping of extension property values to custom task properties. [link:https://github.com/gradle-guides/gradle-site-plugin/blob/master/src/main/java/org/gradle/plugins/site/SitePlugin.java#L96-L98[Code] | link:https://guides.gradle.org/implementing-gradle-plugins/#capturing_user_input_to_configure_plugin_runtime_behavior[More Details]] image:https://img.shields.io/badge/4.0-feature-blue.svg[4.0 feature]þ- Reacting to plugins instead of applying plugins. [link:https://github.com/gradle-guides/gradle-site-plugin/blob/master/src/main/java/org/gradle/plugins/site/SitePlugin.java#L42[Code] | link:https://guides.gradle.org/implementing-gradle-plugins/#reacting_to_plugins[More Details]]þ- Declaration of appropriate plugin identifiers. [link:https://github.com/gradle-guides/gradle-site-plugin/blob/master/src/main/resources/META-INF/gradle-plugins/com.github.gradle-guides.site.properties[Code] | link:https://guides.gradle.org/implementing-gradle-plugins/#assigning_appropriate_plugin_identifiers[More Details]]þ- Functional testing with TestKit. [link:https://github.com/gradle-guides/gradle-site-plugin/blob/master/build.gradle#L6[Code] | link:https://docs.gradle.org/current/userguide/test_kit.html[More Details]]þ- Publication of the plugin artifacts to the Gradle plugin portal [link:https://github.com/gradle-guides/gradle-site-plugin/blob/master/gradle/publishing-portal.gradle[Code] | link:https://guides.gradle.org/publishing-plugins-to-gradle-plugin-portal/[More Details]]þ- Continuous Integration of plugin code with link:https://travis-ci.org/[Travis CI]. þþ# OCB-ToolsþþOCB-Tools er et sæt tools og libraries som har til formål at effektivisere arbejdet med Opencat-business modulet.þþModulet skal kunne udføres på følgende platforme:þþ- Windows.þ- Linux.þ- Mac OS X.þþSkabeloner:þþ- Sikring af syntaks.þ- Sikring af valideringsregler og konfiguration af deres parametre.þ- Sikring at en skabelon kan validere bestemte poster korrekt. F.eks. at en bog-skabelon faktisk kan validereþforskellige bøger korrekt.þþJavaScript:þþ- Eksekvering af JavaScript's unittests.þþ## OCB KommandoerþþþOCB-Tools består af en række kommandolinjeværktøjer som kan anvendes til det daglige arbejde med Opencat-business.þþNedenståendeþþ- **ocb-tt**: Udførelse af tests for skabeloner.þ- **ocb-record**: CRUD af poster som skal bruges i testcases.þ- **ocb-template**: CRUD af skabeloner.þþDatabaser:þþ- **ocb-rr**: CRUD af råpostdatabasen.þ- **ocb-holdings**: CRUD af holdingsdatabasen.þþWebservices:þþ- **ocb-os**: Kommando til at kalde OpenSearch.þ- **ocb-forsrights**: Kommando til at kalde Forsrights.þ- **ocb-fbs**: Kommando til at kalde Build eller Update.þþ## OCB LibrariesþþþOCB Libraries har til formål at sikre at kode som anvendes op tværs af OCB kommandoer eller Opencat-services (Update ogþBuild) anvendes på samme måde.þþFølgende libraries bruges af både OCB-Tools og Opencat-services:þþ- **ocb-scripter**: Library til at embedde det JavaScript som er i Opencat-business.

# react-native-ad-manager (Fork of react-native-admob - only supports ad manager)þþA react-native module for Google DFP Banners.þþ## InstallationþþYou can use npm or Yarn to install the latest beta version:þþ**Yarn:**þþ yarn add react-native-admob@nextþþIn order to use this library, you have to link it to your project first. There's excellent documentation on how to do this in the [React Native Docs](https://facebook.github.io/react-native/docs/linking-libraries-ios.html#content).þþ### iOSþþFor iOS you will have to add the [Google Mobile Ads SDK](https://developers.google.com/admob/ios/quick-start#import_the_mobile_ads_sdk) to your Xcode project.þþ### AndroidþþOn Android the AdMob library code is part of Play Services, which is automatically added when this library is linked.þþ## Usageþþ```jsxþimport { PublisherBanner } from 'react-native-ad-manager'þþ// Display a DFP Publisher bannerþ console.error(error)}þ onAppEvent={event => console.log(event.name, event.info)}þ/>þþ```þþFor a full example reference to the [example project](Example).þþ## Referenceþþ### AdMobBannerþþ#### Propertiesþþ##### `adSize`þþ*Corresponding to [iOS framework banner size constants](https://developers.google.com/admob/ios/banner)*þþþ þ þ þ þ þ þ þ þ þ þ þ þ þ þ þ þ þ þ þ þ þ þ þ þ þ þ þ þ þ þ þ þ þ þ þ þ þ þ þ þ þ þ þ þ þ þ
ValueDescriptionAvailabilitySize (WxH)
bannerStandard BannerPhones and Tablets320x50
largeBannerLarge BannerPhones and Tablets320x100
mediumRectangleIAB Medium RectanglePhones and Tablets300x250
fullBannerIAB Full-Size BannerTablets468x60
leaderboardIAB LeaderboardTablets728x90
þ smartBannerPortrait
þ smartBannerLandscapeþ 		Smart BannerPhones and TabletsScreen width x 32|50|90
þþ*Note: There is no `smartBannerPortrait` and `smartBannerLandscape` on Android. Both prop values will map to `smartBanner`*þþ##### `onAdLoaded`þþAccepts a function. Called when an ad is received.þþ##### `onAdFailedToLoad`þþAccepts a function. Called when an ad request failed.þþ##### `onAdOpened`þþAccepts a function. Called when an ad opens an overlay that covers the screen.þþ##### `onAdClosed`þþAccepts a function. Called when the user is about to return to the application after clicking on an ad.þþ##### `onAdLeftApplication`þþAccepts a function. Called when a user click will open another app (such as the App Store), backgrounding the current app.þþ##### `onSizeChange`þþAccepts a function. Called when the size of the banner changes. The function is called with an object containing the width and the height.þþþ*Above names correspond to the [Ad lifecycle event callbacks](https://developers.google.com/admob/android/banner#ad_events)*þþ### PublisherBannerþþ#### PropertiesþþSame as `AdMobBanner`, with the addition of 2 extra properties:þþ##### `onAppEvent`þþAccepts a function. Called when DFP sends an event back to the app.þþThese events may occur at any time during the ad's lifecycle, even before `onAdLoaded` is called. The function is called with an object, containing the name of the event and an info property, containing additional information.þþMore info here: https://developers.google.com/mobile-ads-sdk/docs/dfp/ios/banner#app_eventsþþ##### `validAdSizes`þþAn array of ad sizes which may be eligible to be served.

# jhipsterþThis application was generated using JHipster 5.3.1, you can find documentation and help at [https://www.jhipster.tech/documentation-archive/v5.3.1](https://www.jhipster.tech/documentation-archive/v5.3.1).þþ## DevelopmentþþBefore you can build this project, you must install and configure the following dependencies on your machine:þþ1. [Node.js][]: We use Node to run a development web server and build the project.þ   Depending on your system, you can install Node either from source or as a pre-packaged bundle.þþAfter installing Node, you should be able to run the following command to install development tools.þYou will only need to run this command when dependencies change in [package.json](package.json).þþ    npm installþþWe use npm scripts and [Webpack][] as our build system.þþRun the following commands in two separate terminals to create a blissful development experience where your browserþauto-refreshes when files change on your hard drive.þþ    ./mvnwþ    npm startþþ[Npm][] is also used to manage CSS and JavaScript dependencies used in this application. You can upgrade dependencies byþspecifying a newer version in [package.json](package.json). You can also run `npm update` and `npm install` to manage dependencies.þAdd the `help` flag on any command to see how you can use it. For example, `npm help update`.þþThe `npm run` command will list all of the scripts available to run for this project.þþ### Service workersþþService workers are commented by default, to enable them please uncomment the following code.þþ* The service worker registering script in index.htmlþþ```htmlþ<script>þ    if ('serviceWorker' in navigator) {þ        navigator.serviceWorkerþ        .register('./service-worker.js')þ        .then(function() { console.log('Service Worker Registered'); });þ    }þ</script>þ```þþNote: workbox creates the respective service worker and dynamically generate the `service-worker.js`þþ### Managing dependenciesþþFor example, to add [Leaflet][] library as a runtime dependency of your application, you would run following command:þþ    npm install --save --save-exact leafletþþTo benefit from TypeScript type definitions from [DefinitelyTyped][] repository in development, you would run following command:þþ    npm install --save-dev --save-exact @types/leafletþþThen you would import the JS and CSS files specified in library's installation instructions so that [Webpack][] knows about them:þEdit [src/main/webapp/app/vendor.ts](src/main/webapp/app/vendor.ts) file:þ~~~þimport 'leaflet/dist/leaflet.js';þ~~~þþEdit [src/main/webapp/content/css/vendor.css](src/main/webapp/content/css/vendor.css) file:þ~~~þ@import '~leaflet/dist/leaflet.css';þ~~~þNote: there are still few other things remaining to do for Leaflet that we won't detail here.þþFor further instructions on how to develop with JHipster, have a look at [Using JHipster in development][].þþ### Using angular-cliþþYou can also use [Angular CLI][] to generate some custom client code.þþFor example, the following command:þþ    ng generate component my-componentþþwill generate few files:þþ    create src/main/webapp/app/my-component/my-component.component.htmlþ    create src/main/webapp/app/my-component/my-component.component.tsþ    update src/main/webapp/app/app.module.tsþþþ## Building for productionþþTo optimize the jhipster application for production, run:þþ    ./mvnw -Pprod clean packageþþThis will concatenate and minify the client CSS and JavaScript files. It will also modify `index.html` so it references these new files.þTo ensure everything worked, run:þþ    java -jar target/*.warþþThen navigate to [http://localhost:8080](http://localhost:8080) in your browser.þþRefer to [Using JHipster in production][] for more details.þþ## TestingþþTo launch your application's tests, run:þþ    ./mvnw clean testþþ### Client testsþþUnit tests are run by [Jest][] and written with [Jasmine][]. They're located in [src/test/javascript/](src/test/javascript/) and can be run with:þþ    npm testþþUI end-to-end tests are powered by [Protractor][], which is built on top of WebDriverJS. They're located in [src/test/javascript/e2e](src/test/javascript/e2e)þand can be run by starting Spring Boot in one terminal (`./mvnw spring-boot:run`) and running the tests (`npm run e2e`) in a second one.þþFor more information, refer to the [Running tests page][].þþ### Code qualityþþSonar is used to analyse code quality. You can start a local Sonar server (accessible on http://localhost:9001) with:þþ```þdocker-compose -f src/main/docker/sonar.yml up -dþ```þþThen, run a Sonar analysis:þþ```þ./mvnw -Pprod clean test sonar:sonarþ```þþFor more information, refer to the [Code quality page][].þþ## Using Docker to simplify development (optional)þþYou can use Docker to improve your JHipster development experience. A number of docker-compose configuration are available in the [src/main/docker](src/main/docker) folder to launch required third party services.þþFor example, to start a mysql database in a docker container, run:þþ    docker-compose -f src/main/docker/mysql.yml up -dþþTo stop it and remove the container, run:þþ    docker-compose -f src/main/docker/mysql.yml downþþYou can also fully dockerize your application and all the services that it depends on.þTo achieve this, first build a docker image of your app by running:þþ    ./mvnw verify -Pprod dockerfile:build dockerfile:tag@version dockerfile:tag@commitþþThen run:þþ    docker-compose -f src/main/docker/app.yml up -dþþFor more information refer to [Using Docker and Docker-Compose][], this page also contains information on the docker-compose sub-generator (`jhipster docker-compose`), which is able to generate docker configurations for one or several JHipster applications.þþ## Continuous Integration (optional)þþTo configure CI for your project, run the ci-cd sub-generator (`jhipster ci-cd`), this will let you generate configuration files for a number of Continuous Integration systems. Consult the [Setting up Continuous Integration][] page for more information.þþ[JHipster Homepage and latest documentation]: https://www.jhipster.techþ[JHipster 5.3.1 archive]: https://www.jhipster.tech/documentation-archive/v5.3.1þþ[Using JHipster in development]: https://www.jhipster.tech/documentation-archive/v5.3.1/development/þ[Using Docker and Docker-Compose]: https://www.jhipster.tech/documentation-archive/v5.3.1/docker-composeþ[Using JHipster in production]: https://www.jhipster.tech/documentation-archive/v5.3.1/production/þ[Running tests page]: https://www.jhipster.tech/documentation-archive/v5.3.1/running-tests/þ[Code quality page]: https://www.jhipster.tech/documentation-archive/v5.3.1/code-quality/þ[Setting up Continuous Integration]: https://www.jhipster.tech/documentation-archive/v5.3.1/setting-up-ci/þþþ[Node.js]: https://nodejs.org/þ[Yarn]: https://yarnpkg.org/þ[Webpack]: https://webpack.github.io/þ[Angular CLI]: https://cli.angular.io/þ[BrowserSync]: http://www.browsersync.io/þ[Jest]: https://facebook.github.io/jest/þ[Jasmine]: http://jasmine.github.io/2.0/introduction.htmlþ[Protractor]: https://angular.github.io/protractor/þ[Leaflet]: http://leafletjs.com/þ[DefinitelyTyped]: http://definitelytyped.org/

# Lupa-Verificador-de-Religadorþþ- Software desenvolvido para realizar a leitura de atributos específicos do ALTERE V3 , e de seu respectivo religador.þAtravés de um arquivo no formato (txt), software realiza uma leitura de determinados atributos para posteriomente realizar validação dos mesmos.þþ# Leitura dos seguintes atributos do arquivo de coleta: þþ- Número de serie do Altereþþ- MAC þþ- Relação de Tensão e Correnteþþ- Número de serie do Religadorþþ- Coeficientes de calibração específicos das faixas de corrente IA, IB, IC, IN þþ- Coeficientes de calibração específicos das faixas de Tensão VA, VB, VC, VR, VS, VT þþ- RTC (Data e Hora)þþ- Tempo de operação do equipamento þþþ# Validadção do Religador atrelado ao seu respctivo ALTERE V3þþApós a leitura dos atributos no arquivo de coleta do(dos) equipamento(s), é realizada uma verificação para a garantia que o os atributos estão parametrizados com a configuração correta, e o arquivo contendo os parâmetros do religador o qual foi designado ao seu respectivo ALTERE V3 foi incorporado ao mesmo.

# Bowl: Bowling Scorekeeper Command Line AppþþThis is a simple application to compute your score in a ten-pin, ten-frame bowling game.þþProvide your rolls as a series of numbers separated by a symbol like a space, comma or semicolon.  þThe app is not picky about format, as long as your numbers are separated by a non-numeric character!þþThe app will compute your score, and print out a frame-by-frame breakdown.þþ1. Download the latest [release](https://github.com/jfirtree/bowl/archive/1.01.zip).þ2. Extract the archive file.þ3. Within the extracted folder, run the program according to usage instructions below.þþ## UsageþThe \<rolls\> parameter is a list of each of your rolls in numeric format.þ#### Valid Input Examples þ`{10,2,3}`þþ`10 2 3`þþ`(10),(2,3)`þþ### Windowsþ`bowl <rolls>`þ### Linuxþ`sh bowl.sh <rolls>`þ### Javaþ`java -jar target/bowl-1.0.jar <rolls>`þþ## Error-checkingþ* Verifies that you have inputted the right number of rolls for a ten-frame game.þ* Verifies that the pins you report knocking down are within the set of upright pins (<= 10 for first ball, and <= remainder for second ball).

description: Produce Graphviz images of your git repository history
readme: git-graphvizþ============þþProduce [Graphviz][1] graphs of your git repository history.þþCommits are grouped by branch name and labelled with:þþ  1. refþ  2. commit messageþ  3. relative commit timeþþAny commits which are a head and tag refs are each given a different style to ordinary commits.þþ![example image](./example.png "example graph")þþUsageþ-----þTo produce a dot file for the current repository:þþ`git-graphiz > graph.dot`þþgit-graphviz uses git log, and all command line arguments are passed to it. This means you can do things like:þþ`git-graphviz --since="4 weeks"` þþTo convert the dot file to a pdf file use dot:þþ`dot -Tpdf -o graph.pdf graph.dot`þþAlternatively to create a png:þþ`dot -Tpng -o graph.png graph.png`þþþThe output from git-graphviz can be piped directly into dot:þþ`git-graphviz --since="4 weeks" | dot -Tpdf -o graph.pdf`þþLimitationsþ-----------þOnly tested on OS X Mountain Lion and with a small number of repositories. I've guarded against someþspecial characters in commit messages but it is possible that invalid dot file could be produced for other inputs.þþWith the default options repositories with lots of commits canþproduce *very* big dot files which are hard to process. Consider usingþa --since argument or --simplify-by-decoration.þþBranches are listed in alphabetical order which can make (for example) master appear as a branch, rather than as your mainline.þþOriginþ------þA project I worked on had a management imposed branching strategy whichþlead to a number of active topic branches at any time. (Based on that proposed by [nvie][2]). þThe development teams were happy visualising this using normal developer tools,þbut management preferred to view a manually generated Powerpoint document.þþThese documents quickly became out of date, and did not give a clear indicationþof how long a topic branch had been away from master. Creating this scriptþprovided a mechanism for automatically creating management friendly branch reports. þþThe intial implementation idea came from the [git wiki][3].þþþ[1]: http://www.graphviz.org "Graphviz"þ[2]: http://nvie.com/posts/a-successful-git-branching-model/ "nvie.com"þ[3]: https://git.wiki.kernel.org/index.php/Aliases#Use_graphviz_for_display "Git Wiki"

readme: # DescriptionþProtects against calling methods on wrong threads using AspectJ and Android'sþ`@MainThread`/`@WorkerThread` annotations.þþ# UsageþSet up AspectA as described here: https://github.com/serso/aspecta.þþImport Thread Guard library to your project:þ```groovyþdependencies {þ  implementation 'org.solovyev.android.threadguard:lib:1.0.2'þ}þ```þþOptionally, you can specify how to penalize the violations:þ```javaþpackage org.example.android;þþclass App extends Application {þþ    @Overrideþ    void onCreate() {þ        ThreadGuard.penaltyDeath();þ        // orþ        ThreadGuard.penaltyLog();        þ    }þ}þ```

description: A database connectivity testing tool. You simply call DBMole with the parameters needed to connect to your DB (host, port, db, user, password), and let DBMole debug your connection for you!
readme: # DBMoleþþA database connectivity testing tool. Currently works with Oracle, but plans are to make it work with databases that are supported by Java.þþ[![Download DBMole](https://img.shields.io/badge/DBMole-Download-orange.svg)](https://github.com/davydany/dbmole/releases)þþ## Supported Databasesþþ* Oracleþ* Oracle with TLSþ* PostgreSQLþ* MongoDBþ* MySQLþ* MariaDBþþ## Getting Startedþþ1. Download the `dbmole-<VERSION>.jar` jar file from here: [![Download DBMole](https://img.shields.io/badge/DBMole-Download-orange.svg)](https://github.com/davydany/dbmole/releases)þ2. Run: `java -jar dbmole-<VERSION>.jar` to see all the options you can pass to DBConn. þ3. Now test the database you want to connect to.þþ## Basic UsageþþTo get started, run with `--help` flag to see all the options. þþYou will need to provide the `hostname` and `port` of your databaseþas they are required, followed by optional fields like `--username`, þ`--password`, and `--database`. Use `--help` for additional parametersþand options you can pass to `dbmole`.

微服务(SpringBoot+Dubbo) + 容器化(Docker) + 自动化部署(Jenkins)
readme:
# Micro微服务þ#### 微服务(SpringBoot+Dubbo) + 容器化(Docker) + 自动化部署(Jenkins)þ---þ#### 项目工具þ* IntelliJ IDEA 2018.1.5 x64þ* VMware Workstation Proþ##### 软件版本号þ* mysql 5.7.22þ* spring-boot 2.0.6.RELEASEþ* jdk 1.8þ* tomcat 8þ* dubbo com.alibaba.spring.boot 2.0.0þ* zookeeper 3.4.6þ* zkclient com.101tec 0.10þ* flywaydb 5.1.4þ##### Docker相关þ* ![](https://github.com/Charm-J/micro/blob/master/image/1.png)þþ* ![](https://github.com/Charm-J/micro/blob/master/image/2.png)þ---þþ#### What can I learn？þ从0搭建一整套微服务系统。þþ#### What is Micro-Service?þ* 微服务架构þ整个应用程序将会被拆分成一个个功能独立的子系统，可独立运行；þ系统与系统之间通过RPC接口通信。这样系统间的耦合度大大降低，易扩展。þ* 容器化部署þ各个微服务将采用Docker来实现容器化部署，避免一切因环境引起的各种问题。þ* 自动化构建þ项目被微服务化后，各个服务之间的关系错综复杂，打包构建费事费力。通过借助Jenkins，实现一键自动化部署。þþ#### Why use them?þ* 为什么用微服务：þ系统架构的演进过程：单机结构->集群结构->微服务结构。þ微服务结构好处有很多：þ系统之间的耦合度大大降低，可以独立开发、独立部署、独立测试，系统与系统之间的边界非常明确，排错也变得相当容易，开发效率大大提升。þ系统之间的耦合度降低，从而系统更易于扩展。我们可以针对性地扩展某些服务。假设这个商城要搞一次大促，下单量可能会大大提升，因此我们可以针对性地提升订单系统、产品系统的节点数量，而对于后台管理系统、数据分析系统而言，节点数量维持原有水平即可。þ服务的复用性更高。比如，当我们将用户系统作为单独的服务后，该公司所有的产品都可以使用该系统作为用户系统，无需重复开发。þ* 为什么需要Dubbo：þ减少运维的复杂度：能够针对性地增加某些服务的处理能力（某些服务的背后可能是一个集群模式）。þ* 为什么需要Docker：þDocker不仅能够实现运行环境的隔离，而且能极大程度的节约计算机资源，它成为一种轻量级的“虚拟机”。þ* 为什么需要Jenkins：þ针对多个系统，不仅依赖关系复杂，而且模块构建顺序有所讲究，每次人工操作耗时耗力，还容易出错。þþþ#### Actual-Training!þ þ##### 1. 项目的组织结构 þþ创建一个Maven Project，命名为“micro” þþ这个Project由多个Module构成，每个Module对应着“微服务”的一个子系统，þ可独立运行，是一个独立的项目。 这也是目前主流的项目组织形式，即多模块项目。þ在micro项目下创建各个子模块，每个自模块都是一个独立的SpringBoot项目：þ```þmicro-controller 请求调度控制层þmicro-user 用户服务þmicro-message 消息服务þmicro-common-api 公用接口-被所有模块依赖þ```þ![](https://github.com/Charm-J/micro/blob/master/image/3.png)þþ* 创建Project þþNew一个Projectþ选择Spring Initializrþ设置groupId、artifactId、versionþþ* 创建Module þþ在Project上New Module þ![](https://github.com/Charm-J/micro/blob/master/image/4.png) þþ和刚才一样，选择Spring Initializr，设置groupId、artifactId、versionþ依次创建好所有的Module，如下图所示： þ![](https://github.com/Charm-J/micro/blob/master/image/5.png)þ* 构建模块的依赖关系 þ目前为止，模块之间没有任何联系，下面我们要通过pom文件来指定它们之间的依赖关系。þ![](https://github.com/Charm-J/micro/blob/master/image/6.png)þþ需要将micro-common-api打成jar包，并让这些模块依赖这个jar。þ此外，为了简化各个模块的配置，我们将所有模块的通用依赖放在Project的pom文件中，þ然后让所有模块作为Project的子模块。这样子模块就可以从父模块中继承所有的依赖，þ而不需要自己再配置了。 þþ---þ实操记录： þþ首先将micro-common-api的打包方式设成jarþ当打包这个模块的时候，Maven会将它打包成jar，并安装在本地仓库中。þ这样其他模块打包的时候就可以引用这个jar。þ```þcom.jeffþmicro-common-apiþ0.0.1-SNAPSHOTþjarþ```þþþ将其他模块的打包方式设为warþ除了micro-common-api外，其他模块都是一个个可独立运行的子系统，þ需要在web容器中运行，所以我们需要将这些模块的打包方式设成warþ```þcom.jeffþmicro-userþ0.0.1-SNAPSHOTþwarþ```þ在总pom中指定子模块þmodules标签指定了当前模块的子模块是谁，但是仅在父模块的pom文件中指定子模块还不够，þ还需要在子模块的pom文件中指定父模块是谁。þ```þþ micro-controllerþ micro-common-apiþ micro-userþ micro-messageþþ```þ在子模块中指定父模块þ```þþ com.jeffþ microþ 0.0.1-SNAPSHOTþ ../pom.xmlþþ```þ到此为止，模块的依赖关系配置完毕！但要注意模块打包的顺序。由于所有模块都依赖于micro-common-api模块，因此在构建模块时，首先需要编译、打包、安装micro-common-api，将它打包进本地仓库中，这样上层模块才能引用到。当该模块安装完毕后，再构建上层模块。þ* 在父模块的pom中添加所有子模块公用的依赖þþ当父模块的pom中配置了公用依赖后，子模块的pom文件将非常简洁，如下所示：þ```þcom.jeffþmicro-userþ0.0.1-SNAPSHOTþwarþþmicro-userþUser for Spring Bootþþþ com.jeffþ microþ 0.0.1-SNAPSHOTþ ../pom.xmlþþþþ micro-userþþ```þ当项目的结构搭建完成之后，接下来你需要配置Docker环境，并将这些项目打包进容器中，验证下是否能正常启动。þþ##### 2. 创建Docker容器þ以创建micro-user容器为例，采用如下命令创建容器：þ```þdocker run --privileged=true --name micro-user -p 8002:8080 -v /opt/micro/tomcat/logs:/usr/local/tomcat/logs -v /opt/micro/tomcat/conf/tomcat-users.xml:/usr/local/tomcat/conf/tomcat-users.xml -v /opt/micro/tomcat/conf/context.xml:/usr/local/tomcat/webapps/manager/META-INF/context.xml -d docker.io/tomcat:8þ```þ_--name_：指定容器的名字 þþ_-p_：指定容器的端口映射 -p 8082:8080 表示将容器的8080端口映射到宿主机的8082端口上 þþ_-v_：指定容器数据卷的映射 xxx:yyy 表示将容器yyy目录映射到宿主机的xxx目录上，从而访问宿主机的xxx目录就相当于访问容器的yyy目录。 þþdocker.io/tomcat:8：表示容器所对应的镜像。 þþ第二个 _-v_ 解决cargo远程自动部署Jekins报错403的问题-涉及到的文件中有IP限制þ这条命令执行成功后，你就可以通过你的IP:8082 访问到micro-user容器的tomcat了。如果你看到了那只眼熟了猫，那就说明容器启动成功了！ þ![](https://github.com/Charm-J/micro/blob/master/image/7.png)þ接下来，你需要按照上面的方法，给剩下几个系统创建好Tomcat容器。þþ##### 3. 整合Dubboþ* 创建zookeeper容器þDubbo一共定义了三种角色，分别是：服务提供者、服务消费者、注册中心。注册中心是服务提供者和服务消费者的桥梁，服务消费者会在初始化的时候将自己的IP和端口号发送给注册中心，而服务消费者通过注册中心知道服务提供者的IP和端口号。þ* 父pom文件中引入dubbo和ZK的依赖þ```þþþ com.alibaba.spring.bootþ dubbo-spring-boot-starterþ 2.0.0þþþþ org.apache.zookeeperþ zookeeperþ 3.4.6þ þ þ slf4j-log4j12þ org.slf4jþ þ þþþþ com.101tecþ zkclientþ 0.10þþ```þþ##### 4. 自动化构建þJenkins是一个自动化构建工具，它可以帮助我们摆脱繁琐的部署过程，我们只需要在一开始配置好构建策略，以后部署只需要一键完成。þ* 创建Jenkins容器þJenkins采用Java开发，也需要Java环境，但我们使用Docker后，一切都采用容器化部署，Jenkins也不例外。þ拉取镜像þ这里我们使用Jenkins官方提供的镜像，大家只需执行如下命令拉取即可：þ`docker pull docker.io/jenkins/jenkins`þþ启动容器þ需要注意：两个默认端口号不能随意抛弃。_-v_ docker内jekins数据卷映射到宿主机上þ```þdocker run -d --privileged=true --name jenkins -u root -p 9002:8080 -p 50000:50000 -v /opt/micro/jenkins:/var/jenkins_home docker.io/jenkinsþ```þþ初始化Jenkinsþ然后你需要访问IP:9002，Jenkins会带着你进行一系列的初始化设置，你只要跟着它一步步执行就OK þþ* Jenkins插件安装þJenkins线上安装插件需要连接谷歌，没有默认安装，可通过搜索安装： þþ依次点击 系统管理->插件管理-> 可选插件-> 过滤搜索框中 查找如下插件：þ```þMaven Integration pluginþSSH pluginþDeploy to container PluginþGitHub Integration Pluginþ```þþ* 在Jenkins中创建项目þ点击页面左侧的“新建”按钮：
þ![](https://github.com/Charm-J/micro/blob/master/image/8.png)
þ输入项目名称micro-user，选择“构建一个Maven项目”，然后点击“OK”：þ配置Git仓库þ选择Git，然后输入本项目Git仓库的URL，并在Credentials中输入Git的用户名和密码，þ构建触发器þ选择第一项，如下图所示： þ![](https://github.com/Charm-J/micro/blob/master/image/9.png)þPre StepþPre Step会在正式构建前执行，由于所有项目都依赖于micro-common-api，因此在项目构建前，需要将它安装到本地仓库，然后才能被当前项目正确依赖。 因此，在Pre Step中填写如下信息： þ![](https://github.com/Charm-J/micro/blob/master/image/10.png)þBuildþ然后就是正式构建的过程，填写如下信息即可： þ![](https://github.com/Charm-J/micro/blob/master/image/11.png)þOK，Jenkins服务和micro-user服务并不在同一个Docker容器中，那么究竟该如何才能将Jenkins本地编译好的war包发送到micro-userr容器中呢？这就需要使用Jenkins的一个插件——Deploy Plugin þþþ* 远程部署þ直接在插件页面搜索Deploy to container安装。þ在父项目的pom文件中增加远程部署插件：þ```þþ org.codehaus.cargoþ cargo-maven2-pluginþ 1.6.5þ þ þ þ tomcat8þ remoteþ þ þ runtimeþ Tomcat的用户名þ Tomcat的密码þ þ þ þ þ deployþ þ redeployþ þ þ þþ```þ为Tomcat设置用户名和密码þ![](https://github.com/Charm-J/micro/blob/master/image/12.png)þ修改Jenkins中micro-user的配置þ在“构建后操作”中增加如下配置： þ![](https://github.com/Charm-J/micro/blob/master/image/13.png)þWAR/EAR files：表示你需要发布的war包 þþContainers：配置目标Tomcat的用户名和密码 þþþ##### 5. Maven的profile功能þ在实际开发中，我们的系统往往有多套环境构成，如：开发环境、测试环境、预发环境、生产环境。而不同环境的配置各不相同。如果我们只有一套配置，那么当系统从一个环境迁移到另一个环境的时候，就需要通过修改代码来更换配置，这样无疑增加了工作的复杂度，而且易于出错。但好在Maven提供了profile功能，能帮助我们解决这一个问题。þ父项目的pom中添加profile元素þ首先，我们需要在总pom的中添加多套环境的信息，如下所示：þ```þþ þ devþ þ devþ þ þ trueþ þ þ þ testþ þ testþ þ þ þ prodþ þ prodþ þ þþ```þ父项目的pom中添加resource元素þresource标识了不同环境下需要打包哪些配置文件。þ```þþ þ þ src/main/resourcesþ trueþ þ þ application.propertiesþ application-dev.propertiesþ application-test.propertiesþ application-prod.propertiesþ þ þ þ src/main/resourcesþ trueþ þ þ application.propertiesþ þ application-${profileActive}.propertiesþ þ þþ```þ父项目的pom中添加插件maven-resources-pluginþ该插件用来在Maven构建时参数替换þ```þþ maven-resources-pluginþ 3.0.2þ þ þ @þ þ falseþ þþ```þ在子项目中创建配置þ分别为dev环境、test环境、prod环境创建三套配置，application.proerpties中存放公用的配置。 þ在application.properties中添加spring.profiles.active=@profileActive@þ`spring.profiles.active=@profileActive@`þþ修改Jenkins的配置þ在所有Jenkins中所有Maven命令的末尾添加 *-P test*，在打包的时候-P后面的参数将会作为@profileActive@的值传入系统中，从而根据该值打包相应的application-{profileActive}.properties文件。þ##### 6. 开发流程þ到此为止，所有准备工作都已经完成，接下来就可以进入代码开发阶段。下面我以一个例子，带着大家感受下有了这套微服务框架后，我们的开发流程究竟有了哪些改变？下面以开发一个用户登录功能为例，介绍下使用本框架之后开发的流程。þþ* 开发登录服务þ首先需要在 micro-common-api 中创建UserService接口，并在其中声明登录的抽象函数。þ![](https://github.com/Charm-J/micro/blob/master/image/14.png)þþ然后在micro-user中开发UserService的实现——UserServiceImpl。 UserServiceImpl上必须要加上Dubbo的*@Service*注解，从而告诉Dubbo，在本项目初始化的时候需要将这个类发布成一项服务，供其他系统调用。þ![](https://github.com/Charm-J/micro/blob/master/image/15.png)þþ* 引用登录服务þ当UserService开发完毕后，接下来micro-controller需要引用该服务，并向前端提供一个登录的REST接口。 若要使用userService中的函数，仅需要在userService上添加*@Reference*注解，然后就像调用本地函数一样使用userService即可。Dubbo会帮你找到UserService服务所在的IP和端口号，并发送调用请求。但这一切对于程序猿来说是完全透明的。þ![](https://github.com/Charm-J/micro/blob/master/image/16.png)þþ* 自动构建服务þ上面的代码完成后，接下来你需要将代码提交至你的Git仓库。接下来就是自动化部署的过程了。þ你需要进入Jenkins，由于刚才修改了micro-user和micro-controller的代码，þ因此你需要分别构建这两个项目。 þ接下来Jenkins会自动从你的Git仓库中拉取最新的代码，þ然后依次执行Pre Step、Build、构建后操作的过程。þ由于我们在Pre Step中设置了编译micro-common-api，þ因此Jenkins首先会将其安装到本地仓库；然后再执行Build过程，þ构建micro-user，并将其打包成war包。þ最后将执行“构建后操作”，将war包发布到相应的tomcat容器中。 þ至此，整个发布流程完毕！þþ* 查看服务的状态þ当Jenkins构建完成后，我们可以登录Dubbo-Admin查看服务发布和引用的状态。þ当我们搜索UserService服务后，可以看到，该服务的提供者已经成功发布了服务： þ![](https://github.com/Charm-J/micro/blob/master/image/17.png)þ点击“消费者”我们可以看到，该服务已经被controller-consumer成功订阅： þ![](https://github.com/Charm-J/micro/blob/master/image/18.png)þjekins 成功部署后þ可以浏览器访问：http://192.168.109.128:8001/micro-controller/user/sayHello?name=2222þ测试服务调用是否成功！
þ![](https://github.com/Charm-J/micro/blob/master/image/19.png)þþ#### docker启动相关服务指令汇总þ* miro-controller > tomcat启动þ```þdocker run --privileged=true --name micro-controller -p 8001:8080 -v /opt/micro/tomcat/logs:/usr/local/tomcat/logs -v /opt/micro/tomcat/conf/tomcat-users.xml:/usr/local/tomcat/conf/tomcat-users.xml -v /opt/micro/tomcat/conf/context.xml:/usr/local/tomcat/webapps/manager/META-INF/context.xml -d docker.io/tomcat:8þ```þ* micro-user > tomcat启动þ```þdocker run --privileged=true --name micro-user -p 8002:8080 -v /opt/micro/tomcat/logs:/usr/local/tomcat/logs -v /opt/micro/tomcat/conf/tomcat-users.xml:/usr/local/tomcat/conf/tomcat-users.xml -v /opt/micro/tomcat/conf/context.xml:/usr/local/tomcat/webapps/manager/META-INF/context.xml -d docker.io/tomcat:8þ```þ* micro-message > tomcat启动þ```þdocker run --privileged=true --name micro-message -p 8003:8080 -v /opt/micro/tomcat/logs:/usr/local/tomcat/logs -v /opt/micro/tomcat/conf/tomcat-users.xml:/usr/local/tomcat/conf/tomcat-users.xml -v /opt/micro/tomcat/conf/context.xml:/usr/local/tomcat/webapps/manager/META-INF/context.xml -d docker.io/tomcat:8þ```þ* zookeeper > 启动þ```þdocker run --privileged=true --name zookeeper -p 2181:2181 -v /opt/micro/zookeeper:/data --restart always -d docker.io/zookeeperþ```þ* dubbo-admin > 启动þ```þdocker run --privileged=true --name dubbo-admin -d \þ-p 9001:8080 \þ-e dubbo.registry.address=zookeeper://192.168.109.128:2181 \þ-e dubbo.admin.root.password=753951 \þ-e dubbo.admin.guest.password=guest \þ-v /opt/micro/dubbo-admin/logs:/usr/local/tomcat/logs \þchenchuxin/dubbo-adminþ```þ* rabbitmq > 启动 þþ这里注意获取镜像的时候要获取management版本的，不要获取last版本的，management版本的才带有管理界面。 þþ默认端口：þ5672 -- client端通信口þ15672 -- 管理界面ui端口þ```þdocker run --privileged=true --restart=always -p 5672:5672 -p 15672:15672 --name rabbitmq -d rabbitmq:managementþ```þ* jenkins > 启动 þþ默认端口：þ8080 -- server页面端口þ50000 -- Slave 与 Master 通信端口þ```þdocker run -d --privileged=true --name jenkins -u root -p 9002:8080 -p 50000:50000 -v /opt/micro/jenkins:/var/jenkins_home docker.io/jenkinsþ```þþ#### 注意事项þ* 项目启动顺序：micro-message > micro-user > micro-controllerþ* Linux 相关端口一定要开放，还要注意一些容易忽视的端口号，比如dubbo:20880。þ* Linux 端口不能冲突。þ* Jenkins 构建异常，除了查看Jekins页面报错信息，还要查看对应项目日志。þ* Jenkins git配置-SSH方式：Username 可以通过公钥末尾项获取；Private Key 私钥全部内容。þ* Dubbo 提供方需要指定注册中心端口，消费方不需要指定注册中心端口。þ* Dubbo-admin 没有数据，多半是注册中心连不上。þ* ZK 数据windows可视化工具[ZooInspector]þ* 同一宿主机下各个容器间通信：本项目使用默认bridge方式。A容器需要B容器的服务，可是使用[宿主机IP]+[宿主机被映射端口]的方式访问。þ* Docker 可视化管理平台推荐使用[Portainer]

# Week # 2 Project - *NYTimesSearch*þþ**NYTimesSearch** is an android app that allows a user to search for articles on web using simple filters. The app utilizes [New York Times Search API](http://developer.nytimes.com/docs/read/article_search_api_v2).þþTime spent: **24** hours spent in totalþþ## User StoriesþþThe following **required** functionality is completed:þþ* [ ] User can **search for news article** by specifying a query and launching a search. Search displays a grid of image results from the New York Times Search API.þ* [ ] User can click on "settings" which allows selection of **advanced search options** to filter resultsþ* [ ] User can configure advanced search filters such as:þ  * [ ] Begin Date (using a date picker)þ  * [ ] News desk values (Arts, Fashion & Style, Sports)þ  * [ ] Sort order (oldest or newest)þ* [ ] Subsequent searches have any filters applied to the search resultsþ* [ ] User can tap on any article in results to view the contents in an embedded browser.þ* [ ] User can **scroll down to see more articles**. The maximum number of articles is limited by the API search.þþ## Video WalkthroughþþHere's a walkthrough of implemented user stories:þþhttps://github.com/pcelande/NYTimesSearch/NYTimesSearch.gifþþGIF created with [LiceCap](http://www.cockos.com/licecap/).þþ## Notesþþ8 [] discovering the importance of the intent ;þþ## Open-source libraries usedþþ- [Android Async HTTP](https://github.com/loopj/android-async-http) - Simple asynchronous HTTP requests with JSON parsingþ- [Picasso](http://square.github.io/picasso/) - Image loading and caching library for Androidþþ## Licenseþþ    Copyright [yyyy] [name of copyright owner]þþ    Licensed under the Apache License, Version 2.0 (the "License");þ    you may not use this file except in compliance with the License.þ    You may obtain a copy of the License atþþ        http://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0þþ    Unless required by applicable law or agreed to in writing, softwareþ    distributed under the License is distributed on an "AS IS" BASIS,þ    WITHOUT WARRANTIES OR CONDITIONS OF ANY KIND, either express or implied.þ    See the License for the specific language governing permissions andþ    limitations under the License.

# Esercitazione Bonusþ--------------þLista utenti:þþ```þadminþ123456þþuserþquertyþ```þþUrl icona:þhttps://romannurik.github.io/AndroidAssetStudio/icons-launcher.html#foreground.type=text&foreground.text.text=EsBonus&foreground.text.font=Aclonica&foreground.space.trim=1&foreground.space.pad=0.5&foreColor=rgb(0%2C%2080%2C%20116)&backColor=rgb(58%2C%20219%2C%20238)&crop=0&backgroundShape=square&effects=none&name=ic_launcherþþ--------------þ##### Scadenza: 15/01/19þþPer l’esercitazione bonus (facoltativa) dovrete implementare un’applicazione Android composto da un form di login semplificato, che permetta a un utente di loggarsi inserendo username e password. þþL’applicazione deve contenere due activity:þþ1. Nella prima ci saranno i campi per l’inserimento dei dati richiesti, ovvero username e password (quest’ultimo campo oscurato come visto in FPW); un pulsante (“ACCEDI”) che consente l’accesso; e una text-view che rimandi al form per la registrazione di un nuovo utente (badate bene, questa funzionalità non è da implementare, basta solo il link). þþ1. Tramite il pulsante ACCEDI verrà visualizzata la seconda activity; questa conterrà una text-view con testo “Benvenuto username”, dove username corrisponde al nome dell’utente che ha appena fatto l’accesso correttamente, oppure “Accesso negato” se i dati non sono corretti. In aggiunta, un pulsante (“INDIETRO”) per tornare all’activity precedente. þþþControllo dei dati: la vostra applicazione deve attuare due tipi di controlli. In primo luogo, il passaggio alla successiva activity non può avvenire se uno dei campi, o entrambi, non sono stati compilati dall’utente. In tal caso dovete visualizzare dei messaggi di errore come visto a lezione.þþMentre, il secondo controllo richiede che i campi inseriti dall’utente corrente corrispondano a un utente presente in una lista di utenti registrati, definita da voi e di cui quindi disponete username e password.þþþLinks:þ1. http://moodle.unica.it/course/view.php?id=50þ1. https://docs.google.com/document/d/1Jsmicpid2Y52iOKSpCjxbw-lcpphbHDEIIbtE1BBRb0/edit#heading=h.ukispj1l3ib1

description: Hack The Future 2018
readme: # The Artifactþþ# The AssignmentþDear Developers,þþWe have deployed a team of secret agents in hostile areas. We deploy packages with weapons, gadgets and supplies by airplane. The locations of those packages are top secret and cannot fall into enemies’ hands. This is where you come in. We need a secure application through which we can share the location of the secret supplies. Some supplies are available to all of our secret agents and some supplies are only available to certain agents. The backend to communicate through is located here. Note that radio connectivity is not always available at the location of the supplies and our agents should be able to locate the packages without relying on internet connectivity. Our agents should also be able to communicate the information of supplies physically through a QR code or other means. Also note that our agents can be captured. Their mobile devices can also be stolen. A stolen or lost device should not lead to compromised data, so take the right security measures.þþWe depend on your expertise to make the optimal decisions on how to visualise and navigate to supplies. Try to be creative.þþThe success and fate of our operation lies in your hands.þþGood luck,þþWith kind regards, þThe Hack the Future Mobile Challenge team+

readme: ### H2O.ai MOJO ScorerþþDeploy MOJO models as REST APIs easily using Javalin.ioþþ###### Inspired byþ* https://github.com/rubuntu/H2O_Mojo_Model_Scorerþþþ##### TODOSþ* ~~Add users authentication~~þ* ~~Add JWT~~þ* ~~Support Clustering models~~þ* Support predict over CSV filesþþ#### Usageþþ* Clone this repo and build the executable `jar` using:þ`mvn clean install`þþ* Copy the `h2o_app-0.0.1.jar` at `target/`þþ* Run the server using:þ`java -jar h2o_app-0.0.1.jar`þþ##### REST APIþþ| Method  | Endpoint | Description | JWT protectedþ| ------------- | ------------- | ------------- |------------- |þ| POST  | /model/:model/predict | Make a single prediction from the specified model name | Trueþ| PUT  | /upload/:model | Upload a MOJO and set name to the model | Trueþ| GET  | /models/list | List all available models name | Trueþ| POST  | /users/get_token | Returns a valid JWT Token | Falseþþ#### Important þ* The `data` must be send as `form-data`, specifying the variable names and values.þ* `MOJOs` are send in a `form-data` too, the `key` must be called `model`and the value is the `MOJO` zip file.þ* By default creates a username and password called `admin` and `pass`, those are stored in a `List`, you can change the code and add a database connection or whatever to get your users.þþ#### Response example:þ```þ{þ    "prediction": "68.13734189777028",þ    "params": {þ        "carbo": "5",þ        "fiber": "10",þ        "sugars": "6",þ        "weight": "1",þ        ...þ    }þ}þ```

readme: # applicationsNewþMicrosim-applications by Matteo Richiardi and Michele Sonnessa (2014) þUpdate to make compatible with JAS-mine by Ross Richardson (2016)þþWorkers sending out applications to vacancies: an example of many-to-many relationships (many vacancies applied for by any worker, many applications received by any vacancy) and how to persist them in the database, with linked tables that facilitate subsequent analysis.þþFeatures:- persists both periodic information (the characteristics of the population in each period, one record per worker per period) and one-off summary data (the complete history of each application / vacancy, one record per application / vacancy saved when simulation ends)þþThe main() method is in the ApplicationsStart.java class in the it.unito.experiment package.  þRun this class as a Java Application, and the JAS-mine GUI will launch.þTo build the simulation, click on the 'Build simulation model' button (the second from the left), which should bring up some empty charts. þTo run the simulation, click on the 'Start simulation' button, which is the next button on the right. þþFor more information on this simulation, see http://www.jas-mine.net/demo/job-applications.

readme: # cs100f2018-lab1-starterþþDesigned for use with [GitHub Classroom](https://classroom.github.com/), thisþrepository contains the solution for Laboratory 1 assignment in Computer Science 100. Since the Travis builds for this repository will initially fail (as evidenced byþa red ✗ appearing in the commit logs instead of a green ✔), theþprogrammer is responsible for completing all of the steps needed to satisfy theþrequirements for the assignment, thus causing a ✔ to instead appear inþthe commit logs.þþþ## IntroductionþþThis assignment requires a programmer to implement and test a Java program,þcalled `DisplayOutput`, that will produce four lines of output. The first lineþof output will contain the name of the programmer and the date at which theþprogram was run. The next three lines of output will feature any one-sentenceþand one-line statements of advice that the programmer would like to provide toþthe person using the program. As verified byþ[Checkstyle](https://github.com/checkstyle/checkstyle), the source code for theþ`DisplayOutput.java` file must adhere to all of the requirements in the [GoogleþJava Style Guide](https://google.github.io/styleguide/javaguide.html).þþThe programmer is also responsible for writing a one-paragraph reflection,þstored in the file `writing/reflection.md`, that explains the challenges thatþyou faced and the solutions you developed. This is a Markdown file that mustþadhere to the standards described in the [Markdown SyntaxþGuide](https://guides.github.com/features/mastering-markdown/). Remember, youþcan preview the contents of a committed Markdown file by clicking on the nameþof the file in your GitHub repository.þþThe source code in the `DisplayOutput.java` file must also pass additional testsþset by the [GatorGrader tool](https://github.com/GatorEducator/gatorgrader). Forþinstance, GatorGrader will check to ensure that `DisplayOutput` produces exactlyþfour lines of output and that you use the `new Date()` construct in the Javaþcode. When you use the `git commit` command to transfer your source code to yourþGitHub repository, [Travis CI](https://travis-ci.com/) will initialize a buildþof your assignment, checking to see if it meets all of the requirements. Ifþyour source code meet all of the established requirements, then youþwill see a green ✔ in the listing of commits in GitHub. If yourþsubmission does not meet the requirements, a red ✗ will appear instead.þThe instructor will reduce a programmer's grade for this assignment if the redþ✗ appears on the last commit in GitHub immediately before theþassignment's due date.þþAvailable for download at the course website [courseþwebsite](http://www.cs.allegheny.edu/sites/jjumadinova/teaching/100/labs.html),þthe carefully formatted assignment sheet for this project provides more detailsþabout the steps that a computer scientist should take to complete thisþassignment.þþ## LearningþþIf you have not done so already, please read all of the relevant [GitHubþGuides](https://guides.github.com/) that explain how to use many of the featuresþthat GitHub provides. In particular, please make sure that you have read theþfollowing GitHub guides: [MasteringþMarkdown](https://guides.github.com/features/mastering-markdown/), [HelloþWorld](https://guides.github.com/activities/hello-world/), and [Documenting YourþProjects on GitHub](https://guides.github.com/features/wikis/). Each of theseþguides will help you to understand how to use both [GitHub](http://github.com) andþ[GitHub Classroom](https://classroom.github.com/).þþTo do well on this assignment, you should also read Chapters 1 and 2 in theþcourse textbook, paying particularly close attention to Sections 1.5 and 2.1.þPlease see the course instructor or one of the teaching assistants or tutors ifþyou have questions about any of these reading assignments.þþ## CommandsþþTo get started in using the GatorGrader tool, you can change into the directoryþfor this assignment and type the command `gradle grade` in your terminal.þRunning this command will produce a lot of output that you should carefullyþinspect. If the output indicates that GatorGrader judges that there are noþmistakes in the assignment, then this means that your source code and writingþare passing all of the automated baseline checks. However, if the outputþindicates that there are mistakes, then you will need to understand what theyþare and then try to fix them.þþYou can also complete several important Java programming tasks by using theþ`gradle` tool. For instance, you can compile (i.e., create bytecode from theþprogram's source code if it is a correct program) the program using the commandþ`gradle build`. There are other additional commands that you can type:þþ- `gradle clean`: clean the project of all the derived filesþ- `gradle check`: check the quality of the code using Checkstyleþ- `gradle build`: create the bytecode from the Java source codeþ- `gradle run`: run the Java program in the command-lineþ- `gradle tasks`: display details about the Gradle systemþþTo run one of these commands, you must be in the main (or "home base") directoryþfor this assignment where the `build.gradle` file is located. Then, you can typeþthe command in the terminal and study the output.þþ## OutputþþTyping the command `gradle run` in the terminal window produces the followingþoutput for the instructor's version of `DisplayOutput`. As long as your programþadheres to all of the requirements for the assignment and passes all of theþverification checks, your version may produce (partially) different output.þþ```þ> Task :runþJanyl Jumadinova Mon Sep 03 18:27:48 EDT 2018þWelcome to programming.þGithub is awesome.þJava is cool.þþþBUILD SUCCESSFUL in 0sþ2 actionable tasks: 1 executed, 1 up-to-dateþ```þþ## ChecksþþYour submission must pass the following checks:þþ- labone/DisplayOutput.java:þ  - Feature two single-line commentsþ  - Feature two multiple-line commentsþ  - Contain four uses of a `println(` statementþ  - Contain one use of a `new Date(` statementþ  - Produce four lines of output in the terminalþþ- writing/reflection.md:þ  - Contains one contiguous paragraph of formatted textþ  - Contains one paragraph containing at least 150 wordsþþ- GitHub repository:þ  - Contains two commits beyond the starting numberþþ## TravisþþThis assignment uses [Travis CI](https://travis-ci.com/) to automatically runþthe checking programs every time you commit to your GitHub repository. Theþchecking will start as soon as you have accepted the assignment, thus creatingþyour own private repository, and the course instructor enables Travis for it. Ifþyou are using Travis for the first time, you will need to authorize Travis CI toþaccess the private repositories that you created on GitHub. If you do not see either a yellow circle or a green checkmark or a red xþin your listing of commits, then please ask the instructor to see whether or notþTravis CI was correctly enabled.þþ## RequirementsþþThe GatorGrader software that supports the checking of this assignment wasþdeveloped for the following software and versions:þþ- Gradle 4.6þ- Java 1.8.0þ- MDL 0.4.0þ- Proselint 0.8.0þ- Python 3.6þþ## ProblemsþþIf you have found a problem with this assignment's provided source code, thenþyou can go to the [Computer Science 100 Lab 1þStarter](https://github.com/Allegheny-Computer-Science-100-01-F2018/cs100f2018-lab1-starter)þrepository and create an issue by clicking the "Issues" tab and then clickingþthe green "New Issue" button.If you have found a problem with the [GatorGraderþtool](https://github.com/GatorEducator/gatorgrader) and the way that it checksþyou assignment, then you can follow the aforementioned steps to create an issueþin its repository. To ensure that your issue is properly resolved, pleaseþprovide as many details as is possible about the problem that you experienced.þþStudents who find, and use the appropriate GitHub issue tracker to correctlyþdocument, a mistake in any aspect of this laboratory assignment will receiveþ extra credit towards their grade for it.þþ## AssistanceþþIf you are having trouble completing any part of this project, then please talkþwith either the course instructor or a teaching assistant during the laboratoryþsession. Alternatively, you may ask questions in the Slack team for thisþcourse. Finally, you can schedule a meeting during the course instructor'sþoffice hours.

http://localhost:8102/user/fb/feed (Get)þþ##þþ## Important Classesþþ```þ* SocialAppScheduler  : Responsible to invoke Scheduler as of now we have set it to every minute for syncing data from different # ArchipeloClientþOfficial repository for the ArchipeloClient!þþArchipelo is a project created to be a simple MMO that can be played on any device. It is built with the LibGDX game engine in Java. Due to lack of time, Archipelo has been cancelled.þþ![Screenshot of latest Archipelo build](screenshot.png)þþ

License

þThis project is under the MIT License. Please see the LICENSE file for more details.þþ

Not Accepting Pull-requests

þFor the sake of preservation, we are not accepting pull requests onto this repository. If you wish to modify the code, we suggest you fork this repository so that you will not have limited access.þþ

Known Bugs

þþ* Game rendering is blurry when moving (Upon further investigation, it seems all pixel art games have this issue)þ* Collisions are unpredictable if y < 0þ* Player does not render if 3 tiles from the top of a chunkþ* Underscore/hyphen characters are switched in the Bitmap Fontþþ### Running the GameþþNOTE: This is NOT recommended. The project's gradle configuration is old and requires an older version of Java. The Archipelo server is also very difficult to set up since it requires an active login server (service has been shutdown). It is encouraged that you use this code in a separate project or just look at it for your pleasure.þþTo play the game properly, you must first set up a [server](https://github.com/hollowbit/archipeloserver).þþTo run the client, simply executeþþ```þ$ ./gradlew runþ```

description: Allows for testing of various location methods (GPS, Fused, GPS with Criteria)
readme: # Mapping_GPS - Android Appþ## Purposeþ- Makes it possible to test phone positioning capabilities or GPS signal at a certain location.1þ- Allows user to see error values of mobile phone positioning methodsþ- Allows all collected data to be exported as a .txt fileþ- Created: June 2018þ- Last Updated: July 2018þ## Location Methods that app supports testing for:þ* GPSþ* GPS with high accuracy criteriaþ* Fused Location Services (combines services like cellular, GPS, etc.)þ## Useþ- When launching, the user specifies location refresh rate, positioning method (see above), and their true latitude and longitude coordinates (if known).þ- Once this is selected, user presses START button to begin retrieving location data.þ- At this point, the location readings of the phone are plotted on a map with labels and colors corresponding to the estimated accuracy reading as given by Android's getAccuracy() function.þ - Green pin: < 10m estimated accuracyþ - Yellow pin: 10-25m estimated accuracyþ - Red pin: 25-100m estimated accuracyþ- The readings can be paused/restarted.þ- Once paused, the data can be written to a .txt file by pressing SAVE. This data can be viewed by pressing VIEW DATA.þ## Data Collectionþ- The .txt file where the data is saved contains the following info:þ - Start and stop times of the data collectionþ - Lat and Lng values entered by the user (if applicable)þ - Average accuracy radius as given by getAccuracy() function2þ - Average true error calculated using user's inputted Lat Lng values (if applicable)þ - Each data point, which consists of:þ - point numberþ - accuracy reading given by getAccuracy() functionþ - True error between Lat Lng readings and user's inputted Lat Lng readings (if applicable)þ - Time that the data point was collectedþ- The data can be exported as a .txt file by clicking SHARE while viewing the data.þ- The data can be copied to the clipboard by clicking COPY.þ- The data can be cleared by clicking DELETE.þ## Screenshotsþ### Initialization UIþThis is what the user sees when starting the app. Here, they have the option to enter the true latitude and longitude values if they are known. The update intervals is in seconds and can be set to 0 to take readings as fast as possible.þþ### Operating and Data Recording UIþThe left image shows the app running with the labels on the map corresponding to where the phone's estimated location is. The right shows the contents of the .txt with all of the data recorded. In this example, the user had provided the true latitude and longitude values at startup so the app was able to calculate and display the true error. The column labels in left image are:þ- "#": data point numberþ- "Accuracy": accuracy radius estimated by Google's built-in getAccuracy() function2þ- "Error": true error (i.e. distance between GPS Lat Lng and user-provided true Lat Lng values)þ- "Time": timestamp of data pointþþþ## Notesþ1. You need to include a Google Maps API key in the google_maps_api.xml file in place of "YOUR_KEY_HERE" for this app to work.þ2. An explanation of the getAccuracy() function can be found here.þþ## Recent Updatesþ7MAR2020: Migrated android.support libraries to androidx libraries. The android.support libraries will no longer be updated by Google. This migration was accompanied by some minor GUI layout tweaks - none should be noticeable to user.
