A fork of audio-analyzer-for-android in Google code, with a lot of enhancement.
readme: Audio Spectrum Analyzer for Androidþ===================================þþ>  A fork of [Audio spectrum Analyzer for Android](https://code.google.com/p/audio-analyzer-for-android/) (See README.old for its original readme)þþ  This software shows the frequency components' magnitude distribution (called spectrum) of the sound heard by your cell phone. Can be used to help tuning musical instrument or tone in singing, (tentative) measure environmental noise and sound revent education or experiments.þþ  You can install this app through **Google Play Store**: [Audio Spectrum Analyzer](https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=github.bewantbe.audio_analyzer_for_android). Comments are welcome.þþ  This software, [Audio Spectrum Analyzer for Android](https://github.com/bewantbe/audio-analyzer-for-android), is released under the Apache License, Version 2.0.þþþFeaturesþ--------þþ* Show [spectrum](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frequency_spectrum) or [spectrogram](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spectrogram) in real-time, with decent axis labels.þ* Linear, Logarithm and (Musical) Note frequency axis support.þ* You can put a cursor in the plot, for measurement or as a marker.þ* Easy gestures to fine exam the spectrum: i.e. pinch for scaling and swipe for  view move.þ* Show peak frequency in a moderate accuracy (FFT + interpolation).þ* Show dB or [A-weighting dB (dBA)](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A-weighting), although not suitable for serious application.þ* Possible to take averages of several spectrum then plot, make the spectrum smoother.þ* You may record the sound (while analyzing!) to a WAV file (PCM format). Then you can deal with it with your favorite tool.þ* Support all recorder sources except those need root privilege (see list in Android reference: [MediaRecorder.AudioSource](http://developer.android.com/reference/android/media/MediaRecorder.AudioSource.html))þ* Support all possible sampling rates that your phone is capable. e.g. useful to find out the native (or best) sampling format for you phone.þþþInstallation Requirementsþ-------------------------þþ* Android version (API level)þ  - \>= Android 2.2 (API level 8), up-to app version v1.6.8. þ  - \>= Android 2.3 (API level 9), master branch, up-to year 2017.þ  - \>= Android 4.0 (API level 14), since year 2018.þ  - These minimum version requirement is due to the "targetSdkVersion" and corresponding supported version range for library "com.android.support:support-v4".þþPermissions:þ* Microphone, of course.þ* External storage (e.g MicroSD card), if you want to record the sound.þþþDevelopmentþ-----------þþ`git clone` then open it use Android Studio. Install the SDK platform if requested (e.g. rev 116 needs API level 20), or tune the `compileSdkVersion` to the value that fits your needs.þþ([Notes on project import for old revision (rev <= 115)](doc/Notes-on-project-import-for-old-revision.txt))þþ### Code structureþþThe whole program structure is roughly follows the MVC model: þþ_AnalyzerActivity.java_ is the controler, as the main activity, it receives user inputs and system events, then sent corresponding commands to views or sampling and analyzing procedures.þþ_AnalyzerViews.java_ is the view in MVC. It is used to manage (initialization, display, refresh) UI texts, buttons, dialogs and graphics.þ_AnalyzerGraphic.java_ is a main sub-view which manage display of spectrum(_SpectrumPlot.java_) and spectrogram(_SpectrogramPlot.java_).þþ_SamplingLoop.java_ is more or less the "model" part. It performs the sampling and FFT analysis, and inform the graphics update.þþþ#### Processing of audio samplesþThe data process loop is located in `run()` in _SamplingLoop.java_ (after commit c9e430b (Feb 06, 2017), but basicly this process didn't change since the initial commit), as well as the trigger of graphics refresh.þþIn every loop of `while (isRunning)`, it reads a chunk of audio samples byþþ    record.read(audioSamples, 0, readChunkSize);þþ, then "stream" it to `STFT.java` byþþ    stft.feedData(audioSamples, numOfReadShort);þþwhich calculates RMS and FFT whenever enough data is collected. The view is then informed throughþþ    activity.analyzerViews.update(spectrumDBcopy);þþwhich ultimately calls `invalidate()` of the graphic view to request an update, then the `AnalyzerGraphic.onDraw(Canvas c)` will be called automatically.þþThanksþ------þþThe code [Audio spectrum Analyzer for Android](https://code.google.com/p/audio-analyzer-for-android/) gives me a good starting point, for learning Java and write this software (that I desired long ago).

readme: This project was bootstrapped with [Create React Native App](https://github.com/react-community/create-react-native-app).þþBelow you'll find information about performing common tasks. The most recent version of this guide is available [here](https://github.com/react-community/create-react-native-app/blob/master/react-native-scripts/template/README.md).þþ## Table of Contentsþþ* [Updating to New Releases](#updating-to-new-releases)þ* [Available Scripts](#available-scripts)þ  * [npm start](#npm-start)þ  * [npm test](#npm-test)þ  * [npm run ios](#npm-run-ios)þ  * [npm run android](#npm-run-android)þ  * [npm run eject](#npm-run-eject)þ* [Writing and Running Tests](#writing-and-running-tests)þ* [Environment Variables](#environment-variables)þ  * [Configuring Packager IP Address](#configuring-packager-ip-address)þ* [Customizing App Display Name and Icon](#customizing-app-display-name-and-icon)þ* [Sharing and Deployment](#sharing-and-deployment)þ  * [Publishing to Expo's React Native Community](#publishing-to-expos-react-native-community)þ  * [Building an Expo "standalone" app](#building-an-expo-standalone-app)þ  * [Ejecting from Create React Native App](#ejecting-from-create-react-native-app)þ    * [Build Dependencies (Xcode & Android Studio)](#build-dependencies-xcode-android-studio)þ    * [Should I Use ExpoKit?](#should-i-use-expokit)þ* [Troubleshooting](#troubleshooting)þ  * [Networking](#networking)þ  * [iOS Simulator won't open](#ios-simulator-wont-open)þ  * [QR Code does not scan](#qr-code-does-not-scan)þþ## Updating to New ReleasesþþYou should only need to update the global installation of `create-react-native-app` very rarely, ideally never.þþUpdating the `react-native-scripts` dependency of your app should be as simple as bumping the version number in `package.json` and reinstalling your project's dependencies.þþUpgrading to a new version of React Native requires updating the `react-native`, `react`, and `expo` package versions, and setting the correct `sdkVersion` in `app.json`. See the [versioning guide](https://github.com/react-community/create-react-native-app/blob/master/VERSIONS.md) for up-to-date information about package version compatibility.þþ## Available ScriptsþþIf Yarn was installed when the project was initialized, then dependencies will have been installed via Yarn, and you should probably use it to run these commands as well. Unlike dependency installation, command running syntax is identical for Yarn and NPM at the time of this writing.þþ### `npm start`þþRuns your app in development mode.þþOpen it in the [Expo app](https://expo.io) on your phone to view it. It will reload if you save edits to your files, and you will see build errors and logs in the terminal.þþSometimes you may need to reset or clear the React Native packager's cache. To do so, you can pass the `--reset-cache` flag to the start script:þþ```þnpm start --reset-cacheþ# orþyarn start --reset-cacheþ```þþ#### `npm test`þþRuns the [jest](https://github.com/facebook/jest) test runner on your tests.þþ#### `npm run ios`þþLike `npm start`, but also attempts to open your app in the iOS Simulator if you're on a Mac and have it installed.þþ#### `npm run android`þþLike `npm start`, but also attempts to open your app on a connected Android device or emulator. Requires an installation of Android build tools (see [React Native docs](https://facebook.github.io/react-native/docs/getting-started.html) for detailed setup). We also recommend installing Genymotion as your Android emulator. Once you've finished setting up the native build environment, there are two options for making the right copy of `adb` available to Create React Native App:þþ##### Using Android Studio's `adb`þþ1. Make sure that you can run adb from your terminal.þ2. Open Genymotion and navigate to `Settings -> ADB`. Select “Use custom Android SDK tools” and update with your [Android SDK directory](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/25176594/android-sdk-location).þþ##### Using Genymotion's `adb`þþ1. Find Genymotion’s copy of adb. On macOS for example, this is normally `/Applications/Genymotion.app/Contents/MacOS/tools/`.þ2. Add the Genymotion tools directory to your path (instructions for [Mac](http://osxdaily.com/2014/08/14/add-new-path-to-path-command-line/), [Linux](http://www.computerhope.com/issues/ch001647.htm), and [Windows](https://www.howtogeek.com/118594/how-to-edit-your-system-path-for-easy-command-line-access/)).þ3. Make sure that you can run adb from your terminal.þþ#### `npm run eject`þþThis will start the process of "ejecting" from Create React Native App's build scripts. You'll be asked a couple of questions about how you'd like to build your project.þþ**Warning:** Running eject is a permanent action (aside from whatever version control system you use). An ejected app will require you to have an [Xcode and/or Android Studio environment](https://facebook.github.io/react-native/docs/getting-started.html) set up.þþ## Customizing App Display Name and IconþþYou can edit `app.json` to include [configuration keys](https://docs.expo.io/versions/latest/guides/configuration.html) under the `expo` key.þþTo change your app's display name, set the `expo.name` key in `app.json` to an appropriate string.þþTo set an app icon, set the `expo.icon` key in `app.json` to be either a local path or a URL. It's recommended that you use a 512x512 png file with transparency.þþ## Writing and Running TestsþþThis project is set up to use [jest](https://facebook.github.io/jest/) for tests. You can configure whatever testing strategy you like, but jest works out of the box. Create test files in directories called `__tests__` or with the `.test` extension to have the files loaded by jest. See the [the template project](https://github.com/react-community/create-react-native-app/blob/master/react-native-scripts/template/App.test.js) for an example test. The [jest documentation](https://facebook.github.io/jest/docs/en/getting-started.html) is also a wonderful resource, as is the [React Native testing tutorial](https://facebook.github.io/jest/docs/en/tutorial-react-native.html).þþ## Environment VariablesþþYou can configure some of Create React Native App's behavior using environment variables.þþ### Configuring Packager IP AddressþþWhen starting your project, you'll see something like this for your project URL:þþ```þexp://192.168.0.2:19000þ```þþThe "manifest" at that URL tells the Expo app how to retrieve and load your app's JavaScript bundle, so even if you load it in the app via a URL like `exp://localhost:19000`, the Expo client app will still try to retrieve your app at the IP address that the start script provides.þþIn some cases, this is less than ideal. This might be the case if you need to run your project inside of a virtual machine and you have to access the packager via a different IP address than the one which prints by default. In order to override the IP address or hostname that is detected by Create React Native App, you can specify your own hostname via the `REACT_NATIVE_PACKAGER_HOSTNAME` environment variable:þþMac and Linux:þþ```þREACT_NATIVE_PACKAGER_HOSTNAME='my-custom-ip-address-or-hostname' npm startþ```þþWindows:þ```þset REACT_NATIVE_PACKAGER_HOSTNAME='my-custom-ip-address-or-hostname'þnpm startþ```þþThe above example would cause the development server to listen on `exp://my-custom-ip-address-or-hostname:19000`.þþ## Sharing and DeploymentþþCreate React Native App does a lot of work to make app setup and development simple and straightforward, but it's very difficult to do the same for deploying to Apple's App Store or Google's Play Store without relying on a hosted service.þþ### Publishing to Expo's React Native CommunityþþExpo provides free hosting for the JS-only apps created by CRNA, allowing you to share your app through the Expo client app. This requires registration for an Expo account.þþInstall the `exp` command-line tool, and run the publish command:þþ```þ$ npm i -g expþ$ exp publishþ```þþ### Building an Expo "standalone" appþþYou can also use a service like [Expo's standalone builds](https://docs.expo.io/versions/latest/guides/building-standalone-apps.html) if you want to get an IPA/APK for distribution without having to build the native code yourself.þþ### Ejecting from Create React Native AppþþIf you want to build and deploy your app yourself, you'll need to eject from CRNA and use Xcode and Android Studio.þþThis is usually as simple as running `npm run eject` in your project, which will walk you through the process. Make sure to install `react-native-cli` and follow the [native code getting started guide for React Native](https://facebook.github.io/react-native/docs/getting-started.html).þþ#### Should I Use ExpoKit?þþIf you have made use of Expo APIs while working on your project, then those API calls will stop working if you eject to a regular React Native project. If you want to continue using those APIs, you can eject to "React Native + ExpoKit" which will still allow you to build your own native code and continue using the Expo APIs. See the [ejecting guide](https://github.com/react-community/create-react-native-app/blob/master/EJECTING.md) for more details about this option.þþ## Troubleshootingþþ### NetworkingþþIf you're unable to load your app on your phone due to a network timeout or a refused connection, a good first step is to verify that your phone and computer are on the same network and that they can reach each other. Create React Native App needs access to ports 19000 and 19001 so ensure that your network and firewall settings allow access from your device to your computer on both of these ports.þþTry opening a web browser on your phone and opening the URL that the packager script prints, replacing `exp://` with `http://`. So, for example, if underneath the QR code in your terminal you see:þþ```þexp://192.168.0.1:19000þ```þþTry opening Safari or Chrome on your phone and loadingþþ```þhttp://192.168.0.1:19000þ```þþandþþ```þhttp://192.168.0.1:19001þ```þþIf this works, but you're still unable to load your app by scanning the QR code, please open an issue on the [Create React Native App repository](https://github.com/react-community/create-react-native-app) with details about these steps and any other error messages you may have received.þþIf you're not able to load the `http` URL in your phone's web browser, try using the tethering/mobile hotspot feature on your phone (beware of data usage, though), connecting your computer to that WiFi network, and restarting the packager. If you are using a VPN you may need to disable it.þþ### iOS Simulator won't openþþIf you're on a Mac, there are a few errors that users sometimes see when attempting to `npm run ios`:þþ* "non-zero exit code: 107"þ* "You may need to install Xcode" but it is already installedþ* and othersþþThere are a few steps you may want to take to troubleshoot these kinds of errors:þþ1. Make sure Xcode is installed and open it to accept the license agreement if it prompts you. You can install it from the Mac App Store.þ2. Open Xcode's Preferences, the Locations tab, and make sure that the `Command Line Tools` menu option is set to something. Sometimes when the CLI tools are first installed by Homebrew this option is left blank, which can prevent Apple utilities from finding the simulator. Make sure to re-run `npm/yarn run ios` after doing so.þ3. If that doesn't work, open the Simulator, and under the app menu select `Reset Contents and Settings...`. After that has finished, quit the Simulator, and re-run `npm/yarn run ios`.þþ### QR Code does not scanþþIf you're not able to scan the QR code, make sure your phone's camera is focusing correctly, and also make sure that the contrast on the two colors in your terminal is high enough. For example, WebStorm's default themes may [not have enough contrast](https://github.com/react-community/create-react-native-app/issues/49) for terminal QR codes to be scannable with the system barcode scanners that the Expo app uses.þþIf this causes problems for you, you may want to try changing your terminal's color theme to have more contrast, or running Create React Native App from a different terminal. You can also manually enter the URL printed by the packager script in the Expo app's search bar to load it manually.

[Node.js][]: We use Node to run a development web server and build the project.þ   Depending on your system, you can install Node either from source or as a pre-packaged bundle.þ2. [Yarn][]: We use Yarn to manage Node dependencies.þ   Depending on your system, you can install Yarn either from source or as a pre-packaged bundle.þþAfter installing Node, you should be able to run the following command to install development tools.þYou will only need to run this command when dependencies change in [package.json](package.json).þþ    yarn installþþWe use yarn scripts and [Webpack][] as our build system.þþþRun the following commands in two separate terminals to create a blissful development experience where your browserþauto-refreshes when files change on your hard drive.þþ    ./gradlewþ    yarn startþþ[Yarn][] is also used to manage CSS and JavaScript dependencies used in this application. You can upgrade dependencies byþspecifying a newer version in [package.json](package.json). You can also run `yarn update` and `yarn install` to manage dependencies.þAdd the `help` flag on any command to see how you can use it. For example, `yarn help update`.þþThe `yarn run` command will list all of the scripts available to run for this project.þþ### Managing dependenciesþþFor example, to add [Leaflet][] library as a runtime dependency of your application, you would run following command:þþ    yarn add --exact leafletþþTo benefit from TypeScript type definitions from [DefinitelyTyped][] repository in development, you would run following command:þþ    yarn add --dev --exact @types/leafletþþThen you would import the JS and CSS files specified in library's installation instructions so that [Webpack][] knows about them:þþEdit [src/main/webapp/app/vendor.ts](src/main/webapp/app/vendor.ts) file:þ~~~þimport 'leaflet/dist/leaflet.js';þ~~~þþEdit [src/main/webapp/content/css/vendor.css](src/main/webapp/content/css/vendor.css) file:þ~~~þ@import '~leaflet/dist/leaflet.css';þ~~~þþNote: there are still few other things remaining to do for Leaflet that we won't detail here.þþFor further instructions on how to develop with JHipster, have a look at [Using JHipster in development][].þþ### Using angular-cliþþYou can also use [Angular CLI][] to generate some custom client code.þþFor example, the following command:þþ    ng generate component my-componentþþwill generate few files:þþ    create src/main/webapp/app/my-component/my-component.component.htmlþ    create src/main/webapp/app/my-component/my-component.component.tsþ    update src/main/webapp/app/app.module.tsþþ## Building for productionþþTo optimize the eshop application for production, run:þþ    ./gradlew -Pprod clean bootRepackageþþThis will concatenate and minify the client CSS and JavaScript files. It will also modify `index.html` so it references these new files.þTo ensure everything worked, run:þþ    java -jar build/libs/*.warþþThen navigate to [http://localhost:8080](http://localhost:8080) in your browser.þþRefer to [Using JHipster in production][] for more details.þþ## TestingþþTo launch your application's tests, run:þþ    ./gradlew testþþ### Client testsþþUnit tests are run by [Karma][] and written with [Jasmine][]. They're located in [src/test/javascript/](src/test/javascript/) and can be run with:þþ    yarn testþþUI end-to-end tests are powered by [Protractor][], which is built on top of WebDriverJS. They're located in [src/test/javascript/e2e](src/test/javascript/e2e)þand can be run by starting Spring Boot in one terminal (`./gradlew bootRun`) and running the tests (`yarn run e2e`) in a second one.þ### Other testsþþPerformance tests are run by [Gatling][] and written in Scala. They're located in [src/test/gatling](src/test/gatling) and can be run with:þþ    ./gradlew gatlingRunþþFor more information, refer to the [Running tests page][].þþ## Using Docker to simplify development (optional)þþYou can use Docker to improve your JHipster development experience. A number of docker-compose configuration are available in the [src/main/docker](src/main/docker) folder to launch required third party services.þFor example, to start a postgresql database in a docker container, run:þþ    docker-compose -f src/main/docker/postgresql.yml up -dþþTo stop it and remove the container, run:þþ    docker-compose -f src/main/docker/postgresql.yml downþþYou can also fully dockerize your application and all the services that it depends on.þTo achieve this, first build a docker image of your app by running:þþ    ./gradlew bootRepackage -Pprod buildDockerþþThen run:þþ    docker-compose -f src/main/docker/app.yml up -dþþFor more information refer to [Using Docker and Docker-Compose][], this page also contains information on the docker-compose sub-generator (`yo jhipster:docker-compose`), which is able to generate docker configurations for one or several JHipster applications.þþ## Continuous Integration (optional)þþTo configure CI for your project, run the ci-cd sub-generator (`yo jhipster:ci-cd`), this will let you generate configuration files for a number of Continuous Integration systems. Consult the [Setting up Continuous Integration][] page for more information.þþ[JHipster Homepage and latest documentation]: https://jhipster.github.ioþ[JHipster 4.3.0 archive]: https://jhipster.github.io/documentation-archive/v4.3.0þþ[Using JHipster in development]: https://jhipster.github.io/documentation-archive/v4.3.0/development/þ[Using Docker and Docker-Compose]: https://jhipster.github.io/documentation-archive/v4.3.0/docker-composeþ[Using JHipster in production]: https://jhipster.github.io/documentation-archive/v4.3.0/production/þ[Running tests page]: https://jhipster.github.io/documentation-archive/v4.3.0/running-tests/þ[Setting up Continuous Integration]: https://jhipster.github.io/documentation-archive/v4.3.0/setting-up-ci/þþ[Gatling]: http://gatling.io/þ[Node.js]: https://nodejs.org/þ[Yarn]: https://yarnpkg.org/þ[Webpack]: https://webpack.github.io/þ[Angular CLI]: https://cli.angular.io/þ[BrowserSync]: http://www.browsersync.io/þ[Karma]: http://karma-runner.github.io/þ[Jasmine]: http://jasmine.github.io/2.0/introduction.htmlþ[Protractor]: https://angular.github.io/protractor/þ[Leaflet]: http://leafletjs.com/þ[DefinitelyTyped]: http://definitelytyped.org/

description: Implementation of Live Video Streaming through VLC plugin in CCN(Content Centric Networking).
readme: # CCN (CONTENT CENTRIC NETWORKING)þContent-Centric Networking (CCN) is a new networking architecture proposed forþthe future Internet. It has the potential to provide better results in terms of band-þwidth usage, scalability and security as compared to the current IP-based architec-þture. The main idea behind content based addressing is to address content insteadþof addressing hosts, thus separating content from its location. As content traversesþthe network, routers and hosts either cache the location(s) where they can find aþcopy of the content or cache an actual copy of the content, enabling future requestsþfor that content to be delivered by any node that currently holds a copy of theþcontent. This enables the use of multiple sources and multiple destinations nativelyþby the network (i.e., creating a multi-path topology to access the content).þþCCN Packets:þThere are two types of CCN packet :-þ1. Interest Packet : Similar to \http get".þ2. Data Packet : Similar to \http response".þBoth are encoded in an efficient binary XML.þþþþ# WORKINGþþCCN is designed to be implemented on top of or alongside TCP/IP, so that it willþwork with the current networks. Content is made available by repositories announc-þing the names of content they serve to adjacent routers, who in turn distribute thisþinformation into the network via the Interior Gateway Protocol (IGP).þThe content matches the request if the ContentName in the interest is a prefixþto the ContentName in the ContentStore. If the content is not available, then theþrouter checks if it matches its list of previously sent, unanswered interests storedþin a Pending Interest Table (PIT) to ensure that a duplicate interest is notþforwarded. If the request is in the PIT, then the router adds this new interest toþthe existing entry in the PIT. If no matches are found in the ContentStore or PIT,þthen the router checks its CCN Forwarding Information Base (FIB) to see if itþknows any other node that might have the content available (longest match lookupþis used in cases of multiple matching entries), if so it forwards the interest to themþand adds an entry to the PIT with this information. If the router does not haveþa copy of the content and does not know where to find one, then the interest isþsimply discarded; the requesting application is itself responsible for re-expressingþinterest if it is not satisfied (as well as dealing with cases where packets are lost inþthe network).þþWhen the name of the content is matched the node sends the content as anþauthenticated data packet back on the interface that the interest arrived on. Nodesþreceiving the data packet should check if it has any entries in its PIT matching theþcontent, if so, then the data packet should also be forwarded to the interface thatþthis interest arrived on. The ContentStore stores a copy of the content if desired.þWhen all of the content has been received, the PIT entry is removed.þContent is transferred backward across the chain of nodes that the interest packetþtraversed, with each CCN capable node storing either a copy of the content or theþlocation it came from and removing PIT entries until the content is delivered to theþapplication who initiated the request for this content. Any future request for thisþcontent can then be served by any of the nodes who have cached a copy in theirþContentStore, making the network an efficient content delivery network.þThe most suitable cache replacement policies in a content caching network areþLeast Recently Used (LRU) and Least Frequently Used (LFU).þþþþ# Implementation procedure for Live Video Streaming through VLC plugin in CCN ----->þþ1) Install following packages on each node:þsudo apt-get updateþsudo apt-get install libssl-dev libexpat1-dev libpcap-dev libxml2-utils vlcþopenjdk-7-jdk ant git-core gcc athena-jot python-dev make libvlc-dev libvlccore-devþlibvlc-devþþ2) Install CCNx on each node:þcdþgit clone https://github.com/manveers96/CCN-Content-Centric-Networking-þcd ccnxþ./configureþmakeþsudo make installþþ3) Start CCNx daemon on each node:þccndstartþþ4) Make a directory that will act as repository , providing persistent storage ofþCCNx content backed by a file system:þmkdir ~/ccnDirþexport CCNR_DIRECTORY = ~/ccnDirþþ5) Start ccnr daemon:þccnr &þþ6) Add all interfaces to CCNx:þccndc add ccnx:/ udp ip_of_system_connectedþccndc add ccnx:/ udp ip_of_h1þccndc add ccnx:/ udp ip_of_r2þccndc add ccnx:/ udp ip_of_r4þþ7) Configure vlc:þsudo sed -i 's/geteuid/getppid/' /usr/bin/vlcþþ8) Install vlc plugin:þcd ~/ccnx/apps/vlcþmake -f Makefile.Linuxþsudo make installþþ9) Publish content, here h1 acts as publisher, so in h1:þccnputfile ccnx:/h1/filename srcFilePathþþ10) Now to access it in subscriber:þccngetfile ccnx:/h1/filename destFilePathþþ11)For video streaming:þvlc ccnx:///ccnx_uriþþThe live streaming of video will start working after the above steps.

readme:
# tsdb-csfþþThis projects is forked from [metrics-opentsdb](https://github.com/sps/metrics-opentsdb) with thanks to [Sean Scanlon](mailto:sean.scanlon@gmail.com) for initiating it.þþCSF is a java library to provide an agent that combines implementations of the following:þ* An asynchronous HTTP client for sending metrics to an [OpenTSDB](http://opentsdb.net) endpoint.þ* Embedded CodaHale/DropWizard [Metrics](http://dropwizard.io/) for collecting and accumulating metrics with OpenTSDB friendly Metrics extensions to assist in generating metric name tagging by converting the native flat metric formats to OpenTSDBs tag based format.þ* A high speed persistence mechanism to store metrics to disk when the agent can't reach the OpenTSDB endpoint and flush the store when connectivity resumes.þ* JMX exposed metric coverage of the agent's status and activity.þ þþ### More Detail on Featuresþ* High performance file system metric storage and retrieval store to save collected metrics when the OpenTSDB endpoint is inaccessible.þ* Background configurable OpenTSDB non-intrusive connectivity monitor. Issues JMX notifications on initial connect, disconnect and reconnect events.þ* Automatic (configurable override) **host** and **app** tag values discovery to identify the provenance of all submitted metrics. If tags are provided, automatic tags are ignored to support monitoring of a remote app or serviceþ* Bad metric name detection and suppression.þ* Extensive JMX instrumentation.þ* Automatically generated hearbeat metric generation. Optional app start and clean shutdown OpenTSDB annotation generation and submission.þ* Fast and efficient GZIP enabled HTTP metric submission using Netty based [AsyncHttpClient](https://github.com/AsyncHttpClient/async-http-client). GZIP automatically disengaged if OpenTSDB does not support GZIP. (OpenTSDB <= 2.1).þ* Tested with [Bosun](http://bosun.org).þ* See [Road Map](https://github.com/nickman/tsdb-csf/wiki/RoadMap).þþ### Getting Started (Build)þ- Clone the project (on most planets, this means ```git clone https://github.com/nickman/tsdb-csf.git```)þ- Navigate to the clone's directoryþ- Build with *maven3*: ```mvn clean install```þ þPublic maven repo pending.þþ### Getting Started (Code)þþ*Note:* References herein to "Metrics" (with the upper case M, yeah ?) refer to CodaHale/DropWizard [Metrics](http://dropwizard.io/), while references to "metrics" refer to several things and must be considered in context.þþHere's a step-by-step of the current version of [KitchenSink](https://github.com/nickman/tsdb-csf/blob/master/csf-core/src/test/java/com/heliosapm/opentsdb/client/KitchenSink.java) which contrives one of each of the main metric types in CodaHale's Metrics.þþ##### Abbreviated java **main**:þ```javaþ public static void main(String[] args) {þ KitchenSink ks = new KitchenSink();þ System.out.println("KitchenSink Started");þ }þ```þþ##### Declare Metrics Using OpenTSDB Style Namespaces:þHere we create a new MetricRegistry and define a set of metrics to register in it.þNothing new to Metrics users here, except the OpenTSDB tag friendly names. (More on this below)þ```javaþ // Create a new MetricRegistryþ final MetricRegistry registry = new MetricRegistry();þ // Create a new Gauge Metricþ final Gauge cacheSizeGauge = new Gauge() {þ @Overrideþ public Long getValue() { þ final Random random = new Random(System.currentTimeMillis());þ return new Long(Math.abs(random.nextInt(1000)));þ }þ };þ // Create a new Counter Metricþ final Counter evictions = registry.counter(name(getClass().getSimpleName(), "evictions", "cmtype=Counter", "op=cache-evictions", "service=cacheservice"));þ // Create a new Histogram Metricþ final Histogram resultCounts = registry.histogram(name(getClass().getSimpleName(), "resultCounts", "cmtype=Histogram", "op=cache-lookup", "service=cacheservice"));þ // Create a new Meter Metricþ final Meter lookupRequests = registry.meter(name(getClass().getSimpleName(), "lookupRequests", "cmtype=Meter", "op=cache-lookup", "service=cacheservice"));þ // Create a new Timer Metricþ final Timer timer = registry.timer(name(getClass().getSimpleName(), "evictelapsed", "cmtype=Timer", "op=cache-evictions", "service=cacheservice"));þ```þA traditional Metrics metric name for, say the *cacheSizeGauge* gauge, would look something like this:þþ
KitchenSink.cacheservice.cache-size
þþOpenTSDB metrics, however, are *mapped*, or *tagged* formatted metrics. A fully qualified metric name consists of a **metric name** which broadly describes what the value is, and one or more tags which are name/value pairs that provide specificity as to the provenance of the metric value. Here's a classic and simple example (slightly modified from a Bosun created metric):þþ
cpu.percpu:host=appserver9,type=idle,cpu=7
þþþFrom this we divine:þ* The *metric name* is **cpu.percpu** which means we're looking at CPU utilization on a *per cpu* basis (as opposed to aggregated CPU stats). þ* The host that this CPU resides on is **appserver9**.þ* Of all the CPUs on the host **appserver9**, this metric is referring CPU **#7**.þþIf you're not familiar with this, I would shoot over to [OpenTSDB](http://opentsdb.net) and read their documentation on [Understanding Metrics and Time Series](http://opentsdb.net/docs/build/html/user_guide/query/timeseries.html)þþOne of the big motivations for starting this project was to provide a means of using Metrics while retaining very granular control of how OpenTSDB metric names are managed. Sensibly defined and implemented OpenTSDB metric names, especially tags, are of paramount importance as concerns the functionality and performance of OpenTSDB. 'nuff said ?þþBack at the KitchenSink, we're using the MetricRegistry's static *name* method to generate what ends up being a fairly detailed (albeit contrived) OpenTSDB metric name (going forward, the OMN). Once again, here's the counter Metric creation:þþ```javaþ // Create a new Counter Metricþ final Counter evictions = þ registry.counter(name(getClass().getSimpleName(), þ "evictions", þ "op=cache-evictions", þ "service=cacheservice"));þ```þþ* The simple class name ("KitchenSink") becomes the first part of the OMN's *metric* portion. This is not strictly a popular naming convention, but this is contrived.þ* The string "evictions" is not a tag by virtue of it's lack of a "=" symbol. Therefore, it is appended to the end of the existing OMN metric, bringing us to a metric of ```KitchenSink.evictions```. þ* The remaining strings to be appended are tags (yah, the '=') so they are appended as such.þþThe basis for the OMN is now ```KitchenSink.evictions:op=cache-evictions,service=cacheservice```, but we're not done yet. There's 2 more additions:þþ1. When the [OpenTsdbReporter](https://github.com/nickman/tsdb-csf/blob/master/csf-core/src/main/java/com/heliosapm/opentsdb/client/opentsdb/OpenTsdbReporter.java) kicks in, as most Metric Reporters do, all Metrics it reports for are decorated with some additional data indicating the meaning of the data. In some cases, there are more than one OMNs generated for each Metric. (Consider Timer which generates 15 metrics). In the case of Counter, there's a one-to-one, but the standard operating procedure for Metric reporters is to append the suffix **count** to indicate that the supplied value is in fact a count of something. The OpenTsdbReporter appends these informational suffixes to the end of the OMN metric name.lþ2. tsdb-csf encourages each OMN to be tagged with a **host** and an **app** so that the source of the metrics is clear. There are several options as to how the values for these tags can be arrived at, but the defaults are supplied by a class called [AgentName](https://github.com/nickman/tsdb-csf/blob/master/csf-core/src/main/java/com/heliosapm/opentsdb/client/name/AgentName.java) which does a pretty decent job by itself, IMHO.þ þAfter these two additions, the OMN used to report the Counter metric will be: ```KitchenSink.evictions.count:app=KitchenSink,host=hserval,op=cache-evictions,service=cacheservice```þþSee [AllKitchenSinkMetrics](https://github.com/nickman/tsdb-csf/wiki/AllKitchenSinkMetrics) for a list of all the OMNs generated by KitchenSink.þþFor our efforts, here's how OpenTSDB sees it:þþ![](https://github.com/nickman/tsdb-csf/wiki/img/Selection_001.png)þþþþþ### LicensingþTSDB-CSF retains the original license of [metrics-opentsdb](https://github.com/sps/metrics-opentsdb) which is [Apache 2.0](https://github.com/sps/metrics-opentsdb/blob/master/LICENSE.txt).þ þ .... and there are a handful of source files that have the wrong header. I will fix them....
